<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-89 2337EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-FosterHomeFire     08-31 0562</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Foster Home Fire,0580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Children Die in Early Morning Fire at Foster Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A predawn arson fire in a foster home killed
four children and injured 12 other people, with two adults and four
children hospitalized in critical condition, fire officials said.
   The fire was the work of an arsonist, said fire Lt. Jack
Christmas, who added that smoke detectors were found in the house
but nothing indicated they had been installed. He would not
elaborate.
   Neighbors said they woke up shortly before 3 a.m. smelling smoke
and hearing the cries of children. ``I heard the kids and they were
screaming, `Help me! Help me!' It was horrible,'' said Gloria Page,
who lives next door.
   When firefighters arrived at the three-story, stone-and-frame
house, they found heavy fire in the first floor and people trapped
upstairs.
   Neighbor Frank Hart said he woke up hearing a car in the street
honking its horn. ``Then I looked out the window and I saw all this
fire raging in the front of the house,'' he said.
   Hart said he ran behind the house and found three or four
children who had jumped from second- and third-story windows. He
said he looked up and saw ``five or six more'' standing at the
windows.
   ``They were crying and shaking and screaming,'' he said.
   Hart said he tried to build a platform out of wood so the
children could have a shorter distance to jump. ``They wouldn't jump
on it, so I told them to jump and I'd catch them. So they jumped and
I tried to catch them or break their fall,'' Hart said.
   The fire was under control by 3:20 a.m., firefighters said.
   Seventeen people lived in the house, firefighters said. The
children who died were found on the second floor.
   Police identified the dead children as Keith Moye, 7, and his
brother, Preston Moye, 5; Anwar Hartwell, 9, and Robert Lavenhouse,
15.
   The house belonged to Hubert and Rose Artis, a couple who took in
foster children and had lived on tree-lined Park Avenue for about 13
years.
   Mrs. Artis, 65, was in critical condition at Albert Einstein
Medical Center with multiple fractures and smoke inhalation. Also in
critical condition at Einstein were Peggy Seymour, 20, Victoria
Palmer, 15, and Christine Knight, 3, all suffering burns and smoke
inhalation.
   Pauline Palmer, 17, was in critical condition at St. Agnes
Medical Center with burns, and Antonio Mills, 12, was in critical
condition at St. Christopher's Hospital for Children.
   In addition, Michael Bullock, 28, was in stable condition at
Temple University Hospital with a fractured wrist and smoke
inhalation. Three others, Hubert Artis, 65; Michelle Rogers, 20; and
Latasha Rodgers, 18, were being evaluated at Temple for burns and
smoke inhalation.
   Jarvis Davis, 2, was treated at Temple for smoke inhalation.
   Neighbor Sylvia Young described the Artises as a good-hearted
couple who took in so many children because they had plenty of room
in their spacious house.
   The Artises had been foster parents since 1972, according to
Richard Olanoff of the city's Department of Human Services.
   State law prohibits more than six children in a foster home, but
police counted 11 children living among the 17 residents of the
house when the fire broke out.
   Olanoff said the department granted the Artises a waiver to care
for eight children about a year ago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
