<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--BostonHarbor     08-31 0169</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Boston Harbor,0172</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study Shows Fish Defects Down but Pollution Still a Threat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A recent study of Boston Harbor found fewer fish
with bent fins, dwarfism or liver abnormalities associated with
pollution, but researchers say the inlet is far from environmentally
sound.
   ``We don't conclude from the study that in fact things are
getting better,'' said William E. Robinson, senior scientist at the
New England Aquarium's Edgerton Laboratory.
   Nearly 200 winter flounder caught one day in mid-May showed fewer
instances of cancerous lesions as well as other defects, compared to
studies in the early 1980s.
   However, Robinson said Wednesday, defects were markedly higher
than the numbers found in cleaner environments further out in the
sea. ``No changes have gone on in Boston Harbor yet,'' he said,
adding that partially treated sewage still is being dumped there.
   The state plans to spend $6.1 billion to clean up the pollution,
which then-candidate George Bush frequently cited in running against
Gov. Michael Dukakis in last year's presidential campaign.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
