<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-89 0007EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-People-Reagans     08-31 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Reagans,0217</SECOND>
<HEAD>Greet Soviet Children at Camp for Kids with Cancer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MALIBU, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Reagan and his wife,
Nancy, greeted four Soviet girls recovering from cancer during a
tour of a camp for children with the disease.
   The Reagans came to this seaside town outside Los Angeles on
Wednesday to visit Camp Ronald McDonald for Good Times. The girls,
whose cancer is in remission, are spending a week at the camp with
their doctors.
   Speaking through an interpreter, 13-year-old Angella Mihay said
she was impressed with the warmth and openness of the former first
couple.
   She joined Tanja Shmorgoner, 13, and 11-year-olds Alina Ivanova
and Nina Dgenda in serenading the Reagans in Russian.
   The Reagans ate macaroni and cheese with 100 children. Soviet
doctors Lev Durnov and Ilana Mikelova gave the couple hand-carved
wooden bowls and spoons, and children gave them pillows made of
quilt patches depicting camp life.
   ``The whole idea behind the camp is to give children with cancer
a camp experience like any other child,'' said McDonald's spokesman
Neil Cohen. ``There's swimming, frisbee, basketball, just like any
normal camp. The kids are encouraged to participate in all they
can.''
   ``We would like to organize a camp like this one, maybe near
Moscow,'' Mikelova said.
</TEXT>
