<FIRST>r a PM-Helmsley-Glance     08-31 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Helmsley-Glance,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Look at the Helmsley Empire</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Helmsley Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Real estate mogul Harry Helmsley and his wife, Leona, who was
convicted Wednesday of tax evasion, head a real estate and hotel
empire worth $5 billion and are personally worth an estimated $1
billion.
   Their Helmsley Enterprises is the holding company for the
Helmsley businesses which include the following:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>HELMSLEY-SPEAR INC.</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Annual revenues of $1.1 billion. Manages or owns 50,000
residential apartments and 50 million square feet of commercial
space in over 600 buildings nationwide, ranging from ordinary office
towers to middle-class residential projects. Prominent holdings
include the Empire State Building, the Flatiron Building, and One
Penn Plaza.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>HELMSLEY HOTELS INC.</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Operates six luxury hotels in New York City _ the Helmsley
Palace, the Carlton House, the Park Lane, the Helmsley Windsor, the
New York Helmsley and the Middletowne.
   The Cleveland-based chain, Harley Hotels Inc., named after Harry
and Leona, operates 17 budget hotels and motor inns in 10 states.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>DECO PURCHASING AND DISTRIBUTING CO.</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Purchases supplies for hotels. This company was operated by Leona
Helmsley's son, Jay Panzirer, who died in 1982. Panzirer, who was in
poor health, dropped his other hotel clients and re-established his
firm as a subsidiary of the Helmsley hotel empire.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>OWNERS MAINTENANCE</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Cleaning services company that holds contracts with many
buildings managed by Helmsley-Spear Inc.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>OTHERS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Other Helmsley companies provide insurance, purchasing and
advertising services to buildings that Helmsley owns or manages in
New York City and across the country.
</TEXT>
