<FIRST>r p PM-Abortion-Election     08-31 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion-Election,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Florida House Race Shows Pro-Life Movement Thriving, Group Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-abortion activists say the outcome of a
special Florida congressional election is a ``pivotal victory'' in
the wake of last month's Supreme Court ruling on abortion.
   A leader of the abortion rights movement, however, said Wednesday
that ethnic issues, not abortion, fueled state Sen. Ileana
Ros-Lehtinen's victory over Democrat Gerald Richman.
   Ms. Ros-Lehtinen, a Republican and the first Cuban-American
elected to Congress, defeated Richman on Tuesday for the seat left
vacant by the death of veteran Democratic Rep. Claude Pepper.
   ``Ileana could not have won the vote with just the Hispanic
vote,'' Sandra Faucher, director of the National Right to Life
Political Action Committee, told reporters. ``There is not a
majority of Hispanics in the district.
   ``There had to be other issues involved, and we feel that
definitely the abortion issue played a major factor in the race,''
she said. ``Ileana Ros-Lehtinen's win is a pivotal victory for the
pro-life movement.''
   The Supreme Court's 5-4 ruling July 3, which gave states greater
power to limit abortions, appeared on the court's docket as Webster
vs. Reproductive Health Services.
   Kate Michelman, executive director of the National Abortion
Rights Action League, said abortion ``was not the issue'' in the
Florida race.
   ``Nothing was an issue there that could supersede the ethnicity
issue,'' Ms. Michelman said. ``The fact is that no issue, even the
issue of choice, could overwhelm the ethnicity issue.''
   The district is about 40 percent Hispanic and unofficial returns
showed that predominantly Latin precincts had turnouts of more than
60 percent and gave Ms. Ros-Lehtinen majorities of 80 percent to 90
percent. She carried the entire district by a 53 percent to 47
percent margin.
   During the campaign, Ms. Ros-Lehtinen, 37, said she favored more
restrictions on abortion. Richman said he favored more choice.
However, with polls indicating most voters supported abortion
rights, the GOP candidate said abortion was more of a state
legislative issue than a congressional issue.
   Abortion rights leaders have contended that state legislative
victories in races in California, Indiana and South Carolina
indicated movement in their direction in the wake of the court
ruling.
   Ms. Faucher, however, said anti-abortion candidates have won in
races in Missouri, Alabama, Mississippi, Georgia and two Florida
legislative districts.
   Ms. Michelman denied that abortion was an important issue in
those races.
</TEXT>
