<FIRST>r w PM-US-Panama 320   08-31 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Panama, 320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Outlines Allegations Against Noriega</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Meeting scheduled for 3 p.m. EDT; Lead prospects uncertain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration, responding to a
challenge from Panama, is outlining to the Organization of American
States today its allegations that Gen. Manuel Noriega is engaged in
drug trafficking.
   Deputy Secretary of State Lawrence Eagleburger's presentation to
the 31-nation meeting requested by the United States is designed to
rally opposition to Noriega.
   So far, the OAS has taken a cautious approach.
   A bland statement issued at a foreign ministers meeting last week
expressed concern over the situation in Panama. It hardly matched
Eagleburger's rhetoric. The State Department official likened
Noriega to Adolf Hitler.
   While Foreign Minister Jorge Ritter walked out in protest,
Panamanian Ambassador Romulo Escobar Betancourt challenged
Eagleburger to document the drug allegations.
   The U.S. response was to request today's special session. William
Price, the acting permanent U.S. representative, said the United
States wanted to present ``a summary of the evidence and elaboration
of the United States position on the critical situation in Panama.''
   Two Florida grand juries have indicted Noriega on drug-smuggling
charges. U.S. officials hinted to reporters this week that there is
more evidence against him.
   Meanwhile, Noriega attorney Raymond Takiff of Miami demanded in a
letter to the OAS the right to cross-examine witnesses who appeared
before the organization.
   The letter asked for the ``opportunity to prove ... that the
indictments against Gen. Noriega are motivated politically
representing nothing more than `indictment diplomacy.'''
   Margaret Tutwiler, the State Department spokeswoman, confirmed
Wednesday that Eagleburger would focus on narcotics, but she
declined to offer any details.
   The term of Panama's provisional president, Manuel Solis Palma,
who was handpicked by Noriega, expires today. The Bush
administration and Panamanian opponents of the general are concerned
Noriega will name a puppet government and not hold free elections.
   The United States has tried unsuccessfully to oust Noriega from
power for 18 months.
</TEXT>
