<DOCNO> AP890831-0031 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-89 0342EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-AcidRain-Costs     08-31 0665</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Acid Rain-Costs,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Acid Rain Legislation Would Mean Higher Electric Costs: Industry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The utility industry says consumers in many
states should be prepared to pay as much as 10 percent more for
electricity if legislation to curb acid rain becomes law.
   The industry contends such legislation will cost more than $5.5
billion a year.
   Environmentalists and analysts at the Environmental Protection
Agency said the industry cost estimates provided Wednesday are too
high, but concede the emission curbs required to reduce acid rain
will be expensive.
   ``We're heartened that their numbers are coming out so close to
ours,'' said Nancy Kete, senior analyst in the EPA's office of air
radiation, when asked about the utility industry figures.
   She said the EPA has estimated industry costs would be about $4
billion a year when full compliance with the proposed acid rain
controls go into effect in 2000.
   The acid rain curbs are included in legislation before Congress
tightening federal air pollution laws. The Bush administration
proposal calls for cutting annual sulfur dioxide emissions _ the
chief source of acid rain _ by 10 million tons, mostly from
coal-burning power plants.
   The report by the Edison Electric Institute projects industry
costs as high as $120 billion over a 20-year period as a result of
having to install pollution control equipment and make other
adjustments to meet the emission curbs required by the legislation.
   Under some scenarios, costs could jump to as much as $7.1 billion
a year after 2000, said the industry report, acknowledging that was
a ``high-cost'' scenario that envisions failure of the
administration's proposed emissions credit trading scheme and broad
reliance by utilities on expensive ``scrubber'' technology instead
of fuel switching.
   The EPA's Kete said the agency continues to believe that
utilities will rely less than the industry believes on expensive
technology, opt more for switching from high-sulfur to low-sulfur
coal, and make the emissions credit system work.
   All of those factors would bring the industry estimates in line
with the EPA cost estimates, she said.
   According to the industry study, about 85 percent of the
increased costs of complying with the proposed emission curbs would
be borne by 15 states in the eastern half of the country where
utilities rely heavily on high-sulfur coal to meet their generating
needs.
   Utilities in Indiana, Missouri, Ohio, Pennsylvania, Tennessee and
Alabama together will face 44 percent of the annual costs
nationwide, the industry group said. The other states in the group
of 15 are Georgia, Illinois, Kentucky, West Virginia, Florida,
Michigan, New York, North Carolina and Wisconsin.
   The additional costs will result in rate increases of more than 5
percent in 19 states with the sharpest increases _ 10.8 percent to
17.3 percent _ coming in Indiana, Kentucky, Missouri, Ohio,
Tennessee and West Virginia, according to the industry study.
   The others states facing rates increases of more than 5 percent
were given as: Mississippi, Alabama, Georgia, South Carolina,
Virginia, Delaware, Maryland, Pennsylvania, New Hampshire, Illinois,
Wisconsin, all 6 percent to 9 percent increase; and South Dakota and
North Carolina, both 5.1 percent to 5.9 percent.
   Thirty-six of the 100 major utilities will have to impose rate
increases of at least 10 percent, the industry group maintained.
   Kete said the EPA has estimated average rate increases as a
result of the additional pollution control requirements at about 2
percent with the highest increases in the 5 percent to 6 percent
range.
   Dave Swanson, the industry group's senior vice president for
energy and environment, said costs could be reduced by as much as 30
percent if Congress eliminates provisions for emission caps for
individual utilities and changes other restrictions he said are
``unnecessarily expensive.''
   ``They're trying to trash the administration's acid rain
proposal,'' said Daniel Dudek, an economist for the Environmental
Defense Fund. He maintained the legislation already is flexible
enough to allow utilities ``to pick sensible alternatives'' that
meet the proposed emission standards and still hold down costs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
