<SECOND>PM-Barry-Drugs,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>DC Mayor Used Crack, Convicted Dealer Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A convicted drug dealer says he used crack
cocaine with Mayor Marion Barry at a Washington hotel and that the
two used cocaine in the Virgin Islands, according to published and
broadcast reports.
   Barry, who has vehemently denied ever using drugs, has twice
testified before a federal grand jury investigating allegations of
drug use.
   Charles Lewis, convicted in April on cocaine trafficking charges
in the Virgin Islands, told federal investigators he repeatedly used
drugs with Barry at Lewis' hotel room in December, The Washington
Post and WUSA-TV reported.
   Lewis also told prosecutors that Barry paid for the drugs,
delivering an envelope of $20 bills Dec. 19 to Lewis, WUSA reported
Wednesday.
   Barry has repeatedly denied seeing any drugs or drug use in
Lewis' hotel room.
   The Post reported today that witnesses corroborated statements by
Lewis, a former district employee, that he and Barry had used
cocaine in the Virgin Islands.
   Karen K. Johnson, another Barry associate, told prosecutors in
mid-1987 that she sold cocaine to Barry 20 to 30 times. Barry was
not charged with any crime.
   Lewis spent more than 80 hours talking with federal officials
earlier this month at the Quantico Marine Base in Quantico, Va.,
WUSA reported.
   Judy Smith, a spokeswoman for U.S. Attorney Jay B. Stephens,
refused to comment on the broadcast.
   Barry is vacationing at an undisclosed location.
</TEXT>
