<SECOND>PM-Lites,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROUNDUP, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   What better place than Roundup to begin the
Great Montana Centennial Cattle drive?
   More than 1,000 cattle from 20 Montana counties arrived at this
rural town Wednesday, along with 45 horses and 20 drovers, Alfred
Adolph said.
   Adolph is staging the Old West pageant that begins Monday as part
of the 100th anniversary celebration of Montana's statehood. The
cattle participating in the 50-mile drive to Billings will be marked
with a commemorative brand.
   Some Longhorns had a tough time disembarking from trucks,
catching their horns in unloading ramps or the horns of others.
   Three brand inspectors and some cowboys checked the cattles' ear
tags and papers to verify ownership and the eventual dispensation of
the animals.
   Beverly Meged, a rancher south of Roundup, said she brought her
cow ``just to be involved in the cattle drive.''
   Meged said her family will retrieve the cow at the end of the
drive, butcher it themselves and keep its hide with a special as a
reminder of the drive.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Owners of a casino couldn't make a go of it
with a 1950s theme, but they hope to recoup some of their losses by
selling off the old-fashioned jukeboxes, neon signs and movie
posters that decorated the place.
   Old Philco television sets, a Seeburg Select-O-Matic 100 jukebox
and movie posters for such flicks as ``The She Creature'' will go on
sale Saturday alongside green felt tables, one-armed bandits, dice
and playing cards from Eddie's Fabulous '50s casino.
   A 1955 Chevy Belair convertible and car backseats that served as
couches also will be on the auction block.
   ``There's a lot of interest in '50s things, which is why we were
kind of surprised the club didn't make,'' casino spokesman Robert
Fiorehe said Wednesday.
   The casino closed a month ago. Fiore and officials with Ramada
Inc., which owns Eddie's, wouldn't say how much money they lost
since the theme casino opened two years ago after a $9 million
renovation. They blamed the financial problems on a lack of parking
and hotel rooms at the downtown resort.
   Ramada officials hope to soak up some of the red ink by putting
more than $3 million worth of 1950s memorabilia and casino and
restaurant equipment up for auction, along with 1,415 cases of
specially made Eddie's beer and wine.
   ``I have no idea how much money we'll get out of it,'' Fiore
said. ``But it should be a pretty fun auction. And definitely
unusual.''
