<FIRST>r a PM-PavarottiBanned     08-31 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pavarotti Banned,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>No Longer Welcome at Chicago Lyric After Singer Cancels</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL A. DRISCOLL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Lyric Opera of Chicago, stung by another
cancellation from tenor Luciano Pavarotti, said it is no longer
interested in doing business with him.
   Pavarotti, who has backed out of 26 of his 41 scheduled
performances with the company this decade, has an inflammed sciatic
nerve and is unable to move extensively on stage, manager Herbert
Breslin wrote to the Lyric.
   ``I think this is going to be very distressing to the ticket
holders, that he's not coming,'' Ardis Krainik, the Lyric's general
director, said Wednesday after announcing of the ``ban.''
   Breslin said in telephone interview from New York that he thinks
Miss Krainik's reaction is ``a little bit irrational,'' particularly
since Pavarotti has raised ``incredible sums of money'' for the
Lyric in fund-raising appearances.
   ``I think she gets the impression that he is doing this out of
spite for the Lyric Opera of Chicago, which is absolutely wrong,''
said Breslin.
   The Lyric has sold nearly all its 3,550 seats for the season,
during which it's celebrating its 35th anniversary.
   Pavarotti was under contract to perform in Puccini's ``Tosca'' on
six dates this fall.
   ``I did everything possible to try to convince him to fulfill his
commitment with us,'' said Miss Krainik, including a suggestion that
he sing his role from a chair.
   ``His medical problem, while certainly a concern, is apparently
not affecting his voice,'' she said.
   The singer rejected the idea, said Miss Krainik.
   ``Lyric Opera is now unwilling to take the risk of one more
cancellation by Mr. Pavarotti,'' she said.
   ``I'm not mad or exasperated,'' she said. ``I didn't have any
choice. ...
   ``We have 32,000 subscribers who over the years have accosted me
on the street,'' she said. ``A lot of people have been very mad
about his cancellations.''
   Pavarotti's manager wrote that the singer recently was obliged to
cancel his engagement at the opera in Bilbao, Spain, because of the
inflamed sciatic nerve.
   ``His doctor advises that the therapy will be necessary for two
months,'' Breslin wrote. ``So as not to alarm you, this does not
mean that Luciano cannot move or walk, only that he cannot subject
himself to the rigors of a live operatic performance.
   ``He can sing as beautifully as ever,'' the manager said.
   His letter concludes by saying Pavarotti ``looks forward to
returning to Chicago again in 1991.''
   Miss Krainik, however, said because of the cancellation, the
Lyric is not interested in considering any other future engagements
with Pavarotti.
</TEXT>
