<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     08-31 0760</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,760</SECOND>
<HEAD>FDA Gives Red Dye No. 3 Another Reprieve</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Food and Drug Administration has extended
for two months its deadline for deciding whether to ban Red Dye No.
3 as a cancer-causing food additive.
   The agency, in announcing the extension Wednesday, said it has
been evaluating research data submitted by the Certified Color
Manufacturers Association on the coloring that gives maraschino
cherries their bright glow.
   The FDA had been prepared to act by the earlier deadline, which
was Wednesday, when the House in July passed legislation calling for
further study of the dye. The Senate has not yet acted on the
legislation.
   Since 1960, when Congress called for a ban on foods that cause
cancer in laboratory animals, Red Dye No. 3 and other additives have
been on a provisional list that allowed them to stay on the market
for an additional two years pending further study.
   Since then, the FDA has granted dozens of extensions of the
provisional listing.
   The manufacturers association says the dye is not a primary cause
of cancer and causes tumors only when used in doses higher than
would ever be consumed through its use as a food coloring.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Educators, Doctors Join to Fight Early Youth Deaths</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A national coalition of doctors and educators,
armed with evidence that 77 percent of adolescent deaths are
preventable, has been formed to attack problems confronting
teen-agers.
   The commission on adolescent health created Wednesday is composed
of members of the National Association of State Boards of Education
and the American Medical Association.
   The commission was formed, said Roseann Bentley, president of the
education association, ``when we observed that we could not reduce
our young people's vulnerability to AIDS, alcohol and drug
addiction, heart disease and other preventable illness without
changing their behavior.''
   Ms. Bentley will serve as commission co-chairman along with Dr.
M. Roy Schwarz of the American Medical Association.
   William Hendee, AMA vice president for science and technology,
said an estimated 77 percent of the nation's adolescent deaths each
year are preventable. In the 1950s, 75 percent of deaths of youths
aged 10 to 19 years were due to natural causes, compared with only
27 percent in the 1980s.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>US Defends Interim Role for Khmer Rouge, Blames Cambodia, Vietnam</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam and Cambodia are to blame for the
failure of a 19-nation peace conference on Cambodia to forge an
agreement over how to end the conflict between rival warring
actions, the Bush administration says.
   A State department officials on Wednesday reiterated the
administration's reluctant support for a Khmer Rouge role in a
transitional government.
   The collapse of the conference, launched in late July in Paris by
Secretary of State James A. Baker III and other foreign ministers,
could result in intensified fighting between government forces and
an anti-communist resistance that includes exiled Cambodian leader
Prince Sihanouk and Khmer Rouge elements.
   When Baker flew to Paris to kick off the conference, it was
recognized that it could take months to reach a compromise, but
there was guarded optimism the bloodletting might be ended with
diplomacy.
   Cambodian Prime Minister Hun Sen, who hopes to retain power after
the scheduled withdrawal of 26,000 Vietnamese troops from Cambodia a
month from now, strenuously objected to any role for the Khmer
Rouge, who were ousted in an invasion by Vietnam in 1978 and still
have China's support.
   The Khmer Rouge, under then-leader Pol Pot, is believed
responsible for the massacre of at least 1 million Cambodians from
1975 to 1978.
   Margaret Tutwiler, the State Department spokeswoman, registered
unalterable U.S. opposition to the Khmer Rouge returning to power.
But she said the United States would continue to support Sihanouk if
he believed that Khmer Rouge elements, along with members of the
Phnom Penh government, ``should have an interim role.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Report: SC Reactor to Restart in July</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Department of Energy will recommend
restarting the Savannah River tritium-producing reactor in July
1990, The Washington Post reports.
   The report published Thursday, quoting unnamed government
sources, said the decision to restart the reactor was made after a
lengthy safety and technical review. The reactor in Aiken, S.C., was
closed for safety reasons a year ago.
   Tritium, a gas, is used to boost a weapon's explosive force.
   The timetable is later than the target previously set by the
Energy Department, but Energy Secretary James D. Watkins plans to
tell President Bush and other members of the National Security
Council next week that the delay will not threaten national security.
