<FIRST>r i PM-Tambo     08-31 0183</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tambo,0188</SECOND>
<HEAD>ANC Says Tambo Comfortable Following Brain Spasm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Exiled black nationalist leader Oliver Tambo is
resting comfortably following a brain spasm earlier this month that
left him partially paralyzed, a spokesman said.
   Tambo, president of the African National Congress, was expected
to make a full recovery, an ANC spokesman who refused to be named
said Wednesday.
   Tambo, 71-year-old leader of the largest guerrilla organization
fighting the white-led government in South Africa, has been in exile
since ANC was banned by Pretoria in 1960.
   The spokesman said Tambo was ``comfortable and in good spirits''
at a London hospital and had recovered from the partial paralysis he
suffered following the Aug. 8 spasm, which the spokesman said was
brought on ``by an intense work load.''
   Tambo was able to talk and was kept fully informed about events
in South Africa, he said, adding that it was not known how long
Tambo will stay in the hospital.
   The South African leader was flown to London from Zambia on Aug.
11 for treatment of what ANC sources initally said was a stroke.
