<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--SpaceShuttle     08-31 0116</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Space Shuttle,0121</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shuttle Workers Load Galileo on Atlantis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Galileo probe has been loaded
into the space shuttle Atlantis in preparation for an Oct. 12
planetary mission.
   Wednesday's loading was accomplished without incident, said Lisa
Malone, a National Aeronautics and Space Administration spokeswoman.
   She said Atlantis' preparations were five days ahead of schedule.
   The one-ton probe is to make a six-year, 2.4-million-mile voyage
to Venus and Jupiter.
   To power it through the long journey, Galileo will carry two
122-pound generators, each containing 24 pounds of highly toxic
plutonium-238 dioxide.
   The plutonium will not be installed in Galileo until the
countdown begins, about six days before takeoff, Ms. Malone said.
</TEXT>
