<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-89 0345EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Colombia-Americans     08-31 0742</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Colombia-Americans,0769</SECOND>
<HEAD>Americans in Colombia Edgy, but Not Panicked by Cartel Threats</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Colombia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans in Colombia are edgy about the
drug traffickers' retaliatory campaign against the government but
few say they sense any imminent personal danger.
   Nonetheless, some are packing their bags.
   ``I love Colombia, but I just can't live here right now,'' Martha
Reyes, who has lived in the country 18 years, said Wednesday in a
telephone interview.
   She said other factors contributed to her decision to leave next
week with her three daughters, but that the latest wave of violence
``just topped it off.''
   The U.S. State Department on Wednesday recommended that Americans
in Colombia leave the country to avoid being caught up in the
violence. The U.S. Embassy ordered the evacuation of all embassy
dependents, apparently for fear of becoming the targets of the
ruthless cocaine cartels.
   Traffickers are lashing out because of a government
anti-narcotics offensive that has included a nationwide manhunt and
the confiscation of more than $200 million in drug barons' property.
   Part of the campaign, sparked by the Aug. 18 assassination of
popular presidential candidate Sen. Luis Carlos Galan, included
renewal of an extradition treaty with the United States. Traffickers
are known to greatly fear extraditon to the United States.
   Mrs. Reyes, married to a Colombian, said she planned to spend a
year in the United States with her daughters. Her husband, an
economist with a private company in Bogota, plans to stay behind for
now but will look into job possibilities in the States, she said.
   She said she felt no direct threat, but admitted the tension of
Colombia ``gets really tiring.''
   A change of scene would also be welcome, she said.
   ``I'd like to see something different for a year,'' Mrs. Reyes
said. ``Who knows? I may be back in a year. It may be too quiet for
me over there.''
   At Bogota's American School, summer vacation ended Tuesday. On
the first day of classes, all students were assembled and the
headmaster told them to assure their parents special security
measures were being taken.
   One teacher said the measures included constant contact between
the school, the U.S. Embassy and the Bogota mayor's office; strict
measures to keep unauthorized people off campus and checks on any
cars parked on the school's perimeter. The school has always
employed guards and watchmen.
   ``The teachers are all there working with confidence and calm and
without fear,'' she said, asking not to be identified by name. ``We
don't feel any particular threat to Americans.''
   ``On the other hand, there aren't many of us left,'' she added.
Of the school's 1,400 students, less than 10 percent are U.S.
citizens, she noted.
   The American community shrank dramatically in late 1984, when
extradition of drug traffickers to the United States began. Angry
cocaine cartel bosses threatened to kill five Americans for every
dealer who was extradited to America for trial.
   A bomb exploded outside the downtown U.S. Embassy, killing a
female Colombian passer-by.
   Hundreds of Americans fled to the States, many of them executives
in U.S. companies that before the drug violence had been frequent
targets of the country's well-entrenched leftist guerrilla
organizations. Some eventually trickled back. But many returned only
long enough to pack their furniture.
   The U.S. Embassy then established its policy of barring
dependents under 18 years of age.
   Recalling those frightening times, the oft-repeated refrain among
those who remain now is: It's been worse.
   ``There's been many incidents over the last few years,'' said
Steve Walker, who works for a U.S. drilling company. ``To me this is
just one of many.''
   Walker makes regular forays into the guerrilla-plagued jungles of
Colombia's oil-producing region. Extremist kidnappings of Americans
are not unknown.
   ``I'm concerned for the family, the children being out in
public,'' he said. It's not the fear of being a target, but of being
in the wrong place at the wrong time, he said. ``Indiscriminate
bombing kills a lot of people.''
   About the State Department suggestion that they abandon the
country, he said: ``I'll have to talk it over with my wife.''
   An American woman, interviewed on condition she not be
identified, said she wanted to let relatives at home know that
``there's not a state of civil disorder.
   ``We're still getting stuck in traffic jams, we still have to go
to the grocery store. We still pay the electric bill.''
</TEXT>
