<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     08-31 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Nikkei Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose sharply against the yen in slow
trading today, while prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange declined.
   The dollar closed at 144.28 yen, up 1.20 yen from Wednesday's
close. It opened at 144.33 yen and ranged between 144.15 yen and
144.45 yen.
   The dollar also had climbed to 144.28 yen, a nine-week high, on
Monday, but then fell a total of 1.20 yen in the next two days.
   An official of the Bank of Tokyo said the dollar rose in Tokyo
today after rallying sharply in New York late Wednesday.
   The rally was triggered by speculation that U.S. monetary
authorities would allow the dollar's upswing as long as the U.S.
economy continued its ``soft-landing.''
   But many Tokyo players were cautious about stepping into the
market too aggressively before the release of the latest U.S.
unemployment figures, due out in Washington Friday, said the Bank of
Tokyo official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues fell 40.46
points, or 0.11 percent, closing at 34,431.20 points.
   Trading was moderate, with volume at 650 million shares, compared
with 500 million shares Wednesday.
   An official at Nomura Securities Co. said share prices fell by
173.77 points in the morning session, reflecting sluggish buying by
institutional and corporate investors concerned about the dollar's
sharp rise against the yen.
   But in the afternoon, investors purchased blue-chip shares and
the index recovered much of its losses, he said.
</TEXT>
