<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-89 0526EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-VirginiaExecution     08-31 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Virginia Execution,0509</SECOND>
<HEAD>Killed Goes to Electric Chair in Rape, Stabbing of 61-Year-Old Woman</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL BASKERVILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former textile worker was executed for
raping and murdering the 61-year-old woman he stabbed 42 times with
a butcher knife in her farmhouse 12 years ago.
   Alton Waye, 34, was put to death in the electric chair at the
State Penitentiary late Wednesday.
   The sentence was carried out following a day of appeals that
ended with the U.S. Supreme Court voting 7-2 against postponement.
Justices William J. Brennan and Thurgood Marshall, who oppose the
death penalty under all circumstances, voted for a reprieve.
   Earlier, Gov. Gerald L. Baliles denied clemency for Waye.
   Waye was baptized Tuesday night, and took communion before the
execution.
   In a final statement, he said: ``I would express that what is
about to take place is a murder. I don't hate anyone. I forgive
everyone involved.''
   Waye was convicted of murdering Lavergne B. Marshall, a widow who
authorities testified had been beaten beyond recognition when her
nude body was found in a bathtub in 1977. She had been bitten as
well as stabbed, and the killer had poured laundry bleach on the
body, according to testimony.
   Amnesty International argued that Waye should have been spared
the death penalty because he is borderline mentally retarded.
   Defense attorneys offered new evidence showing brain damage and
diminished mental capacity.
   Richard H. Burr, a lawyer from the NAACP Legal Defense and
Educational Fund in New York, told an appeals panel that Waye was
deprived of an adequate psychiatric evaluation when he was tried in
1978.
   Deputy Attorney General Linwood Wells argued that the defense
should have raised such objections earlier.
   Waye was the eighth person to be put to death in Virginia since
the state resumed executions in 1982, and the 117th nationwide since
the U.S. Supreme Court allowed states to resume capital punishment
in 1976.
   About 50 opponents of the death penalty held a candlelight vigil
Wednesday night outside the prison, and about 20 supporters of
capital punishment gathered on a sidewalk across the street.
   ``As far as the victim goes, I have sympathy for the family, but
as far as the guy goes, I believe people can change,'' said Mirella
Neff, 24, who was at the vigil with her 2{-year-old daughter.
   Across the street, Joe Jackson of Richmond said: ``You can't let
them get away with murder. If I committed a crime like he did, I
would deserve to die.''
   Sue Stone of Lunenburg County, who was a close friend of Mrs.
Marshall, said she had had no reaction to Waye's execution.
   ``With anyone being killed the way she was, you never get over
it,'' she said by telephone. ``You try to come to terms with it
through the years. We were very, very close, and for a person as
good as she was ... a religious woman, a gentle woman, it's hard to
accept.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
