<FIRST>r a PM-NJDisturbance     08-31 0525</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NJ Disturbance,0540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Racial Tension High, Some Violence After Funeral Services for Vineland
Man</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MELANIE BURNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWFIELD, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As racial tension and violence continued
over the fatal shooting of a black man by police, about 200 people
gathered for the victim's funeral and heard a prayer he wrote
pleading for a better life.
   Community leaders in Vineland had hoped the violence that
followed Sunday night's shooting had subsided, but unrest continued
late Wednesday and four more people were arrested.
   Hour earlier, mourners packed into Truth Baptist Church in the
nearby town of Newfield for the two-hour ceremony and listened to a
reading of the prayer written by Samuel Williams shortly before his
death. He called it ``A Letter to the Lord.''
   ``My Father, bless me so I can bless my family and do better,''
the 26-year-old Williams wrote. ``Help.''
   Before the service, Vineland Mayor Harry Curley met with
community leaders to defuse the unrest. He said an eight-member
special task force was formed to find a way to restore calm in the
southern New Jersey city.
   ``We're hoping this will be the first step,'' Curley said.
``We're hoping that we can be assured there won't be any more
outbreaks.''
   Curley said 32 people have been arrested since Monday night, when
some 200 people threw rocks and bottles at stores lining the city's
main drag.
   In Wednesday's violence, a WPVI-TV news crew from Philadelphia
was attacked by youths as they interviewed people in downtown
Vineland, where the rioting and looting first broke out Monday, said
city spokesman Lee Tofanelli.
   Reporter Dann Cuellar was listed in stable condition at Newcomb
Medical Center in Vineland with a broken nose and facial injuries.
   Hie wallet and some television equipment were stolen. The
equipment was returned later, Tofanelli said.
   One man allegedly involved in the attack was arrested on assault
and robbery charges, and three other people were arrested in a
separate incident after they refused police orders to leave the
area, Tofanelli said.
   At the service, Jynell Harris, an educational coordinator for the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People, read
Williams' letter.
   ``I feel so ashamed of the way I let you down,'' it said.
``Father, please have mercy on me. I feel so lost in a life of
drugs. I was doing the same thing too many years.''
   Williams, a father of two children, was shot after he allegedly
threatened Officer Paul Letizia with a steel rod, according to
police Chief Joseph Cassisi.
   Williams, who was wanted on drug and weapons charges, was spotted
by officers after police received an anonymous telephone tip about a
man on a bicycle carrying drugs, Cassisi said.
   After officers told Williams he was under arrest, he picked up
the rod and approached Letizia, swinging, Cassisi said. Letizia, who
is white, fired two shots at Williams, hitting him both times, the
police chief said.
   Curley said Letizia has been taken off street duty and put on
special assignment. The mayor said he had no intention of following
the demands of some blacks who want Letizia suspended without pay
pending the outcome of an investigation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
