<FIRST>u i PM-Israel     08-31 0697</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel,0716</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israeli Dies of Firebomb Wounds, Sharon Calls for Killing Masked
Youths</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Israeli tax collector died today of injuries
suffered in a firebomb attack by Palestinian assailants in the
occupied West Bank, a hospital spokeswoman said.
   Industry Minister Ariel Sharon, meanwhile, suggested Israel
consider legalizing the killing of masked Palestinians without
checking whether they are armed. He said the masked youths are the
ringleaders behind slayings in the 20-month-old uprising.
   In another development, Arab reports said a Palestinian teen-ager
died of wounds suffered in a clash four days ago with soldiers in
the occupied Gaza Strip.
   In the West Bank city of Nablus, the body of a 28-year-old
Palestinian was found in a pushcart with stab wounds, Israel radio
and Arab reports said.
   The man, whose name was not given, was believed to have been
slain as a suspected collaborator with the Israeli authorities,
raising the number of such Arab deaths in the uprising to 101. The
army said it was investigating the circumstances of the slaying.
   An army spokesman said the military was investigating a possible
link between a stoning attack in the Gaza two weeks ago and the
death of a reservist soldier at his home on Wednesday.
   In northern Israel, a Soviet-made Katyusha rocket fired from
southern Lebanon slammed into a home on Wednesday night, breaking
most of its windows but causing no injury, the army said.
   Northern Commander Gen. Yossi Peled said the attack appeared to
be the work of the pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem movement Hezbollah, or
Party of God. He said Israel would retaliate if the attacks
continued.
   In the Gaza, 19-year-old Ahmad Abdullah Al-Agha died at Nasser
Hospital in Khan Yunis of head injuries suffered in a clash with
troops on Aug. 27, Arab reports said.
   The reports quoted family as saying Al-Agha had been beaten by
troops. The army confirmed the death and said it was investigating
the circumstances.
   The tax collector, Gideon Zaken, 34, died at Jerusalem's Hadassah
Hospital of breathing complications after suffering burns on 70
percent of his body in the Aug. 14 firebombing, spokeswoman Ruth
Mekel said.
   Zaken was one of four Israelis injured in the attack by
Palestinians in the West Bank city of Ramallah on a vehicle carrying
Israeli civilian employees of the military government.
   His death raised to 39 the number of Israelis killed in the
uprising against Israeli rule of the occupied territories.
Palestinian deaths have totalled 554.
   Israeli and Arab reports said soldiers had apprehended a suspect
in the firebomb attack, identified as Majed Jamal al Zain of
neighboring El Bireh, and that his family was appealing army orders
to demolish their home as punishment.
   Army and police investigators were conducting an autopsy today to
determine whether a man identified as Haim Shaharabani, 38, found
dead at home Wednesday, died as a result of a stoning attack.
   The Haaretz daily and Israel radio said Shaharabani, of the Tel
Aviv suburb of Herzliya, received hospital treatment after being hit
in the head by a stone while serving as a reserve soldier in Khan
Yunis in the Gaza two weeks ago.
   After the incident, Shaharabani complained repeatedly of
headaches and vomiting, his family was quoted as saying. Police
believed the stoning may have caused the symptoms and his death,
according to the reports.
   Khan Yunis, home to about 35,000 Palestinians, has been a
frequent scene of protests against Israeli rule. Two soldiers were
injured by rocks in the town on Wednesday, and 11 Palestinians were
reported wounded when soldiers opened fire at the stone throwers.
   Sharon, of the right-wing Likud bloc, made his comment about
killing masked men in a speech broadcast on army radio. He said the
key activists in the uprising wore masks during attacks.
   ``They are people who are acting, murdering. They must be
liquidated and if the law doesn't allow this, then we must take care
so the law will allow it,'' Sharon said.
   He added, ``There is no possibility of checking every masked
person to see if he is or isn't carrying weapons. These are people
who are conducting murders. This is what must be done.''
</TEXT>
