<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-89 0612EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Nuclear     08-31 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Nuclear,0401</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan's Doi Tells United States: No Nukes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of Japan's largest opposition
party said in an interview published today that if she became prime
minister she would ban U.S. nuclear weapons from Japan.
   The Sydney Morning Herald newspaper said such a policy might
force the U.S. Navy to abandon many of its operations in the
northwest Pacific, and it quoted U.S. and Japanese officials as
saying it could damage the alliance between the nations.
   Takako Doi, chairman of the Japan Socialist Party, was quoted as
telling the newspaper that the United States had pledged to consult
with Japan before carrying nuclear weapons into its territory, and
that it was time to enforce the agreement.
   The popular Ms. Doi could become prime minister if the governing
Liberal Democratic Party loses its control of parliament in an
upcoming general election and the Socialists are able to forge a
coalition with other opposition parties.
   ``Once the U.S. has promised, it must observe its promise,'' the
Morning Herald quoted her as saying. ``It is a matter of principle.
Japan must face up to its responsibilities and hold diplomatic
negotiations with the United States.
   ``Japan cannot admit, from any country, ships carrying nuclear
weapons.''
   Ms. Doi said she was prepared to pursue the policy even if it
denied the U.S. Navy the ability to operate in the parts of the
Pacific.
   The Herald said the United States has ignored its pledge and
routinely carries nuclear weapons into Japanese territory on ships.
   The United States refuses to publicly confirm or deny whether its
ships carry nuclear weapons. Such a policy has affected its
relations with New Zealand, which has denied U.S. ships suspected of
carrying nuclear warheads entry to its ports.
   The Herald quoted a U.S. diplomat as saying a policy such as the
one promoted by Ms. Doi would have a ``tremendous impact on our
strategic posture'' and would be ``tantamount to an abrogation of
the Japan-U.S. security treaty.''
   It quoted a Japanese defense official as saying the change would
``produce a breakdown in the Japan-U.S. relationship and be a very
serious source of instability in the region.'' Neither official was
identified.
   Japan, the only nation to have suffered atomic attacks, maintains
a policy of not manufacturing, storing or allowing nuclear weapons
to be introduced into the country.
</TEXT>
