<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-89 0641EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BarkerSued     08-31 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Barker Sued,0511</SECOND>
<HEAD>Game Show Host Bob Barker Sued By Humane Association</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNE M. PETERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Game show host and animal rights crusader Bob
Barker has been slapped with a $10 million libel lawsuit by the
American Humane Association and its West Coast director.
   The action, filed in Superior Court Wednesday, contends Barker
and other animal rights organizations conducted a two-year campaign
to ruin the reputation of the association and its regional director
Betty Denny Smith.
   The lawsuit claims Barker falsely stated on radio shows that the
association allowed muzzling of two dogs and approved a fight
between the animals on the film ``The Tender,'' which would have
been illegal.
   Barker also claimed the association lied on its reports of an
investigation of cruelty against chimpanzees during production of
the film ``Project X,'' the lawsuit says.
   Barker denied the allegations.
   ``If this suit results in the American public becoming more aware
of the extent of animal cruelty in entertainment then the suit will
have served a very valuable purpose and it will be well worth the
money and the time it costs me,'' he said.
   The lawsuit accuses Barker, United Activists for Animal Rights
and its executive director, Nancy Burnet, of libel, slander, trade
libel, interference with prospective business relations, conspiracy
and false-light invasion of privacy, association attorney Barry
Langberg said.
   ``No one is saying Mr. Barker isn't an animal rights activist,''
Langberg said at a news conference. ``We're only saying he has other
things on his schedule than the protection of animal rights.''
   A separate claim was filed against the city and Department of
Animal Regulation head Robert I. Rush for allegedly assisting Barker
in the campaign, Langberg said.
   ``I haven't even seen it,'' said Rush, ``but the conduct of this
office in the past has been beyond reproach and it is currently
beyond reproach. The claim will be discussed with the city attorney
and a response will be made.''
   Telephone calls to Ms. Burnet and the United Activists seeking
comment were met with repeated busy signals.
   Ms. Smith said it was unfortunate the situation resulted in a
lawsuit, since both parties want to protect animals.
   ``It is sad, and it has wasted a lot of our time. But we are not
the ones doing the attacking,'' she said. ``We've been trying to get
our work done. We didn't want to take it this far, but these have
been vicious attacks.''
   The association was founded in 1877 for the protection of animals
and children, and the West Coast regional office has been active in
protecting animals in the entertainment industry.
   Barker, longtime host of the television game show ``The Price Is
Right,'' said he has never been sued before.
   In 1987 he won the highest award given by the American Society
for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals. That same year he quit
after 19 years as host of the Miss USA Pageant because contestants
wore fur coats.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890831-0057 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-89 0643EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Refugees     08-31 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Refugees,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Posing as Vietnamese Refugees Arriving in Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said today that at least 86 of the
nearly 2,000 boat people who have arrived in Japan over the last
three months were Chinese job-seekers posing as Vietnamese.
   A Foreign Ministry spokesman said its United Nations bureau
director, in a meeting today with a Chinese embassy official, asked
China to investigate the matter and take measures to stop the
illegal entries of Chinese into Japan.
   The Foreign Ministry said Japanese immigration officials
determined that at least two of the 86 were carrying fake Vietnamese
birth certificates.
   Ministry officials said 1,919 boat people have arrived on 14
vessels, many of them barely seaworthy, since May. That figure
contrasts sharply with the 219 refugees from Vietnam who arrived in
Japan in all of 1988
   On Wednesday, Japan issued its first deportation order for
Chinese who came to the country pretending to be refugees from
Vietnam.
   The first order was for Xu Weiming, 30, who admitted he boarded a
Vietnamese refugee boat in hopes of finding a job in Japan, said
Hideo Daian, spokeman of the Justice Ministry's immigration office
in Fukuoka, on the southernmost main island of Kyushu.
   Xu, considered an illegal immigrant, was among six Chinese
discovered among 107 Vietnamese who arrived in southwestern Japan
aboard a wooden boat on May 29, Daian said.
   Meanwhile, Chief Cabinet Secretary Mayumi Moriyama said today
that Japan would tighten screening of the boat people to cope with
the refugee problem.
   Japan has decided it will accept only refugees from political
persecution, and not economic migrants, but officials say details of
the screening policy remain to be worked out.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
