<FIRST>u i PM-Cambodia     08-31 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cambodia,0402</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Blames Vietnam for Failure of Cambodian Peace Conference</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China today blamed Vietnam for the failure of the
Cambodian peace conference and questioned whether its rival would
make good on a promise to pull its troops out of Cambodia by the end
of September.
   The monthlong international conference ended Wednesday night in
the French capital without an agreement to halt fighting among
Cambodia's Vietnam-installed government and three guerrilla
factions, which united as a coalition for negotiations at the
conference.
   The delegates from 19 countries and the United Nations agreed to
suspend the meeting and come back when the warring parties were more
willing to compromise.
   Prince Norodom Sihanouk, leader of the coalition and one of its
three factions, called for patience in ending the 19 years of
fighting in his nation.
   Cambodian Prime Minister Hun Sen blamed the Khmer Rouge, the
strongest of the three resistance groups, for sabotaging the
negotiations. He predicted it would begin a new round of killing
after the Vietnamese troops pull out.
   ``They are striving for victory on the battlefield and did not
have the slightest intention of striving for a political
arrangement,'' he said Wednesday.
   But China, which backs the Khmer Rouge, blamed the stalled
negotiations on ``the intransigence of Vietnam and Phnom Penh
authorities,'' Foreign Ministry spokesman Li Zhaoxing said in
Beijing.
   Despite the lack of an accord, Vietnam will complete the
withdrawal of its 26,000 troops by Sept. 27 as planned, Hun Sen said.
   China's official Xinhua News Agency quoted Vice Foreign Minister
Liu Shuqing as saying in Paris that China did not believe that.
   ``Vietnam showed no sincerity at the conference,'' Liu said.
   The main obstacle was the insistence by Vietnam and Hun Sen's
government that the Khmer Rouge be barred from any future coalition
government.
   The Khmer Rouge, the strongest of three guerrilla forces, is
blamed for the deaths of hundreds of thousands of deaths during its
fanatical rule from 1975 to 1978, when Vietnam invaded the country.
   Foreign ministers Roland Dumas of France and Ali Alatas of
Indonesia, the chairmen of the conference, said they will begin
consultations within six months with the Cambodian factions in hopes
of reconvening the meeting.
   ``We will come back to Paris,'' Sihanouk said. ``The problem is
complicated. We must be patient.''
</TEXT>
