<FIRST>r i PM-MarkandAnne     08-31 0654</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mark and Anne,0670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shared Love of Horses Wasn't Enough To Keep Them Together</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Royal Split, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The love of horses that initially drew Princess
Anne and Mark Phillips together wasn't enough to sustain their
marriage after 15 years.
   The 39-year-old daughter of Queen Elizabeth II and her
40-year-old husband both remain involved in the equestrian world but
have drifted apart in the past decade, with rumors of marital
troubles surfacing repeatedly since 1981.
   Once the most unpopular of Britain's royals, the queen's only
daughter has become one of its greatest assets, admired for her
charity work, including grueling travels to visit children in poor,
war-torn Third World countries.
   Never at ease with royal duties, Phillips has devoted himself to
farming and various equestrian-related business interests including
his own equestrian center in Scotland and schools for young riders
in Britain and overseas.
   They have been spending up to half the year apart. On their 15th
wedding anniversary Nov. 15, Anne attended a Buckingham Palace ball
while Mark was giving riding lessons in Australia.
   When news of their separation was reported Wednesday night, he
was at their Gatcombe Park home estate in western England and she
was more than 3,000 miles away in Puerto Rico attending an
International Olympic Committee meeting.
   Their marriage at Westminster Abbey on Nov. 14, 1973, watched by
more than 500 million television viewers, climaxed the storybook
romance of a dashing commoner and a headstrong princess.
   She had already made headlines in the swinging '60s for wearing
mini-skirts and dancing onstage with the cast of the rock musical
``Hair.''
   A captain in The Queen's Dragoon Guards, Mark met Anne in 1968 at
a dinner for the British Olympic riding team, and both have been in
equestrian teams at the Olympics. Their relationship became serious
in 1972.
   Both went on to win riding championships, and two children were
born _ Peter, now 11, and Zara, 8.
   By the late 1970s, Anne had the reputation of being rude and
intolerant, fonder of horses than people. Tabloid newspapers labeled
the princess ``Her Royal Haughtiness.''
   The image began to thaw in 1982 with her tour on behalf of the
Save the Children Fund to seven African countries and Beirut.
Impressed by her courage, knowledge and appetite for hard work, the
newspapers switched to headlines about ``The Caring Princess.''
   Mark joined his wife on some of her early overseas visits, but as
the years passed, he was rarely with her in public. In a Sunday
Express interview last year, he said accompanying Anne had ``become
easier over the years, but I wouldn't say I find it easy.''
   Describing himself as ``quiet and shy,'' Mark said farming was
his passion, and he spoke with delight about planting thousands of
trees and trying to save wildlife.
   Possessed of a biting wit, Anne says she never wanted to be the
prettiest, sweetest or most loved of the royals, preferring to do
something constructive for others. ``I didn't match up to the
public's idea of a fairy princess in the first place,'' she told the
Sunday Times.
   Now the busiest member of the royal family after her mother, Anne
is president or patron of more than 75 charities ranging from
disabled riders to prison workers, plus 23 military groups and six
trade guilds.
   Britain's tabloids have tried to link Anne to a former bodyguard,
to actor Anthony Andrews and most recently to Royal Navy Cmdr.
Timothy Laurence, a handsome aide to the queen who wrote her
personal letters which were stolen and sent to a newspaper.
   Mark has been linked by the tabloids to one of his stable girls,
a Canadian public relations executive, and most recently to a former
Miss India.
   Anne and Mark have been at pains to preserve the children's
privacy. They attend private schools, and Anne has refused to accept
any titles for them.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
