<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-89 0835EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-RockyFlats     08-31 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rocky Flats,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>Safety Problems Continue At Rocky Flats Nuclear Weapons Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rocky Flats nuclear weapons plant was plagued
by safety problems two months after federal agents raided it for
evidence of alleged environmental crimes, according to an Energy
Department report.
   The safety inspection report for the week of Aug. 7-11, obtained
Wednesday by The Denver Post, said there was ``no improvement in the
radiological protection areas'' at Rocky Flats during the past
several months.
   A similar report, based on a plant inspection in July, detailed
10 serious problems with radiation protection at the plant. None of
the specific problems cited in July resurfaced in August, however.
   Rocky Flats is operated by Rockwell International Corp. under
contract from the DOE. The plant produces plutonium triggers for
nuclear bombs.
   A federal grand jury in Denver is investigating officials from
Rockwell and the DOE for allegedly conspiring to illegally dispose
of radioactive and hazardous wastes.
   About 75 FBI agents and special officers from the Environmental
Protection Agency raided the plant on June 6 after a search warrant
was issued on an affidavit containing more than 100 pages of
allegations.
   A Rockwell spokesman said the new safety inspections they started
at Rocky Flats in early July are correcting many problems. But
spokesman Ed Heints admitted no factory is perfect, not even one
that handles plutonium.
   ``We act on these things as soon as we are notified of them,'' he
said. ``But with as many people as we have here, some people are
just going to get careless.'' The plant employs about 6,000 people.
   The report, written by an unidentified Energy Department safety
inspector, said an employee was seen in a radiation control area not
wearing anti-contamination clothing. The employee then left the area
without going through a required monitoring device.
   Another employee in a building where radioactive material is
handled violated safety procedures by leaving doors open that should
have been closed, the report said.
   ``These are just two of the numerous problems observed across the
Rocky Flats site,'' the inspector wrote.
</TEXT>
