<FIRST>u i PM-Colombia-Analysis 1stLd-Writethru   08-31 0949</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Colombia-Analysis, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0489,0981</SECOND>
<HEAD>Colombia's War With Traffickers: Little Chance of Quick Victory</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Recasts top three grafs for clarity. Pickup 4th pvs, `The official...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Colombia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Colombia is in a costly war with drug
traffickers, and it appears to have little chance of a quick victory.
   The current campaign to crush drug lords and their private
armies, if it continues, is likely to drag on for years before it
succeeds, according to officials familiar with the situation.
   It will take billions of dollars and at least a decade to defeat
the traffickers, a senior U.S. diplomat with the U.S. Embassy in
Bogota said in response to a question during a briefing Wednesday.
   The official spoke on condition that his remarks be paraphrased,
that he not be identified and that the briefing not be recorded.
   A former Colombian army intelligence officer told an Associated
Press reporter that he, too, thinks it will take billions of dollars
and well over a decade before drug traffickers are no longer a
threat.
   The officer, a former major, said he has his doubts about whether
the war can be won at all. He also spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The former army officer pointed out that there is no reason to
believe government security forces will have any more success
fighting drug traffickers than they have had combating leftist
guerrillas.
   The army has been fighting leftist guerrillas for three decades,
and the rebel forces have grown steadily to an estimated 10,000
combatants.
   The traffickers' power also has grown quickly.
   Fifteen years ago, some of today's millionaire and billionaire
cocaine traffickers were pickpockets and pig farmers. Six years ago
they offered to pay off Colombia's $10 billion foreign debt if the
government would give them amnesty.
   The offer was rejected.
   Today, the traffickers have private armies totaling about 4,000
men, intelligence-gathering units, modern weapons and fleets of
airplanes and helicopters, the former major said.
   To meet this growing threat, the government has sharply increased
its spending on security forces, and President Bush has authorized
$65 million of emergency assistance to Colombia to fight the
traffickers.
   Unfortunately, it all may be too little, too late.
   ``A lot of army officers know it would take billions of dollars
to exterminate all of the drug traffickers, to destroy their
empires,'' the former intelligence officer said.
   The United States has been giving Colombia about $10 million a
year to fight the traffickers, an amount that seems small
considering the urgency the United States has given the drug problem
and the traffickers' power.
   In the last five years, an AP reporter in Bogota has seen many
signs of Colombia's inability to combat the cocaine problem.
   A U.S. DEA agent once said that Colombia's anti-drug agents were
so poorly equipped that they had to beg gas from their U.S.
counterparts to go on drug raids.
   An Air Force pilot flying search-and-destroy missions over the
eastern jungles to eradicate coca plantations told the AP reporter
that pilots need longer range planes to be effective.
   And farmers in the Andes in southeast Colombia told the reporter
they weren't worried about police helicopters swooping down
periodically to destroy coca bushes. New bushes are planted
immediately after police leave, they said.
   Army troops in the field are poorly equipped. Boots are worn
until they almost fall apart. As AP reporter in combat areas has
seen soldiers flagging down banana trucks and forcing drivers to
transport troops because the army does not have enough trucks of its
own.
   Meanwhile, the traffickers use the most modern automatic weapons,
including light antitank weapons.
   The former intelligence officer told The AP that former
colleagues told him recently about raids on one trafficker's hideout
that turned up records indicating he spent $100,000 a month
gathering information.
   Former President Belisario Betancur, speaking of the traffickers
during his 1982-86 term, said: ``Colombia is fighting against
something that is stronger than the state.''
   Betancur's justice minister, Rodrigo Lara Bonilla, was murdered,
riddled with bullets because raids on cocaine laboratories had hurt
the traffickers too much.
   In the last 10 years, traffickers have killed 220 judges and
other court employes, two newspaper editors, a justice minister, an
attorney general, hundreds of policemen and soldiers and dozens of
others perceived by traffickers as a threat to their business.
   To counter the violence, the Colombian government has started for
the first time in 30 years spending more on the military than on
education.
   The government increased the military's share of the 1990 budget
to 17 percent from 10 percent, for a total of $560 million.
   That is almost certainly bound to limit growth of spending on
schools, hospitals and other public works.
   It is that sort of thinking that got Colombia's guerrillas
started three decades ago.
   Progressive governments have done much to develop the country,
but extreme poverty is still a problem.
   Many children grow up never tasting meat or milk. Cardboard boxes
discarded in front of houses disappear in minutes, taken by people
who sell them.
   People digging in garbage dumps for bones to sell to chemical
companies and for such things as bottles are so common that there
are labor unions among the scavengers.
   Such shortcomings are eventually going to have to be weighed as
Colombia's guerrillas continue to press for changes in government
spending to help the country's poor people.
   A costly and continued war against drug traffickers will make
that difficult if not impossible unless there is massive aid from
the United States and elsewhere.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Tom Wells, The Associated Press bureau chief of
Colombia, has been based in Bogota since 1978.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890831-0065 </DOCNO>
