<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-89 0941EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-TMICracks     08-31 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-TMI Cracks,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cracks Confirmed In Steel Lining of Three Mile Island Reactor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIDDLETOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A steel sheet lining the bottom of a Three
Mile Island reactor cracked in spots during the 1979 accident,
officials said after seeing video footage from the depths of the
submerged reactor.
   But a clear picture of how well the Unit 2 reactor vessel
withstood the 5,000-degree heat will have to await further study.
   The first color video to be taken inside the 40-foot depths of
the submerged reactor clearly showed that lines first spotted in
July were cracks, said the plant operator, GPU Nuclear Corp., on
Wednesday.
   Investigation of the four cracks on Saturday required a newly
developed radiation-resistant color television camera and specially
designed tools to brush debris from the area, probe each crack and
take measurements.
   The cracks, one as long as 6 inches and just fractions of an inch
wide and deep, were caused by molten uranium fuel that streamed like
lava to the reactor bottom during the accident.
   ``It's all new, but it is not surprising to find them at this
location,'' said GPU Nuclear spokesman Doug Bedell.
   Though other cracks are possible in the thin steel sheet, the
company feels it's more important to concentrate on removing
thousands of pounds of fuel debris still left in the reactor.
   Fuel removal should be completed by November so a $7 million,
11-nation research project into the 5-inch thick, carbon steel
reactor vessel can start, Bedell said.
   ``That's when we'll get a more definitive analysis of how the
bottom head withstood the accident,'' Bedell said.
   Until then it will not be known if the cracks in the
three-sixteenths-inch thick sheeting extend into the vessel, he
added. The stainless steel layer is intended to protect the carbon
steel walls of the vessel from corrosion.
   The accident, the worst ever at a U.S commercial nuclear power
plant, was triggered by a combination of operator and mechanical
errors. Water was cut off to the 150-ton radioactive core and about
half of it melted. Radioactive gas was released to the atmosphere.
   TMI's Unit 1, adjacent to the damaged plant, was closed for six
years after the March 1979 accident, but was returned to commercial
service in 1985.
</TEXT>
