<FIRST>r a PM-DeathSentence     08-31 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Death Sentence,0433</SECOND>
<HEAD>Execution Ordered for Couple Convicted of Abduction and Torture</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN BERNARDINO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who said she was brutalized
into helping her boyfriend in a rape-murder was sentenced to death
by a judge who said he believed she ``was in this thing up to the
hilt.''
   Cynthia Lynn Coffman, 27, on Wednesday became the first woman to
be sentenced to death in California since capital punishment was
reinstated in 1977.
   Superior Court Judge Don A. Turner sentenced both her and her
former lover, James Gregory Marlow, 33, to death for the Nov. 7,
1986, slaying of Corinna Novis, 20. They still face charges in the
death of another young woman whose body was found five days later.
   Ms. Coffman wiped away tears when the sentence was pronounced.
``I'm sorry for what happened and I am ashamed that I let it
happen,'' she told Turner.
   Ms. Coffman testified she was brutalized and forced to commit the
crimes, but the judge upheld the jury's recommendation, saying Ms.
Coffman ``was in this thing up to the hilt and enjoyed it up to the
last minute.''
   ``They were equal partners in this thing all the way down the
line,'' Chip Haight, a San Bernardino County deputy district
attorney, said after Wednesday's sentencing. ``I didn't buy her
domination story one bit.''
   Ms. Coffman testified that Marlow raped her, beat her and cut off
all her hair. She said he once told her, ``I am the devil, and I own
you.''
   Ms. Coffman, who has a 9-year-old son, will be imprisoned at the
Correctional Institution for Women at Frontera. If appeals that are
expected to take several years fail, she will be executed in the gas
chamber.
   One woman has been executed in the United States since capital
punishment was reinstated by the U.S. Supreme Court in 1977. Velma
Barfield, 52, was put to death in North Carolina in 1984 for
poisoning her boyfriend.
   The last woman executed in California was 58-year-old convicted
killer Elizabeth Ann Duncan in 1962.
   Ms. Novis was raped, tortured and killed after she offered to
give Ms. Coffman and Marlow a ride near a shopping mall in Redlands.
Ms. Coffman said she thought she and her boyfriend were only going
to kidnap and rob the woman. The judge said it was clear the two
planned murder.
   ``One of the reasons she was fascinated with Mr. Marlow and made
him her man is that he had the strength to do things she could not
do,'' Turner said.
</TEXT>
