<HEAD>Opposition Party Members Clash With Gandhi Supporters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition activists clashed with
governing party workers in Calcutta today and 15 people were
injured, news reports said.
   The clash came one day after opposition groups called a one-day
nationwide strike to protest the government of Prime Mininster Rajiv
Gandhi and his Congress Party. Clashes between rival parties left 12
people dead.
   Today, Congress Party workers and members of the Marxist
Communist Party battled with sticks and rocks for two hours on the
streets in the eastern city of Calcutta, United News of India
reported.
   It said one Congress worker's house also was set on fire.
   Calcutta is the capital of the West Bengal state, which is
governed by the Marxist Communist Party, one of the four sponsors of
Wednesday's nationwide strike. The other participants were the
Communist Party of India, the centrist People's Group and the
right-wing Indian People's Party.
   The strike was called to demand Gandhi's resignation and to
highlight alleged corruption in his government.
   Police said they arrested 103,450 opposition activists during the
daylong strike. Arrests during such demonstrations are routine, and
detainees are generally released after a few hours.
