<HEAD>Confiscated Vehicles May Be Sent to Colombia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Limousines, trucks and other vehicles
confiscated from U.S. drug dealers may be sent to Colombia to help
protect judges from the Medellin cartel, the Justice Department said
today.
   Justice Department officials, reviewing Colombia's request for
$19 million in U.S. aid to help protect judges, are trying to
determine if any of the seized property can be useful to the Bogota
government.
   ``We're taking a look at what's been confiscated to see if any of
that meets any of their needs,'' Runkel said.
   The government has a large inventory of boats, planes, limousines
and other vehicles seized as a result of drug prosecutions.
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh is a frequent flyer on an
executive jet the FBI once seized from a convicted drug dealer.
   Colombia's Justice Minister Monica de Greiff this week asked the
Bush administration to expand from $5 million to $19 million the aid
package it had promised for judicial security, saying bullet-proof
cars and metal detectors are needed to protect judges from
drug-cartel death squads.
   Runkel said Mrs. de Greiff, who is in Washington to press her
appeal for more help, is expected to meet next Tuesday with Justice
Department officials for further discussions about her request.
