<FIRST>u a PM-Bush-Alaska     08-31 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Alaska,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Scrubs Plan to Visit Alaska</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush has abandoned plans to
travel to Alaska next month in the face of continuing negative
publicity over the Exxon Valdez oil spill, it was learned today.
   Bush's trip would have been part of a mid-September swing to
Montana, South Dakota and Washington. The White House had not
officially announced the trip, as details continued to be worked out.
   The Alaska leg of the trip would have been for the purpose of
examining the cleanup progress in the wake of the
multimillion-gallon oil spill from the tanker Exxon Valdez last
March.
   Bush was said to be very intent on going, but one source,
speaking on condition of anonymity said the views of other officials
that it would be unwise politically prevailed.
   It was thought it would not be a good idea for the president to
renew focus on the oil spill, a situation for which he was
criticized for not moving quickly enough to involve the federal
government in the cleanup.
   Initially the administration took the position that Exxon Corp.
was handling the job adequately. But after several days, officials
criticized the company, saying it had not moved as quickly as it
could have.
   The 11-million gallon spill occurred March 24 in Prince William
Sound, smearing oil on hundreds of miles of once pristine shoreline.
   Environmentalists have criticized Exxon's plan to halt the
cleanup next month in the face of severe weather conditions.
</TEXT>
