<FIRST>u a PM-Marijuana-Teacher 1stLd-Writethru a0504 08-31 0758</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Marijuana-Teacher, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0504,0780</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Who Was Selected Teacher of The Year Acquitted of Drug Charges</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 13 grafs to UPDATE school superintendent saying he
does not plan to rehire the teacher. Picks up 9th graf, pvs, ```My picture
...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLIOTT MINOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOULTRIE, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A school superintendent said today he does
not plan to to rehire the county's Teacher of the Year even though a
jury acquitted her of charges she manufactured and possessed
marijuana.
   Vicki Sherling, who was accused of helping her husband, Michael,
grow marijuana in their backyard greenhouse, was found innocent of
the charges in Superior Court late Wednesday.
   She said afterward she might try to get her job back because ``I
am a teacher.''
   But Superintendent Billy Mock said today he does not intend to
rehire Mrs. Sherling to her former post at Colquitt County High
School.
   ``The action of the school board will stand until we're told
otherwise,'' he said, noting that Mrs. Sherling already has appealed
her firing to the state Board of Education.
   Mock said Mrs. Sherling was fired on a charge of immorality _
that she knowingly allowed marijuana to be used. The local school
board did not consider whether she was involved in possessing or
growing marijuana, he said.
   ``She admitted in our hearing that she knew it was going on, that
it was being used,'' he said. ``The action taken yesterday (by the
jury) and the action taken by the Board of Education are not related
to each other.''
   Jurors deliberated two hours Wednesday before reaching their
verdict.
   ``I respect the opinion of the jury _ and that's why we have
juries _ but I'll continue to prosecute cases where drug squads find
marijuana growing in someone's back yard,'' District Attorney Lamar
Cole said.
   The couple were arrested May 19 when drug agents, acting on a
tip, found 22 small marijuana plants growing in their back yard and
drug paraphernalia in their house.
   Mrs. Sherling testified that her husband planted marijuana
without her knowledge. Sherling said the same thing in earlier
testimony, and 11 character witnesses took the stand to vouch for
her honesty.
   ``It was the truth, and they knew it,'' Mrs. Sherling said as
jubilant relatives and supporters rushed up to congratulate her
Wednesday evening.
   During the trial, the 38-year-old teacher testified: ``I'm trying
desperately to put my life back together. I'm trying to clear my
name.
   ``My picture was on the front page of the newspaper _ Teacher of
the Year charged with marijuana. I spent two weeks curled up in a
fetal position.''
   Cole questioned her about marijuana found in a chest of drawers
in the couple's bedroom and about a pipe with drug residue in a
washroom chest.
   ``I trust my husband, and in one thing he betrayed me,'' she
said. ``He never told me he would quit. That would have been a lie.
He said: `Vicki I'll cut down. Vicki, I won't smoke it in your
presence.'''
   In closing arguments, Cole said both Sherlings were too
intelligent for one to have grown marijuana in the back yard without
the other's knowledge.
   Dwight May, Mrs. Sherling's attorney, said she had suffered
enough by putting up with her husband's marijuana addiction.
   ``Vicki Sherling is innocent except for one thing,'' May said.
``She's guilty of loving her husband, and she may be guilty of
living with him all these years and suffering through what she's
suffered.''
   The couple's arrest came as a shock to most in Moultrie, an
agricultural community of 15,000.
   Mrs. Sherling could have been sentenced to up to 11 years in
prison and fined $1,000 if convicted on a felony count of
manufacturing marijuana and a misdemeanor charge of possessing less
than an ounce of the drug.
   She told the Superior Court that she first learned of the
marijuana in the back yard when she phoned her home and a drug agent
answered.
   ``I went home and saw police cars all over the place,'' she said.
``I saw my husband in the living room with his hands handcuffed
behind his back. My whole world came crashing in on me.''
   Character witnesses, including co-workers, members of a theater
group and parents from a local Boy Scout troop, praised Mrs.
Sherling as a woman of stellar character who would never lie to her
friends about something as serious as marijuana use.
   Sherling, a former teacher and attorney, has admitted chronic
marijuana use. He testified Tuesday that his wife never grew or
smoked the stuff.
</TEXT>
