<FIRST>r a PM-WitchSuit     08-31 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Witch Suit,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Accused of Witchcraft Sues School District</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teacher who tells fortunes and gives
card readings but says she was falsely accused of practicing
witchcraft has filed a $1.6 million suit against a school district,
contending it ruined her career.
   Laura Linzay Dick filed suit against the North Kansas City School
District in federal court Tuesday, six months after she quit her job
teaching speech and drama at Maple Park Middle School.
   She contends that school district administrators accused her of
practicing witchcraft and coerced her into resigning. She has been
unable to find a teaching job since, the suit says.
   Ms. Dick resigned from the tenured teaching position she had held
for seven years in February after complaints from a parent that she
practiced witchcraft.
   In her lawsuit, Ms. Dick said she never practiced or believed in
witchcraft.
   But in a newspaper interview in February, Ms. Dick said she had
been hearing voices ``like Joan of Arc'' since childhood. She said
she tells fortunes, gives card readings and has warned people to get
medical treatment for otherwise undetected illnesses.
   She said her belief in psychic phenomenon does not extend to
witchcraft.
   Ms. Dick said in February that she resigned rather then fend off
speculation about her beliefs. Her attorney, James Humphrey, said
his client was never disciplined while working in North Kansas City.
   The parent's complaint stemmed from a publication, Intuitive
Directory, that listed Ms. Dick as one of several people in the
Kansas City area who practice witchcraft.
   Ms. Dick said at the time that the publication erroneously
included witchcraft along with her talents in hypnosis, meditation,
channeling and card reading.
</TEXT>
