<FIRST>r a PM-Abortion-CourtOrder 1stLd-Writethru a0544 08-31 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion-Court Order, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0544,0374</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Drops Suit Seeking to Prevent Abortion By Former Girlfriend</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RECASTS throughout to move up reason suit was dropped because
woman not believed to be pregnant. Edits to trim. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRIP DuBARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man has dropped a lawsuit seeking to keep
his ex-girlfriend from getting an abortion after learning that she
was not pregnant, his lawyer said.
   Elton K. Johnson of Columbia on Wednesday dropped his suit
against a woman publicly known as ``Jane Doe'' after learning
through a variety of sources, though not from a medical examination,
that she was not pregnant, said his attorney, Richard G. Whiting.
   The 23-year-old woman has refused to take a pregnancy test and
still will not say if she was pregnant, said the woman's attorney,
Victoria Eslinger.
   ``That is none of their business,'' she said, referring to
Johnson and his attorney.
   Eslinger said Johnson knew no more about her client's condition
Wednesday than when he undertook his court fight last week.
   ``We take the position that that is a victory,'' Ms. Eslinger
said.
   Once the suit was withdrawn, a temporary restraining order
preventing the woman from seeking an abortion became invalid.
   ``She was extremely relieved,'' Ms. Eslinger said. ``She plans to
resume her life.''
   Ms. Eslinger said a three-month relationship between her client
and Johnson ended about a month ago but Johnson, 34, wanted the
woman to carry the fetus to term, if indeed she was pregnant.
   Ms. Eslinger said she sees the suit's withdrawal as both
vindication of her belief that the Family Court did not have
jurisdiction, and affirmation of a woman's right to independently
terminate a pregnancy within the first three months.
   Steven Bates, executive director of the state chapter of the
American Civil Liberties Union, said the lawsuit appeared to be part
of an effort by anti-abortion activists to alter current law.
   ``This is guerrilla warfare by the right-to-lifers,'' Bates said.
``There is no legal basis for bringing these actions.''
   But Whiting said he felt Johnson's motives were sincere and in
the interests of the unborn child.
   ``This case was not brought for publicity reasons,'' Whiting said.
</TEXT>
