<HEAD>Marlon Brando Says Won't Make Any Movies</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: CORRECTS AP designator and category code.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CPT23</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oscar-winning actor Marlon Brando says he's made
his last movie _ and it's a dud.
   ``It's horrible,'' he said of ``The Freshman.'' ``It's going to
be a flop, but after this, I'm retiring. I'm so fed up. This
picture, except for the Canadian crew, was an extremely unpleasant
experience. I wish I hadn't finished with a stinker.''
   Brando, 65, who has been shooting the movie in Canada for the
past 12 weeks, also told the Toronto Globe and Mail on Wednesday
that he's fed up with kowtowing to the Hollywood publicity system,
detests New York and adores Canada.
   ``I didn't realize how utterly pleasant it was to be here.
   ``I've come from New York, which is a warthog straight from hell.
To sing my swan song here is very pleasant,'' said Brando, who made
his name in stage productions in the late 1940s and went on to such
as movies as ``On The Waterfront'' and ``The Godfather.''
   ``This is my last day,'' he said at the conclusion of the
lunchtime interview as he was called back to the set.
   ``Two more shots and I'm done with this madness ... You can't
imagine how happy I am.''
