<HEAD>Measles Kills 28 in West Java</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An outbreak of measles in West Java has
claimed 28 lives, all but one of them children, a newspaper reported
Thursday.
   The disease broke out in early August in three villages in
Wanaraja district, about 100 miles southeast of Jakarta, and has
afflicted at least 140 people, including the 28 who died, the daily
newspaper Pos Kota reported.
   Most of the victims were children who had never been vaccinated,
the newspaper said, quoting unidentified sources at Wanaraja's
public health center.
   The lack of clean water was the cause of the epidemic, according
to Kurnadi Sumawiganda, chief of the local health department in
Garut.
