<FIRST>r i AM-Honecker     08-31 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Honecker,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Acknowledge Honecker Recovering Slowly, Deny He Has Cancer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist officials said Thursday that Erich
Honecker was recovering ``very slowly'' from a gall-bladder
operation but denied reports the 77-year-old East German leader has
cancer.
   On Wednesday, Western media reported that Honecker's gall bladder
operation two weeks ago had to be abandoned because of the
``condition of the tissue.'' West German security sources confirmed
they had information Honecker's operation had to be abandoned
because of complications.
   The mass-circulation West German newspaper Bild, said Honecker
was ``struggling with death. He is apparently incurably sick with
cancer.
   East German officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
Thursday such assertions on cancer were ``totally unfounded.''
   They conceded, however, that Honecker's recovery was ``proceeding
very slowly.''
   Bild, which did not identify its sources, also said Honecker is
in an East Berlin hospital, receives heavy doses of pain-killing
medication and is ``hardly aware of his surroundings.''
   Western diplomatic sources in East Berlin said Honecker would not
be attending the Leipzig trade fair and all his appointments up to
the middle of September had been canceled.
   East Germany's leadership attaches enormous prestige to the
Leipzig trade fair, which begins Sunday, and Honecker traditionally
opens the biannual international event.
   Honecker underwent a gall bladder operation two weeks ago and has
not been seen in public since.
   The operation was the second time this summer Honecker was
hospitalized.
   Illness forced him to leave the Warsaw Pact summit in Bucharest
on July 8 before its conclusion, and the official East German media
later announced he was in a hospital for problems related to
gallstones.
   He was released the following week, but looked frail and tired at
a public appearance.
   Honecker has ruled the country of 16.6 million people since 1971.
He supervised the building of the Berlin Wall 10 years earlier. He
has shunned the adoption of Kremlin-style reforms, a factor in the
recent surge of refugees from East Germany to the West.
</TEXT>
