<FIRST>r i AM-Vietnam-US     08-31 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vietnam-US,0257</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Team Discuses MIA-POW Issue in Vietnam</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A team of U.S. officials met with
Vietnamese officials in Hanoi on American servicemen listed missing
or taken prisoner during the Vietnam War, a U.S. Embassy spokesman
said Thursday.
   It was the latest in a series of technical meetings to improve
cooperation between the two nations on the issue, he said. The last
was in May.
   The team spent three days in Vietnam, he said, and returned to
Bangkok Wednesday.
   The team was led by Lt. Col. Joe Harvey, commander of the Joint
Casualty Resolution Center, and included Lt. Col. Johnie Webb,
commander of the U.S. Army's Central Identification Laboratory. Both
are located in Hawaii.
   As of Aug. 24, he said, 2,340 servicemen are listed as missing.
There are 1,707 unaccounted for in Vietnam, with the rest missing in
Laos, Cambodia and China.
   On July 31, Vietnam returned 15 sets of remains believed to be
those of U.S. servicemen.
   The United States does not preclude that there are still American
prisoners left alive in Vietnam although it says it lacks firm
evidence.
   In July, President Bush said that finding out what happened to
U.S. servicemen listed missing in Southeast Asia or prisoners of war
remained a ``matter of highest national priority.''
   Bush called on Hanoi to shed light on the fate of the missing and
said that the pace of restoring diplomatic relations with Vietnam
could be impeded unless it cooperates on the POW-MIA issue.
</TEXT>
