<SECOND>AM-Deng,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foreign Ministry Says Deng in Good Health</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senior leader Deng Xiaoping, rumored to be
seriously ill, is in ``very good health,'' the Foreign Ministry said
Thursday.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Li Zhaoxiang declined comment,
however, on the whereabouts of Deng, 85, who has not been seen since
June 9.
   He said some foreign correspondents ``did concoct and spread
rumors'' about Deng's health. When asked whether Deng was dead or
alive, Li replied: ``That's a provocative question.''
   Deng's last appearance was before a gathering of military
officers whom he congratulated for their actions in the bloody
suppression of student-led pro-democracy protesters on June 3-4.
   Well-placed Chinese sources have said Deng is seriously ill with
cancer and is receiving medical treatment in Beijing.
   Premier Li Peng told the Bangladesh foreign minister last week
that Deng was resting at Beidaihe, a popular seaside resort for
Chinese leaders. Anna Chennault, a prominent Chinese-American with
ties to the Chinese leadership, said Saturday she was told by
members of Deng's family that he was in good health at Beidaihe.
   Although Deng has retired from all his official posts except head
of the Central Military Commission, he is still regarded as the
ultimate source of power in the inner circles of Chinese leadership.
   His death could open the way for a power struggle between
factions, particularly between the conservatives wielding power and
reformers who have been on the retreat since the military crackdown.
</TEXT>
