<FIRST>r a PM-Drownings     08-31 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drownings,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Testifies Husband's Leg Cramp Caused Accident In Which Children
Died</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WYANDOTTE, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman testified today that her husband
tried to take his foot off the accelerator as the family car crashed
through a barrier and into the Detroit River, where the couple's
four children drowned.
   The preliminary hearing for Lawrence DeLisle, 28, is to determine
whether he will stand trial in Circuit Court on four counts of
first-degree murder and one count of attempting to murder his wife
in the Aug. 3 car wreck.
   Suzanne DeLisle, 32, testified that her husband complained of leg
cramps as the family rode, but declined her offer to drive. She said
the cramp worsened, and she watched her husband vainly try to pull
his leg off the pedal and steer the car away from the river.
   The car rammed through a barrier, flipped over and landed on its
top in the river bottom, drowning Bryan, 8, Melissa, 4, Kathryn, 2,
and Emily, 8 months. Lawrence and Suzanne DeLisle escaped from the
car and were rescued when passing boaters tossed them life
preservers.
   DeLisle was charged in the deaths a week later, after police said
he confessed to driving into the river to try to rid himself of
family and financial burdens. He has been jailed without bond since
Aug. 10.
   Mrs. DeLisle has said previously she believes her husband to be
innocent and that police coerced his confession.

</TEXT>
