<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Dalitz     08-31 0199</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Dalitz,0205</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nevada Gaming, Business Pioneer Morris `Moe' Dalitz Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Morris ``Moe'' Dalitz, a gaming pioneer who
helped develop several major Las Vegas casinos but was later dogged
by his early ties to organized crime, died early today. He was 89
and had been ill for some time.
   Dalitz was born near Boston and he and his brothers operated a
chain of cleaners in Detroit and Cleveland. Shortly after coming to
Las Vegas in 1949, he acquired an ownership interest in the Desert
Inn and Stardust hotels.
   In the early 1950s he joined partners to form Paradise
Development Co., which built the city's convention center, a major
hospital and shopping center and several buildings at the University
of Nevada-Las Vegas.
   Dalitz recently was involved in the development of the Fitzgerald
hotel-casino, but he never applied for a gaming license there
because of concerns over past crime ties.
   He was listed in a 1978 California attorney general's report on
organized crime, but was never accused of a crime.
   In later years Dalitz was known as a philanthropist and received
the 1976 Humanitarian Award from the American Cancer Research Center
and Hospital.
   Funeral services were pending.
</TEXT>
