<FIRST>u a PM-BridgeCollapse 2ndLd-Writethru a0525 08-31 0455</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bridge Collapse, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0525,0464</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bridge Collapses on Baltimore-Washington Parkway; 14 Injured</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with no one else believed trapped, quote
from governor, other detail, and to CORRECT time of accident to 6:30 a.m.
sted 7, reflecting official change. No pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos ANCX1,2, WX8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATTY REINERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAUREL, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bridge being built over a major roadway
collapsed during rush hour this morning, raining debris on commuters
and injuring 14 people, state police said.
   One woman was in critical condition after the collapse of the
Route 198 overpass over the Baltimore-Washington Parkway, which came
about 6:30 a.m. while workers were pouring concrete, police said.
   U.S. Park Police Deputy Chief Richard Kusick said four of the
injured were in a car that was crushed under the overpass. Another
was in a second car that was hit by debris, while the other nine
were construction workers.
   Rescue and construction workers drilled holes into the pile of
rubble and carried away debris a piece at a time searching for other
vehicles that may have been trapped. By midday, however, officials
concluded no one else was in the rubble, and heavy equipment was
brought in to clean it up.
   The critically injured woman was taken by helicopter to the
University of Maryland Shock Trauma Center in Baltimore, said state
police spokesman Sgt. Joseph Ireton. The others were taken to
various hospitals, he said.
   State police spokesman Chuck Jackson said the collapse caused
tremendous traffic backups. The southbound parkway was closed at
Route 32, and traffic was being detoured around the area.
   Maryland police, U.S. Park Police and rescue teams from Anne
Arundel, Howard and Prince George's Counties were dispatched to the
scene, along with at least two Medevac helicopters and two rescue
buses.
   Gov. William Donald Schaefer said he expected the roadway to be
opened within 24 hours.
   ``Everyone's question is why, but it's impossible to tell,''
Schaefer said. ``There is no way in the world I could tell what
happened here.''
   Investigators from the Maryland Safety and Health Administration
were on the scene. Gene McCormick, deputy administrator for the
Federal Highway Administration, said an independent investigator
would also be brought in.
   The workers had poured about 120 cubic yards, or 200 tons, of
concrete and were about two-thirds of the way through when the
bridge collapsed in the middle, McCormick said. They began pouring
concrete at 2 a.m. and were being watched by federal inspectors.
   ``The foreman said he heard a clanging or a clunk just before the
bridge collapsed, but there was really no warning,'' McCormick said.
   He said the supports for the molds into which the concrete was
being poured had been inspected and approved in early July.

</TEXT>
