<HEAD>Ng Moves Step Closer to Extradition to California</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS lead to show 12 murder charges sted 13.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court of Canada refused on Thursday to
hear the case of Charles Ng, moving the former U.S. Marine a step
closer to extradition to California to face 12 murder charges.
   Ng can still appeal directly to Justice Minister Doug Lewis, who
has the power to block extradition for any prisoner facing the death
penalty.
   Ng, 28, a native of Hong Kong who was educated in Britian, is
charged with murder, kidnapping and burglary in the deaths of 12
men, women and children.
   Eleven deaths involved sex slayings at a cabin 120 miles east of
San Francisco. The 12th involved the slaying of a San Francisco disc
jockey.
   Ng is serving a 4{-year sentence for shooting a security guard in
the hand in a bungled shoplifting attempt in Calgary in 1985.
