<FIRST>r w AM-Census-Families     08-31 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Census-Families,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>For release at 6:30 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Stepparent Families Up Sharply</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of American children living with
stepparents has risen sharply, as women have children before
marriage and parents change spouses, the Census Bureau reported
Thursday.
   The number of children under age 18 living with a stepparent
jumped 11.6 percent between 1980 and 1985, increasing from 6,082,000
to 6,789,000, the bureau reported.
   During the same period the number of children in biological
families, that is, children living with both their natural parents,
slipped from 39.5 million to 37.2 million.
   The findings on stepchildren were reported Thursday in ``Studies
in Marriage and the Family,'' the first of a new series of special
topical studies to be issued by the agency.
   The report contains sections on unmarrieds, single parents and
married couple families. It summarizes information issued previously
by the bureau, bringing together statistics on related topics in a
single publication.
   The rise in stepchildren has occurred during a period when more
divorces were occurring, giving rise to second marriages.
   For there to be a stepchild in a family, at least one of the
parents had to be married twice or the mother had to have a birth
prior to her first marriage, the report observed.
   As of 1985, the bureau found, 4,469,000 married couples included
stepchildren in their families. Of these 2,387,000 included only
stepchildren, while 2,082,000 families included both stepchildren
and biological children of that couple.
   For stepchildren, the vast majority lived with their biological
mother and a stepfather. Only 10.9 percent in 1985 were living with
the biological father and a stepmother.
   Other detail reported in the new compilation included:
   _The share of Americans aged 18 and over who are single increased
from 28 percent in 1970 to 37 percent in 1988.
   _The median age at first marriage was 25.9 for men and 23.6 for
women in 1988. By comparison it was 22.8 for men and 20.3 for women
in 1960.
   _As of 1988, 10.1 percent of all adults who had ever been married
were divorced, up from 3.8 percent in 1970.
   _The number of unmarried couples living together rose from
523,000 in 1970 to 2.6 million in 1988.
   _Between 1970 and 1988 the number of single parents climbed from
3.8 million to 9.4 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
