<FIRST>r w AM-FlagAmendment     08-31 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flag Amendment,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Legion Says Says 1 Million Sign Flag Desecretion Petition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Legion said Thursday it has
received about 1 million signatures on a petition seeking a
constitutional amendment against desecration of the American flag.
   Senate Republican Leader Robert Dole of Kansas, appearing at a
press conference with American Legion national commander H.F.
Gierke, said legislation calling for the amendment has been
scheduled for Senate floor action Oct. 16.
   The House will consider a bill Sept. 12 that would create a
federal law against flag desecration, but not amend the Constitution.
   ``It's a long process,'' Dole said of the amendment route, which
requires approval by two-thirds of the House and Senate and
ratification by three-fourths of the states.
   But, he said, the issue was one that deserved consideration by
the states.
   Gierke said that the legion was getting about 40,000 signatures a
day in its nationwide petition drive, which still goes on.
   ``The constitutional process requires constitutional assurances
we'll do the right thing,'' said Sen. John Warner, R-Va., who also
appeared at the news conference.
   Proponents of the amendment say it, rather than a statute, is
needed so that the Supreme Court will not rule the prohibition
unconstitutional. Earlier this year, the court touched off the
controversy by deciding that burning the flag was a constitutionally
protected form of political protest.
   Many lawmakers and constitutional law experts oppose the
amendment, saying that while emotionally offensive, flag-burning is
not a serious enough offense to merit curtailment of free-speech
protections.
   The House bill includes penalties of up to a year in prison plus
an unspecified fine for physically desecrating a flag, and was
drafted to address the high court's decision that existing statutes
against flag burning were an attempt to squelch free speech.
   Reps. Gerald Solomon, R-N.Y., and Chuck Douglas, R-N.H., who also
attended the news conference, said the fight in the House for an
amendment would be much tougher than in the Senate.
   House Majority Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., has said the
Democrats want to try a statute before a constitutional amendment to
avoid ``adding political graffiti to the Constitution.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
