<FIRST>r a AM-Marijuana-Teacher     08-31 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Marijuana-Teacher,0439</SECOND>
<HEAD>School Official Says Acquitted Teacher Won't Get Job Back</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLIOTT MINOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOULTRIE, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The local Teacher of the Year can't have her
job back despite her acquittal on charges of growing marijuana in
her back yard because she knew her husband smoked pot, the school
superintendent said Thursday.
   Vicki Sherling was fired after her arrest in May on charges she
helped her husband grow marijuana in a vine-covered greenhouse. She
could have received up to 11 years in prison but was found innocent
by a jury Wednesday.
   After the trial, Mrs. Sherling said she felt vindicated and would
try to return to the classroom. But Colquitt County Superintendent
Billy Mock said he has no plans to rehire the former high school
chemistry teacher.
   Mock said she was fired for immorality for allowing her husband
to use marijuana. He said the county School Board did not consider
whether she was involved in possessing or growing marijuana.
   ``She admitted in our hearing that she knew it was going on, that
it was being used,'' he said.
   Mrs. Sherling, 38, who was named Colquitt County's 1989 Teacher
of the Year, said Thursday she is appealing her dismissal to the
state Board of Education.
   ``I feel great that finally the truth got out and I have cleared
my name, which was my intent,'' she said. ``I had the truth on my
side.''
   Mrs. Sherling and her husband, Michael, were arrested May 19 when
drug agents, acting on a tip, found 22 small marijuana plants
growing in their greenhouse and drug paraphernalia in their house.
   Sherling, a former teacher and lawyer, admitted chronic marijuana
use and pleaded guilty to drug charges. He is awaiting sentencing.
   At her trial Wednesday, Mrs. Sherling testified she first learned
of the marijuana in the greenhouse when she returned home and found
her house full of drug agents and her husband in handcuffs.
   ``I felt betrayed by my husband because he had grown marijuana in
my back yard,'' she said.
   Mrs. Sherling denied ever smoking or knowingly possessing
marijuana and said her husband's use of it had been the only source
of trouble in their 16-year marriage. They have two sons.
   Mrs. Sherling testified she had pleaded with her husband to stop
smoking pot.
   ``I don't know how often he smoked,'' she said. ``We have argued
about this since our marriage. I have used every argument I could. I
said, `Mike, it is illegal.' I said, `Mike we have children. What if
they find it?'''
</TEXT>
