<HEAD>Pentagon Readies Equipment for Colombia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon hopes to begin sending equipment
to Colombia on Sunday under President Bush's $65 million military
aid package to help the Bogota government fight drug traffickers,
spokesman Pete Williams said Thursday.
   Williams said a small group of Defense Department personnel were
to arrive Friday in Colombia to begin logistical preparations for
the equipment, which will include aircraft, weapons, communications
gear and medical supplies all in stock at government warehouses.
   Williams said 200 American military personnel would be involved
in operations in Colombia ranging from training to unloading.
   Williams said he was not certain the shipments would begin Sunday
because the final list of goods had not been completed.
   The spokesman said two C-130B medium range cargo planes requested
by the Colombians would be among the first shipments of goods to be
sent.
   Bush announced the aid package on Aug. 25. It followed the murder
of a presidential hopeful in Colombia and the Bogota government's
unprecedented crackdown on drug traffickers.
