<FIRST>r a AM-WhoopingCranes     08-31 0201</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Whooping Cranes,0207</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Wildlife Officials to Split Whooping Crane Colony</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAUREL, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wildlife officials will split the only captive
colony of endangered whooping cranes to reduce the chances of
disease or disaster wiping out the flock.
   The U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service said this week that 22 of the
54 birds at the Patuxent Wildlife Research Center will be sent in
November to the International Crane Foundation in Baraboo, Wis.
   ``The service has been concerned about having all of their eggs
in one basket, literally,'' David Trauger, the Patuxent center's
deputy director.
   ``The service felt it was the prudent thing to do, to separate
the breeding flocks, and there's enough breeders now to do that.''
   The center started in 1987 to breed the rare birds, known for
their elaborate courtship dance, under a joint program with Canadian
wildlife officials.
   A wild flock of the cranes migrates to Texas for the winter from
Canada, 2,400 miles away. This year, 138 made the migration. Before
conservation efforts began, there were only 21 whooping cranes in
Texas in the winter.
   Scientists hope that by breeding whooping cranes in captivity,
they will be able to establish another flock in the wild.
</TEXT>
