<FIRST>r w AM-Homeless-Election     08-31 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Homeless-Election,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Election Weighed in Reagan Administration Homeless Decision</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Reagan administration official last year
urged repeal of a program to assist the homeless, but several
Department of Health and Human Services officials warned against
such a move in an election year, according to documents released
Thursday.
   ``Such an effort would undoubtedly be unsuccessful and could
unfortunately be interpreted as a lack of in interest in the plight
of the homeless by this department, thus subjecting the secretary
and the administration to strong criticism of a politically
sensitive and visible issue during an election year,'' one
Department of Health and Human Services official wrote in response
to the recommendation from then Social Security Commissioner Dorcas
Hardy.
   In that memo, Robert Docksai, then the department's assistant
secretary for legislation, also warned that it would be
``politically untenable'' to attempt to repeal the program, under
which the government was to fund efforts to screen the homeless
population for people eligible for Social Security.
   The memo in which Hardy made the recommendation to then-HHS
Secretary Otis Bowen and a number of subsequent internal HHS memos
discussing the idea were released by the National Law Center on
Homelessness and Poverty, which had criticized the Reagan
administration for not implementing the program.
   The documents show that while several HHS officials appeared to
agree with Hardy's recommendation, they did not believe Congress
would agree to the repeal and also suspected that even suggesting
such a move would hurt the GOP in last year's presidential election.
The law center obtained the documents under the Freedom of
Information Act.
   ``We agree that the department should not seek an appropriation
for the program,'' Assistant Secretary for Health Steven A. Grossman
wrote in an April 1988 memo. ``However, if we actively work to
repeal the legislation, the administration risks being portrayed as
uncaring for the homeless. Since nothing is happening at the moment,
silence seems the best policy given the politics of homeless
issues.''
   In a letter to Bush administration HHS Secretary Louis Sullivan,
the advocacy group said the program still has not been funded.
   ``This policy is reprehensible; it is also illegal,'' Maria
Foscarinis of the law center said in the letter to Sullivan. ``I ask
that you reverse this policy by implementing the outreach program at
once.''
   A Sullivan spokesman did not immediately return a telephone
message left Thursday.
   The program was authorized by Congress in 1987. It was designed
to create an HHS-administered pilot program under which the federal
government would provide money to state and local governments that
established teams to identify homeless people potentially eligible
for Social Security benefits. Congress authorized $3.75 million for
the program and said up to $1 million should be taken from Social
Security Administration surplus funds to pay for implementation of
the program.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
