<FIRST>r i AM-Philippines-Awards     08-31 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-Awards,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Five Winners Receive Magsaysay Awards</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American Jesuit priest who was
jailed by Ferdinand Marcos for criticizing the government said
Thursday the church's greatest recent achievement was helping oust
the former president.
   The Rev. James Bertram Reuter Jr., made the remarks during
ceremonies at which he was awarded the 1989 Ramon Magsaysay Prize
for journalism, literature and creative communications arts.
   A Malaysian, an Indian, a South Korean and a technological school
in Thailand also were honored by the Magsaysay Foundation.
   The awards were presented Thursday by the Foundation on the 82nd
birthday of the late President Ramon Magsaysay Jr.
   ``The most spectacular contribution of the Church to the world in
recent years, through media, was EDSA,'' said Reuter, referring to a
highway where mutinous soldiers took control of the military's
headquarters to start a four-day revolt that toppled Marcos and
propelled Corazon Aquino to the presidency.
   ``It was the first revolution in history to be run by radio,''
Reuter added. He said the Roman Catholic Church led by Manila's
Archbishop Cardinal Jaime Sin called on the people to march in the
streets as a sign of support for the rebellious soldiers.
   Sin's call was made over the church's radio station Veritas.
Troops loyal to Marcos destroyed the Church's transmitter but the
radio station continued airing information about the revolt using
another radio station.
   ``It was an accident of history that the Church was in position
at that time,'' Reuter said. ``we had the equipment. We had the
personnel. We had the organization. And we had the courage to do
it.''
   Reuter, who has lived in the Philippines for more than 40 years,
ran a weekly newsletter that had been critical of Marcos rule. When
martial law was declared in 1972, the newspaper was closed and he
was placed under house arrest for two years.
   The other winners were Zakiah Hanum binti Abdul Hamid of Malaysia
for government service, Sri Lakshmi Chand Jain of India for public
service, Kim Im-soon of South Korea for community leadership, and
the Asian Institute of Technology, based in Thailand.
   Each winner received a gold medallion, a scroll and $30,000.
</TEXT>
