<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-89 2006EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Pilots     08-31 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pilots,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pilot's License Now Easier to Obtain, Despite Objections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New regulations designed to make it easier and
less expensive to learn to fly went into effect Thursday over the
objections of federal air safety regulators and the Air Line Pilots
Association.
   The new rule would permit issuance of a so-called recreational
pilot's license after only 30 hours of flight instruction, compared
with the 40 required for a regular license.
   The recreational license will permit pilots to fly only within 50
miles of the airport where they learned to fly. They may fly only in
the daytime and in clear weather and may not use airports with
traffic control towers.
   ``We are hoping this is going to provide a stepping stone,'' said
John Leyden, a spokesman for the Federal Aviation Administration.
``People are going to get into aviation as a result of this, because
it is going to be less expensive.''
   Leyden said the FAA hopes many of them will then go on to get a
regular pilot's certificate, helping to fill a growing shortage of
airline pilots.
   John Lauber, a member of the National Transportation Safety
Board, said the board has long opposed the new license.
   ``I am in sympathy with the problem we have of getting more
people involved in aviation,'' Lauber said. ``It's just that I'm not
convinced that that's the right way to go about it.''
   ``I do wonder how they can adequately enforce the many
restrictions that have been put on,'' he said.
   The new rule was first proposed in 1979.
   The FAA estimates it will reduce the cost of learning to fly by
as much as 39 percent, from about $3,000 to less than $2,000.
   The license will limit the pilot to planes with no more than four
seats and 180-horsepower engines.
   John O'Brien, director of engineering and air safety for the Air
Line Pilots Association, said the association plans to renew its
objections to the new rule, which is still subject to revision.
   ``It does cost an awful lot for a young person coming up through
the ranks to try to get a private pilot's license today,'' O'Brien
said. ``And if there is any means of reducing the cost of that
license, then we might provide more pilots and a larger demand for
airlines and a larger group of pilots for the airlines to select
from.''
   ``This seems to make sense, except that by getting a recreational
license you certainly aren't getting the kind of training necessary
to go on to flying with the airlines or making yourself a good,
safe, sane pilot,'' he said.
</TEXT>
