<FIRST>u i AM-Vatican-Lebanon     08-31 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vatican-Lebanon,0307</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vatican Silent on Papal Trip to Lebanon</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Lebanon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Vatican has remained silent this week on
the possibility of a trip by Pope John Paul II to Lebanon, while
apparently keeping up diplomatic efforts to arrange such a mission.
   Vatican spokesman Joaquin Navarro told reporters on Aug. 25 that
``different practical possibilities are being studied so that this
desire of the pope can be carried out'' and contacts were under way
``on different levels.''
   Since then, Navarro and other Vatican officials have declined to
elaborate on the statement.
   The pontiff first said Aug. 15 that he wanted to go to Lebanon to
pray for peace there.
   But several obstacles have cropped up to a possible papal trip,
including a recommendation by the pro-Iranian leader of Lebanon's
fundamentalist Sunni Moslems that the pontiff be kidnapped.
   A previously unknown Islamic organization also threatened in
Beirut Monday to kill John Paul if he visited Lebanon.
   John Paul has frequently expressed anguish in recent weeks about
the six-month battle between Christian troops and Syrian-led forces
including Lebanese Moslems. The fighting has claimed more than 810
lives.
   On Wednesday, during his weekly general audience, the pontiff
appealed once again for prayers for peace in Lebanon.
   Vatican media have also been quiet on a possible papal peace
mission since Sunday, when the director of the Vatican daily
L'Osservatore Romano defended such a trip in a front-page commentary.
   ``Certainly, those who carry out politics only with the criteria
of craftiness and slyness can't understand the logic of care and the
most deeply felt testimony (of the pope),'' wrote director Mario
Agnes.
   He did not say who he was referring to.
   Some Lebanese political figures have said a papal visit would
express support for Lebanese Christians.
</TEXT>
