<FIRST>r w AM-Obit-Schakne     08-31 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Schakne,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Veteran CBS Newsman Robert Schakne Dies at 63</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emmy award-winning CBS newsman Robert Schakne,
who covered civil rights, war, political scandal and revolution
during a 39-year career, died Thursday of cancer, CBS News said. He
was 63.
   Schakne, who died at Sibley Hospital here, worked at CBS for 33
years, covering such major stories as the Iran-Contra arms and money
scandal, the Watergate trials, the investigation of the Challenger
space shuttle disaster and the Vietnam War.
   He won a national Emmy for his reporting on the grand jury
investigation of former Vice President Spiro Agnew and his
resignation from office.
   ``For decades, Bob Schakne set the highest standards in our
profession,'' said David Burke, president of CBS News. ``He was a
sensitive man with great class and intelligence, and the people of
CBS News are indebted to him for his enormous contributions and
achievements.''
   Howard Stringer, president, CBS@Broadcast Group, called Schakne
``a reporter's reporter _ dogged in pursuit of the truth and
committed to the craft of careful reporting. His professionalism,
his precision and, perhaps above all, his integrity, will be long
remembered and treasured at CBS.''
   Prior to joining CBS, Schakne was employed by the Chicago bureau
of International News Service in 1949. He covered the Korean War for
INS from 1950-53 and later became chief of the INS Tokyo bureau.
   Schakne went to CBS News in 1955 as a writer in the New York
bureau. From 1957 to 1961 he covered the civil rights movement and
he became a CBS News correspondent in 1961. He was transferred to
the Los Angeles bureau in 1962 and became West Coast bureau manager
briefly before being named Latin American correspondent in 1964.
   He was based in New York from 1966 to 1976, where he covered New
York's fiscal crisis, the trials of Watergate figures John Mitchell
and Maurice Stans and the Agnew investigation. He covered campus
unrest in the late 1960s from Columbia to Kent State to Berkeley.
   He also reported on Latin America during the early and mid-1970s,
including Juan Peron's return to power in Argentina, Salvador
Allende's election in Chile and fugitive Robert Vesco in the Bahamas.
   Schakne had been down a Bolivian tin mine and up 15,000 feet in
the Andes, and he witnessed revolutions in Brazil, Bolivia, the
Dominican Republic, Argentina and Ecuador. He covered Vietnam from
September 1967 through the Tet offensive in January 1968, and in
1968 reported on the return of the U.S.S. Pueblo crew at Panmunjon,
Korea.
   He was the recipient of the Sigma Delta Chi Distinguished Service
Award for his coverage of the Attica State Prison riots in September
1971.
   He retired from CBS in July 1988.
   Schakne was born in New York City on Aug. 19, 1926. He attended
the University of Chicago, where he majored in political science.
   He is survived by his wife, Toshiye Schakne, of Washington; a
daughter, Miye, of Anchorage; and a sister, Ann Harris, of New York.
   A memorial service was tentatively scheduled for Tuesday in
Washington.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
