<FIRST>u a AM-Bush-Alaska     08-31 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Alaska,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Won't Visit Alaska, Aide Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush has scrapped plans to
go next month to Alaska, still embroiled in controversy over the
Exxon Valdez oil spill, officials said Thursday.
   Bush's trip, which never was finalized or officially announced,
would have been part of a mid-September swing to Montana, South
Dakota and Washington. The trip may be rescheduled for the spring,
officials said.,
   There were various reasons voiced privately by administration
officials on why the Alaska trip was dropped.
   Chief of staff John Sununu told reporers covering the president's
vacation here that logistical problems and weather conditions caused
the cancellation. He said there was a possibility it could be
rescheduled for the spring.
   But another official said the main reason for dropping the trip
was a feeling that Bush already had a full schedule for September,
with several important policy issues, and that the Alaska trip would
not do him any good politically.
   ``Something had to give, in what was already shaping up to be a
busy month,'' said one official who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Two officials denied that weather and logistics were the reason
for the cancellation, as indicated by Sununu in his public
statements.
   The purpose of going to Alaska would have been to examine the
progress of the cleaup of the 11-million-gallon spill from the Exxon
Valdez tanker on March 24.
   The spill swept masses of gooey oil on the once pristine beaches
along Prince William Sound.
   Bush was said to be very intent on going, sources said.
   But one source said other officials prevailed with advice that it
would could do him no good to refocus attention on the Valdez oil
spill.
   Bush was criticized in the aftermath of the spill for not moving
quickly enough to get the federal government involved in the cleanup.
   Initially administration officials said the Exxon's cleanup
efforts were satisfactory. But eventually, Bush said those efforts
had been inadequate and ordered U.S. military personnel to assist in
the cleanup.
   Winter weather conditions are the reason also given for Exxon's
decision to shut down its cleanup efforts in mid-September.
   Environmentalists have criticized the pullout plan, contending
some aspects of the effort could continue.
   Critics also are blasting a government plan calling for all
studies on damage caused by the spill to be completed by Feburary.
   Environmentalists say the plan could lead to a serious
under-estimation of harm to the environment and a limited recovery
of damages from Exxon.
   Bush has a heavy legislative calendar in September, and is trying
to focus attention on his drug strategy which he unveils on Tuesday.
He also has called a two-day education summit with all the nation's
governors and will take trips to New Jersy, Boston, the United
Nations in New York and Annapolis, Md.
</TEXT>
