<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru   08-31 0815</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0591,0837</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fundamentalist Leader Says Pope Should Be Kidnapped</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE casualties; picks up 4th pvs, `Ad-Diyar
quoted...' Minor editing thereafter to conform and trim.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BEI1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pro-Iranian leader of fundamentalist
Sunni Moslems was quoted Thursday as saying Pope John Paul II should
be kidnapped if he visits Lebanon's besieged Christians.
   Sheik Said Shaaban also recommended President Bush and President
Francois Mitterrand of France be abducted as a means of ending
support for Lebanese Christians and for Israel, the Beirut daily
Ad-Diyar reported.
   Seven people were killed in artillery and rocket exchanges
between Syrian and Christian soldiers, including a 27-year-old woman
who burned to death in an apartment set ablaze by shellfire, police
reported. They said at least 36 people were wounded.
   By police count, 812 people have been killed and 2,354 wounded,
nearly all of them civilians, in the artillery war that began March
8 between Gen. Michel Aoun's Christian army command and a Moslem
alliance led by the 40,000 Syrian troops stationed in Lebanon.
   A mediation mission by French envoy Francois Scheer appeared to
have collapsed, raising fears of intensified fighting.
   An artillery round hit the second-floor apartment of Mustafa
Najjar, 33, a sound technician with the British television agency
Visnews. Neighbors said he carried his 8-year-old daughter and
7-year-old son down the stairs, but returned to find the charred
body of his wife, Amal, lying in the flames.
   Ad-Diyar quoted Shaaban as saying in an interview: ``If the pope
comes to Lebanon and we manage to hold him for the sake of salvaging
Palestine, I wouldn't be against such an act.
   ``It is our duty to abduct all those related to states that
recognize Israel. Every citizen of a foreign state that recognizes
Israel should be a hostage in our hand.
   ``I support the abduction of Bush and ... Mitterrand to serve the
purpose of ousting Israel from Palestine and stopping the French
intervention (in Lebanon) and the naval warships that have come to
rescue France's children in Lebanon.''
   Although Shaaban is a Sunni, he supports the radical Shiite
Moslem goal of an Iran-style Islamic repubic in Lebanon and has made
several trips to Tehran.
   His reference was to six French warships in the eastern
Mediterranean. France, which governed Lebanon by mandate until 1943,
says the ships are on a ``humanitarian'' mission, to evacuate the
7,000 French citizens in Lebanon if necessary.
   Shaaban's talk of abduction was the most overt threat to John
Paul since he expressed a desire Aug. 19 to visit Lebanon and help
end the 14-year-old sectarian civil war, which has killed more than
150,000 people. Iran has advised him to stay away.
   Threatening to kidnap the pope may seem farfetched, but Shiite
zealots loyal to Iran carried out suicide bombings against American,
French and Israeli forces in Lebanon in 1983-85 and have kidnapped
scores of Westerners. Sixteen Western hostages, including eight
Americans, still are held.
   Police said Syrian artillery deployed in Moslem west Beirut and
the mountains south and east of the capital hit the Christian
enclave with up to 20 shells a minute Thursday.
   They said scores of 240mm and 180mm mortar rounds exploded at and
around the hilltop presidential palace in Baabda, a Christian suburb
east of Beirut.
   Aoun's command bunker is under the palace, a regular target of
Syrian fire. His 155mm howitzers fired on Syrian positions along the
sectarian dividing line in Beirut, the seafront boulevards of west
Beirut and the wooded Aramoun hills southeast of the capital, police
said.
   One salvo landed at the Khaldeh junction, which is south of
Beirut on the coastal highway linking the Syrian-controlled sector
of the city with the rest of Lebanon. Syrian soldiers scrambled from
sandbagged checkpoints and dived into foxholes along the seafront.
   Dozens of apartment buildings on both sides of the city were set
afire and burned out of control because the shellfire kept
firefighters from reaching them.
   Ad-Diyar said the shelling increased because Scheer's mediation
effort foundered on differences about halting arms supplies to the
rival factions.
   Aoun wants international guarantees that Syria would stop arming
its allies. Syria wants an inter-Lebanese committee to make sure
ships bound for Christian ports do not carry weapons and ammunition
for the Christians.
   Iraq, an Arab enemy of Syria, is Aoun's main arms supplier.
   Scheer ended two days of talks with Lebanese leaders Wednesday
and is expected to visit Saudi Arabia, Morocco and Algeria.
   An Arab League summit in May appointed the leaders of those three
nations _ King Fahd, King Hassan II and President Chadli Bendjedid _
to find a solution to the Lebanese crisis by November. They
announced July 28 that their efforts were stymied, blaming Syria's
refusal to withdraw its soldiers.
   Syrian troops are in Lebanon under an Arab League peacekeeping
mandate issued in 1976.
</TEXT>
