<FIRST>r w AM-Poindexter     08-31 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poindexter,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Hearing Set for Poindexter in Iran-Contra Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The judge in John M. Poindexter's Iran-Contra
case Thursday ordered a hearing on whether the former national
security adviser may introduce evidence that covert aid to
Nicaraguan rebels was legal.
   U.S. District Judge Harold Greene scheduled a Sept. 6 hearing to
discuss whether there was valid evidence that Poindexter could use
to defend the charge that he obstructed congressional inquiries into
whether National Security Council aide Oliver L. North was secretly
helping arm the Nicaraguan Contras.
   Poindexter is accused of obstructing Congress in August 1986 by
assuring three House committees in letters that the National
Security Council was observing ``the spirit as well as the letter''
of a ban on U.S. military assistance to the anti-Sandinista rebels.
   Greene said he wanted to determine if Poindexter should be given
a chance to prove he had no motive to conceal North's activities by
showing they were ``legal, authorized, or known throughout the
government.''
   At issue is whether any knowledge of the activities by President
Reagan or other government officals could be presented as evidence
that Poindexter thought the National Security Council was following
the law.
   Greene said he would also hear arguments on whether the existence
of other covert operations by the Reagan administration could also
be cited as evidence that Poindexter thought North's activities in
support of the Contras did not violate the congressional ban.
   No date has been set for the trial of Poindexter, who is also
accused of lying and helping devise a false chronology of U.S.-Iran
arms sales in November 1986 when Congress began its investigation of
the Iran-Contra affair.
</TEXT>
