<FIRST>r a AM-Child-Kennel     08-31 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Child-Kennel,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Authorities Charge Grandparents Of 4-Year-Old In Pen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MUSKOGEE, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A couple kept their 4-year-old grandson in
a filthy, outdoor pen next to dog kennels for most of each day with
a bottle of water and no access to a toilet, authorities charged
Thursday.
   ``He looked like a caged kid, a wild kid that had been caged up
and you'd find out in the woods somewhere living with the animals,''
said police Cpl. Jim Doty.
   District Attorney Drew Edmondson filed a misdemeanor charge of
``omitting to provide'' against Joyce and Gene White. The charge,
usually filed in cases of failure to pay child support, carries a
year in jail or a $500 fine.
   Mrs. White said her grandson was kept in the pen to keep him from
running onto a highway. She said he was safe there and kept cool
under large trees.
   Investigators said the boy appeared to be well-nourished and had
no apparent injuries. But Edmondson said, ``If the pen were
sanitary, if you were talking about an outdoor play pen, that might
be reasonable.''
   Edmondson said the boy was confined to the 100-square-foot pen
from morning until night. He said the boy used a corner of the pen
as a toilet and had a dirty baby bottle of water to drink. The pen
is next to a kennel with dozens of dogs.
   The boy was ``filthy from head to toe,'' said sheriff's Deputy
Patrick Howland.
   The boy, an 11-year-old cousin and the Whites' 13-year-old
daughter were taken into custody Tuesday by the state. Child welfare
investigators will hold a hearing to determine if the children
should be returned to the home or placed in temporary custody
elsewhere.
   The Whites and the children have been living in a motor home at a
site where the Whites are trying to start a commercial kennel,
officials said.
   Howland said the boy's mother left him with the grandparents when
he was 2, and the boy's father apparently works in another city.
</TEXT>
