<FIRST>u i AM-Egypt-Libya     08-31 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Egypt-Libya,0496</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mubarak Sends Envoy to Libya as Thaw Continues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAURICE GUINDI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Hosni Mubarak sent a top-level
envoy to Libya Thursday in a cautious new step toward reconciling
one of the Arab world's bitterest conflicts.
   However, Mubarak's decision to send an envoy to celebrate Col.
Moammar Gadhafi's 20th anniversary in power _ and not attend himself
_ indicated the Egyptian leader remains unwilling to forget more
than a decade's conflict with his western neighbor.
   Government sources say this wariness is due largely to Gadhafi's
frequent changes of mood toward Egypt.
   The current rapprochement began in May, when fellow Arabs enticed
Gadhafi to sit with Mubarak at an Arab League summit. They hugged,
then met privately for several hours.
   Since then, their desert border has been reopened and air service
between the countries restored. Each has ended invective against the
other.
   But they still have no diplomatic relations, and Egypt is waiting
for Gadhafi to restore relations he ruptured in 1978 after Mubarak's
predecessor, Anwar Sadat, began peace talks with Israel.
   Gadhafi's invitation to Mubarak to attend the anniversary
celebrations of the coup in which Gadhafi ousted King Idris is
itself progress.
   Mubarak's acceptance was another step forward.
   He designated as his representative Deputy Prime Minister Youssef
Waly. Waly, who flew Thursday to Tripoli, is the most senior
Egyptian official to visit Libya since 1977 when the two countries
fought a five-day border war.
   Tripoli fell out with Egypt in 1972 when Sadat spurned Gadhafi's
proposal to merge their countries. Relations deteriorated as Sadat
pursued his peace policy and rapprochement with the United States.
   Egypt blamed Gadhafi for bombings in Cairo, Alexandria and other
cities in 1975 and 1976, which led to the war.
   Since Mubarak took office in 1981, Gadhafi envoys have embarked
on more than a dozen futile secret missions to Egypt. Mubarak
publicly said they always brought expressions of friendship, yet
each trip was followed by hostile Libyan actions.
   That was before this spring's summit in Casablanca, Morocco. On
May 23, Mubarak and Gadhafi met there and agreed to bury the hatchet.
   About relations with Libya, Mubarak told the Yugoslav news agency
Tanjug in an interview published Thursday: ``They are improving
steadily. There is no problem there.'' He added embassy buildings in
the respective capitals ``are being prepared,'' but did not say when
he expects resumed diplomatic relations.
   A senior government official, who demanded anonymity, said Waly's
trip ``underlines the two countries' common desire to reinforce and
normalize relations.''
   But on restoring diplomatic ties, he said: ``It's up to Libya.''
   Syria and Libya are the only two to hold out among 17 Arab states
that broke with Egypt between December 1978 and the following April
because of the treaty with Israel. Cairo exchanged ambassadors with
the other 15 after a November 1987 Arab summit gave its approval.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
