<DOCNO> AP890831-0145 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-89 1735EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Poland     08-31 0758</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland,0783</SECOND>
<HEAD>Much To Celebrate On Solidarity's Ninth Anniversary</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto GDA50</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GDANSK, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 10,000 Poles roared their
applause as Lech Walesa joined them Thursday to celebrate the ninth
anniversary of the birth of Solidarity and pray for the success of
the new Solidarity-led government.
   Walesa and Solidarity, the East bloc's first independent trade
union, had much to celebrate this year. The union emerged from seven
years of banishment to end 45 years of communist control of the
Polish government.
   ``On Aug. 31, 1980, I signed in your name the document which
became the basis for the creation of Solidarity and which changed
the course of Polish history,'' Walesa told his cheering supporters.
   ``We reject the road of violence and revolution, but we have the
right to use legal measures. We want to have a government really
capable of changing Poland, and really responsible in front of
Solidarity and its allies and in front of the nation.
   ``It is our duty to make sure that is what happens. Remember at
the end, it is always the nation, the ordinary people, who decide.''
   Walesa, a shipyard electrician and 1983 Nobel Peace laureate,
drew cheers as he took his seat in front of the towering workers
monument in front of the Lenin Shipyard, where Solidarity was born.
   Sitting next to Walesa was a special guest, Jan Nowak, the
``Courier from Warsaw,'' who smuggled information out of
Nazi-occupied Poland during World War II and who long headed the
Polish section of U.S. government-financed Radio Free Europe,
becoming an enemy of the communist state for his uncensored
broadcasts.
   Solidarity's Tadeusz Mazowiecki, who became prime minister last
week, said in a television address he could not join the Gdansk
commemoration because of the pressing need to form his new
government.
   Dozens of delegations from mines and factories across Poland
dipped Solidarity flags at the monument honoring workers killed
during 1970 workers' riots along the Baltic coast. Two parachutes
lettered with ``Solidarity'' fluttered from poles near the shipyard
entrance.
   Exactly one year ago, the shipyard was strikebound for the second
time in four months and Walesa was in Warsaw for his first talks in
six years with communist authorities desperate for a solution to
nationwide labor unrest.
   Later that day, Walesa returned to Gdansk and successfully
appealed for an end to the strikes. His discussions with authorities
led to the start in February of talks on political and economic
reform.
   After the historic negotiations came restoration of Solidarity's
legal status April 17 and June elections that were the freest in the
Soviet bloc in four decades.
   Solidarity's stunning victories and the Communist Party's
disastrous showings led to the unprecedented possibility of
power-sharing.
   And on Aug. 24, as a result of a parliamentary coalition forged
by Walesa between Solidarity and two smaller parties long allied
with the Communists, Mazowiecki became prime minister.
   ``We enter a new epoch. It depends on us when we will be able to
say Poland is a free, democratic and wealthy country. Now I say that
next year, we will be thankful for visible economic acheivements,''
Walesa said.
   Mazowiecki said over TV, ``I very warmly greet all my friends
from those times that we spent together in such hard, dramatic, but
I think fruitful, circumstances. I am with them during these solemn
ceremonies.''
   Nowak was overcome by emotion as he stood to address the
assemblage. He returned to Poland on Tuesday for the first time
since fleeing at the end of the Warsaw Uprising of 1944.
   ``It seems absolutely impossible I can stand in front of you,''
Nowak said. ``Solidarity, although defenseless, opened a road to me
for my own country with its spirit.
   ``Not so long ago, what I would have faced here would have been a
death sentence.''
   An outdoor Mass was celebrated by Gdansk Bishop Tadeusz
Goclowski, who wore robes embroidered with ``Solidarity'' in red
glitter.
   ``Today we can be real co-partners in truth, be those who will
build the new reality of our homeland,'' Goclowski said.
   Piles of bouquets, two framed photos of Polish-born Pope John
Paul II and a wooden cross decorated the main gate of the Lenin
Shipyard.
   Even the Gdansk Communist Party newspaper Glos Wybrzeza marked
the anniversary in a front page article under the headline ``Hope.''
   ``Almost all of us remember that day ... From August 1980, not
only nine years have passed, an epoch has passed. Especially the
recent months were filled with changes that stunned the world,'' the
paper said.
</TEXT>
