<FIRST>r a AM-ElderlyOrdeal     08-31 0308</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Elderly Ordeal,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>Old Man Survives Wilderness Ordeal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With nothing but blueberries for food
and the wisdom of years to guide him, a 95-year-old miner survived
three weeks lost in the wilderness with little more than sore feet
to show for the ordeal.
   ``I knew the Good Lord would rescue me,'' Dennis D. Wilkins said
after he was found Tuesday northwest of Anchorage. ``As for being
scared as that no one would find me, well, I never even gave it a
thought.''
   After his meager supply of food ran out, Wilkins ate nothing but
berries for almost two weeks as he wandered moose trails through the
woods.
   He said that except for his swollen and blistered feet, he was in
good condition, but ``I'm sore inside and out. I feel like I've been
run over by a logging truck.''
   Wilkins said things went awry Aug. 8 when he set out from his
cabin for Derf Lake, where he was to meet friends who would fly him
to Anchorage.
   ``I can't explain it, but somehow I got lost,'' he said. ``There
were a lot of moose trails crisscrossing, and then my food supply
ran out. Should have brought more. And I think I must have had some
blackouts. You know, you don't think right when your stomach's
empty.''
   State troopers were called in to search for Wilkins. ``We've had
to look for him in the past,'' said Sgt. Warren Grant.
   Wilkins, meanwhile, reached a cabin and subsisted on its store of
crackers before being discovered in a day or so by its surprised
owners, Harold Brian and Wayne Davis. ``Those fellows looked like
heaven to me,'' Wilkins said.
   Grant said that people have been lost in Alaska's woods for
longer periods but that Wilkins ``must be one rugged guy'' to
survive at his age.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
