<FIRST>r w AM-WorldBank-Environment     08-31 0246</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-World Bank-Environment,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>World Bank Assailed as Unaggressive on Threats to Environment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leading private environmental group said
Thursday the World Bank was not doing enough to help Third World
countries combat the threat of rising global temperatures.
   The bank, owned by 151 governments, is the largest source of aid
to the Third World, lending over $19 billion a year.
   ``The status quo is not acceptable as an option,'' said David A.
Wirth, senior attorney for the National Resources Development
Council.
   His criticism was based on an internal bank paper prepared in
advance of a major speech on the environment that the bank's
president, Barber Conable, is due to deliver in Tokyo on Sept. 11.
The paper includes a section entitled: ``The Bank Can Do More.''
   ``This document is the equivalent of saying that hats and
sunglasses will solve the problem of stratospheric ozone
destruction,'' Wirth said in a statement on the paper.
   One threat to the environment foreseen by some scientists is that
chemicals released on Earth are destroying the layer of ozone, a gas
in the upper atmosphere that protects the planet from harmful rays
of the sun.
   Frank Vogl, the bank's chief spokesman, said the paper was only
one of many inputs for Conable's speech and for a new ``operational
directive'' the bank is preparing.
   ``The statements of a tiny number of environmentalists fail to
acknowledge the immense volume of undertakings by the bank,'' he
said in an interview.
</TEXT>
