<DOCNO> AP890831-0150 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-89 1758EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Panama     08-31 0672</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama,0695</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Noriega Classmate Named Provisional President</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A council controlled by Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega named one of his high school classmates as
provisional president Thursday and said the timing of new elections
depends on the United States.
   The Council of State _ Cabinet ministers and heads of agencies
and the military _ chose Francisco Rodriguez to head the government
and said elections could not be held until U.S. economic sanctions
and ``aggression'' ended.
   It said the situation will be evaluated in six months to
determine whether elections are possible.
   Noriega, who holds the real power in Panama as head of the
military and police, is a member of the council and is presumed to
control it.
   He and Rodriguez were close friends in high school and graduated
in 1957. Rodriguez, who has spent most of his life as a government
administrator, takes office Friday when acting President Manuel
Solis Palma's term ends.
   Solis Palma finished the term of Eric Arturo Delvalle, who was
dismissed after trying to fire Noriega last year as chief of Panama
Defense Forces. The United States still recognizes Delvalle.
   International observers said the opposition candidate won the May
7 presidential elections by a 3-1 margin, but the government
annulled the vote on grounds the results were ``distorted'' by U.S.
interference and economic aid to the opposition.
   The United States has imposed economic sanctions on Panama in an
effort to oust Noriega, who has been indicted in Florida on federal
charges of drug trafficking and money laundering.
   At a meeting of the Organization of American States in
Washington, Deputy Secretary of State Lawrence Eagleburger said
Noriega was a man of ``shameless excess,'' who amassed a fortune of
up to $300 million from drugs and other criminal activities.
   Eagleburger made the allegation in response to a challenge from a
Panamanian diplomat last week for the Bush administration to back up
charge charges.
   Chosen as provisional vice president of Panama was Carlos Ozores
Typaldos, a leader of the ruling Revolutionary Democratic Party and
deputy director of the newspaper La Estrella.
   The Council of State said the national legislature would be
abolished and the government would rule with a legislative
commission of 41 appointed members. It said the government would
rule by decree until the commission was selected.
   City governments will be replaced by appointed officials and the
new government will draft a new constitution, the council said.
   ``Panama has lived a historic moment today as a free and
sovereign nation and within its laws,'' Noriega said after the
announcement that his friend would become president.
   Political opposition leaders have called the new government ``a
continuation of the military dictatorship.''
   Solis Palma said Rodriguez was chosen ``because of the knowledge
he has of the country's economic situation and balanced judgment he
has exercised in his decisions.''
   Panama is in an economic crisis aggravated by the two-year
confrontation with the United States.
   According to the comptroller's office, the gross national product
declined 17 per cent in 1988, the worst drop since 1945, and more
than 30,000 jobs were lost.
   Washington has has withheld fees for use of the Panama Canal
since March 1988, has stopped payment of taxes on salaries of Panama
Canal Commission employees and has frozen Panamanian government
funds in American banks.
   U.S. officials say normal relations cannot be resumed with a
government Noriega controls.
   Panama claims the United States plans to kidnap the general.
Sandbagged fortifications have been built around the headquarters of
the Defense Forces and other military installations.
   Military units of the two countries have been had several
confrontations in which, as a diplomat put it, ``they have come
pretty close to shooting.''
   The United States has military installations in Panama and is
charged with protecting the canal until the end of 1999, when it
will be turned over to Panama.
   Noriega claims the U.S. charges against him are part of a plot to
renege on the 1977 treaties and keep the canal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
