<SECOND>AM-El Diario Sold,130</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gannett Sells NY Spanish Language Daily</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gannett Co. announced Thursday that it has sold
El Diario-La Prensa, a Spanish language daily newspaper in New York
City, to a partnership headed by the paper's publisher.
   Gannett, which had owned the paper since 1981, sold it to El
Diario Associates, a New York partnership, whose principals included
the paper's publisher, Carlos Ramirez.
   Ramirez, who has been publisher of the newspaper since 1984, will
continue in that position, according to Gannett.
   The sale price of the El Diario-LaPrensa, which has a circulation
of 51,000, was not disclosed.
   The sale dropped the number of daily newspapers owned by Gannett
to 83, including USA Today.
   Gannett also publishes 35 non-daily papers, operates 10
television and 16 radio stations and owns the largest outdoor
advertising company in North America.
</TEXT>
