<FIRST>r a AM-Hoover     08-31 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hoover,0210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conservative Think Tank Director Retires, Chides Stanford Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STANFORD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   W. Glenn Campbell, for 30 years director
of the Hoover Institution of War, Revolution and Peace, a
conservative think tank former President Reagan once called a
``national treasure,'' retired Thursday.
   Campbell, 65, tripled the size of the Hoover Institution, whose
scholars helped build the ideological framework of the Reagan
administration, and fattened its endowments more than 50-fold to
more than $125 million during his tenure.
   But that increased tension between the think tank and Stanford
University, of which it is technically a part, a collection within
the university's library.
   Some Stanford faculty members want Hoover's independence curbed,
while others want to clip the ties altogether.
   Hoover has been an irritant to the Stanford faculty for years.
Faculty critics have complained that the academic system has allowed
the institute by its independence to pursue a philosphy that has
tainted the university. Campbell calls his critics ``huns.''
   More than a score of Hoover fellows served in full-time posts
under Reagan, and some now are in the Bush administration, including
Michael Boskin, head of the president's Council of Economic Advisors.
   Boskin has been mentioned as a candidate for new Hoover director.
</TEXT>
