<FIRST>u a AM-BushRdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0692 08-31 0738</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0692,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Holds Talks With Mulroney</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Drug Strategy Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: To CORRECT typo and add Bush's mother, SUB 7th graf pvs, Both
men ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush and Canadian Prime
Minister Brian Mulroney, emerging from a seaside retreat, said
Thursday they explored ways of providing more help for Colombian
President Virgilio Barco in his battle against the drug barons.
   But both leaders, pressed on the possibility of sending a
multilateral force to fight the drug cartels, stressed that any such
appeal must start with Barco and not be imposed upon the Latin
American nation.
   Bush said, ``There is no point in Canada or the United States or
... any group of countries imposing its will on a country that is
now trying very very hard to rid itself of this menace.''
   Mulroney said they were in ``complete agreement ... (on) the need
to support a very courageous leader in Colombia and the need to
stomp out by every reasonable means the terror of drugs.''
   In a windy, seaside news conference, the two leaders also renewed
their condemnation of Panama's Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, who has
thwarted democratic rule in his country.
   Bush, who played host to Mulroney and family for a 26-hour stay
here, called it ``an unusually productive visit'' that despite its
private nature included almost four hours of talks on world issues
and U.S.-Canadian ties.
   Both men wore yellow sports shirts and casual slacks while their
wives, Bush's 88-year-old mother, Dorothy, and Mulroney's children
stood watching them field questions on the lawn between Bush's
tennis court and the blue sea, dotted with brightly colored markers
from lobster pots.
   Lobster, in fact, was one of the few areas of strain in
U.S.-Canadian relations, and Mulroney allowed that Bush had
``advanced some persuasive arguments'' about Canadian lobstermen's
catch of lobsters that in U.S. waters would be too small to keep.
The Americans contend the Canadian catch lobsters before they grow
big enough to reproduce.
   While Bush said there was broad agreement between the United
States and Canada on trade, ``there are still bumps in the road.''
   On the lobster dispute, Mulroney said, ``The president was big on
lobsters today. I was big on pork because we feel that the Americans
have just imposed an unfair tariff on pork.''
   He said they had discussed the mechanisms to resolve the pork
dispute under the Free Trade Agreement.
   The Canadian leader said they were making progress on acid rain,
thanks in part to Bush's recently proposed Clean Air amendments. But
Mulroney said he wants a U.S.-Canada bilateral clean air accord
``and I won't be satisfied that the issue is resolved until
President Bush and I sit down and sign that accord.''
   ``We agree on almost all the major issues,'' said the president.
``And where Canada and the U.S. may have bumps in the road, we can
talk very frankly.'
   Bush said the national drug strategy he will unveil next Tuesday
will not slight drug interdiction efforts abroad to expand drug
enforcement at home.
   Afterwards, his chief of staff, John Sununu, predicted the drug
package will cost $7.8 billion, almost $2 billion above current
spending levels, and require a reallocation of resources.
   On another issue, Bush said he was considering increasing
emergency food shipments to Poland. ``That is one (area) where we
ought to be able to do more,'' he said.
   On the situation in Panama, Bush said, ``I've never seen a coming
together in world opinion as there is on this one ... that Noriega
ought to get out.'' He said he had just received a letter from
British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher on Panama.
   ``I am not going to give up on multilateral diplomacy,'' said
Bush.
   ``There's a high frustration level. I'm ready to concede that.
But we are not going to give up on this,'' Bush said. ``We are not
going to permit the will of the people of Panama to be thwarted by
this dictator.''
   Mulroney, who came with his wife, Mila, and four children,
encountered the same luck as Bush when he tried fishing.
   Mulroney offered ``the impartial international assessment of the
fact that there are no fish out there. I can certify to that. It's
not the president's fault.''
   Bush said, ``I positively guarantee you that this jinx will be
broken'' before he heads home Monday from his 20-day vacation.
</TEXT>
