<DOCNO> AP890831-0161 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-89 1838EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Cambodia     08-31 0566</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cambodia,0582</SECOND>
<HEAD>Experts Predict Renewed Factional War in Cambodia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE GANLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delegates and experts predict more factional warfare
in Cambodia now that an international conference has failed to
produce a peace plan.
   ``The moment is favorable'' for a period of military testing,
Asian specialist Francois Godement of the French Institute for
International Relations, said Thursday. ``The question is at what
level of intensity.''
   An overriding concern at the monthlong conference, which ended
Wednesday in Paris, was that civil war would resume when Vietnam
pulled its forces out Sept. 27, leaving the army of Premier Hun Sen
to fend for itself.
   Vietnam invaded Cambodia in December 1978 and overthrew the
brutal Khmer Rouge regime of Pol Pot, which was held responsible for
1 million deaths during less than four years in power.
   Lt. Gen. Naruedol Dejpradiyuth, the Thai army spokesman, said
Thursday in Bangkok he doubted the Vietnamese pullout would be
complete but still expected a renewal of the war in neighboring
Cambodia. He spoke at the monthly army news conference.
   A Vietnamese radio broadcast said guerrillas encamped near the
border already were trying to push soldiers and civilians into the
Cambodian interior ``to provide a legal status for the so-called
resistance ... before a cease-fire takes effect and elections are
held.''
   Delegates and observers note the Vietnamese departure comes at
the beginning of the dry season, the traditional time for
intensified combat in Cambodia.
   Although it may have been inadvertent, the conference left time
for military confrontation with its decision to renew contacts
within six months about resuming peace talks.
   ``Without results on the battlefield, there are no results at the
negotiating table,'' said Ek Sereywath, spokesman for the delegation
of Prince Norodom Sihanouk, the former Cambodian ruler who leads the
guerrilla alliance. ``We were deadlocked here because the military
situation is not decisive.''
   Most of those commenting felt the Chinese-backed Khmer Rouge, the
strongest element of Sihanouk's three-party rebel coalition, would
act first.
   ``The Khmer Rouge have something to prove ... that they cannot be
eliminated in the political domain and that they are a permanent
factor'' in any settlement, Godement said in a telephone interview.
   At the 19-nation conference, Hun Sen excluded a share of
authority for the Khmer Rouge. Sihanouk, contending his allies would
be less dangerous in power than out, insisted they participate in a
four-party transitional government that would run the country before
elections.
   China's chief delegate, Vice Foreign Minister Liu Shuqing, said
the failure to reach a settlement ``signifies that the resistance
struggle against Vietnamese agression will continue in Cambodia.''
He said China would continue aid to the guerrillas while seeking
peace.
   A senior U.S. official said privately: ``We may be moving into a
period where, having had this initial test of political opinion,
things will go back to ... the battlefield.''
   In Washington, State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler
said the Bush administration welcomed the progress made at the
conference and hoped it would lead to a comprehensive settlement.
   Li Mai, Vietnamese ambassador in Bangkok, said Hun Sen's army was
capable of defending itself. ``They are very self-confident and I
think they are very capable,'' he said.
   At a news conference Wednesday night, Hun Sen called for a
diplomatic solution but said he expected renewed attacks by the
Khmer Rouge. ``We have really prepared ourselves for the worst,'' he
told the reporters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
