<FIRST>u i AM-Libya 2ndLd-Writethru   08-31 0681</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Libya, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0656,0698</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foreign Leaders Stream Into Tripoli for Gadhafi Fete</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with meeting broken off, details
on Syrian leader. Pickup 6th pvs, ``A military ...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRY LEONARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRIPOLI, Libya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign dignitaries streamed into a freshly
painted Tripoli on Thursday for celebrations of the 20th anniversary
of the radical revolution led by Col. Moammar Gadhafi.
   Friday's multimillion-dollar bash, featuring a military parade
and air show, was expected to attract top officials from Nicaragua
to North Korea.
   The dispatching of high-ranking envoys from Egypt, Chad and Italy
to the festival underlined Gadhafi's efforts in recent years to move
away from a radical, go-it-alone policy to one of cooperation with
his Northern African neighbors and Western Europe.
   However, it appeared not all of Gadhafi's plans for the
celebration would come off. A Western European diplomat, speaking on
condition of anonymity, said committee sessions on a planned Maghreb
summit had broken off over differences in financial matters between
the Maghreb members _ Libya, Algeria, Tunisia, Morocco and
Mauritania. He did not elaborate.
   Gadhafi seized power from King Idris on Sept. 1, 1969, and
replaced the country's pro-Western policy with his own personal
brand of socialism and pan-Arabism. Relations between Libya and
Washington deteriorated, and in April 1986 the United States bombed
Tripoli and Benghazi in retaliation for what it called Libya's
sponsoring of international iterrorism.
   On Thursday, Gadhafi went to Tripoli's military airport to greet
the leaders of Gabon, Madagascar, South Yemen, Ghana, Algeria,
Tunisia, Mozambique and Syria, as well as Palestine Liberation
Organization chief Yasser Arafat.
   Syrian President Hafez Assad's presence was unusual. He rarely
travels and is thought to have gone to Libya, an ally, because of
his isolation in his war against Lebanon's Christians.
   A military band played and 21-gun salutes boomed as the
dignitaries were met by Gadhafi, wearing white slacks, a white
jacket, a green shirt and sunglasses.
   King Hassan II of Morocco made the grandest entry, sailing into
Tripoli's downtown harbor in a small white ship flanked by Libyan
escort vessels and blaring its horn.
   The leaders of Madagascar, Somalia, Malta, Djibouti and South
Yemen already were in Tripoli, along with official delegations from
other Arab, African and Asian countries. Nicaraguan President Daniel
Ortega said he would attend.
   Italian Foreign Ministrer Gianni De Michelis was the
highest-ranking Westerner who traveled to the former Italian colony.
He was the first Italian government official to visit Libya since it
fired a missile at an Italian island in 1986.
   Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak sent a top-level envoy to the
celebrations, in a cautious step toward resolving a bitter feud with
Libya. Youssef Waly, deputy prime minister and secretary-general of
the ruling party, was the highest Egyptian official to visit since
1977, when the two countries fought a five-day border war.
   Egypt and Libya recently reopened their border and resumed air
flights. Western European diplomats in Tripoli said they expected
the two countries would soon re-establish diplomatic relations,
broken in 1978.
   In Algeria, diplomats announced that Libya and Chad had signed a
peace agreement. In the accord, signed in Algiers, the two countries
agreed to end 16 years of fighting over the disputed Aozou strip and
try to reach a political settlement within a year.
   Chad was represented at the Tripoli festivities by a delegation
led by Minister of State Jedenkar Donou Aukar.
   In Tripoli, sirens blared as white-jacketed policemen on
motorcycles escorted official motorcades to seaside hotels.
   The city was freshly painted white and green, the colors of
Libya's flag, for the celebration.
   Brightly colored helium balloons about three feet in diameter
floated from buildings, and a large green, yellow and white hot-air
balloon emblazoned with Gadhafi's picture rose from a parking lot
near the central Green Square.
   Hundreds of green Libyan flags fluttered from lampposts and
windows, and strings of lights glowed above the streets.
   The celebrations to mark the annivesary begin Friday with a
special meeting of the General People's Congress, Libya's
parliament. The session will be followed by the air show and
military parade.
</TEXT>
