<FIRST>u i AM-Ethiopia     08-31 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ethiopia,0404</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ethiopian Leader Says Rebels Launched Surprise Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mengistu Haile Mariam said
Tigrean rebels launched surprise attacks ``on all fronts'' in
northeastern Ethiopia at dawn Thursday _ six days after saying they
wanted peace talks.
   The announcement came only hours after Mengistu had given an
optimistic assessment of recent peace moves to the country's Shengo,
or parliament.
   But when the legislative assembly resumed its afternoon session,
Mengistu reappeared to tell deputies of a dawn offensive by the
Tigrean People's Liberation Front.
   The president said the rebels launched massive attacks in Tigre
and Wollo provinces in northeastern Ethiopia and that fighting may
have extended to Gondar in the northwest.
   He said the offensive appears to be supported by Ethiopia's major
rebel group, the Eritrean People's Liberation Front.
   ``There are indications that the rebels might extend the fighting
to Gondar and attempt to cut the Addis Ababa-Assab highway,''
Mengistu said.
   Assab is Ethiopia's main port on the Red Sea and the highway,
which was badly damaged in a series of earthquakes 10 days ago, was
reopened only Wednesday. It is the capital's main link to the sea.
   The two rebel groups supported each other in coordinated attacks
in early 1988 that won them control of all of Tigre and most of
Eritrea, Ethiopia's northernmost province. Gondar and Wollo were
largely spared in that offensive.
   Mengistu called Thursday's attack ``a regrettable and sad
development.''
   While he did not give casualty figures for either side, his
description of the fighting suggested government forces are being
pushed back.
   Mengistu had told the morning's opening session of Parliament
that his government soon would hold peace talks with the Tigrean
rebels.
   Although he made no reference to those planned talks in his
afternoon announcement, the attack may have put any possible
negotiations on indefinite hold.
   Government officials and Eritrean rebels have planned to meet in
Atlanta beginning Sept. 7 with former President Jimmy Carter acting
as an observer. Tigrean rebels took up arms 14 years ago to press
for increased autonomy in their region. On Aug. 25, they announced
they were ready for peace talks overseen by Carter.
   Eritrean rebels have been fighting for independence since 1961.
They agreed to peace talks in June after Mengistu announced there
would be no conditions and he would welcome an independent observer.
</TEXT>
