<FIRST>r a AM-OilSpill     08-31 0195</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Spill,0199</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tanker Spills Crude Oil in Delaware River</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Jery in 6th graf is CQ</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARCUS HOOK, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 865-foot Singaporean tanker spilled at
least 1,000 gallons of crude oil Thursday into the Delaware River
while discharging cargo at a refinery, the Coast Guard said.
   ``Preliminary reports indicate that human error may be
responsible,'' the Coast Guard said about four hours after the
tanker Minerva's 11:20 a.m. at the British Petroleum Refinery. The
cause remained under investigation.
   The Coast Guard, which initially reported the spill at 4,200
gallons, revised its figure after British Petroleum said the spill
involved only 600 gallons. A slick extended 4{ miles downriver from
the site.
   Representatives of the Minerva, owned by Argo Dua Shipping PTE
Ltd. of Singapore, and the refinery immediately notified authorities
and put containment booms around the tanker, the Coast Guard said.
   The ship hired a pollution contractor, which deployed a boat and
trucks to vacuum up the crude.
   Petty Officer Jery Scheddel said spills of less than 10,000
gallons are considered minor on the Delaware. On June 24, the
Uruguayan tanker Presidente Rivera spilled an estimated 300,000
gallons of heating oil.
