<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-89 1945EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Israel     08-31 0664</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel,0688</SECOND>
<HEAD>Medical Chief Doubts Many Listed Actually Died in Clashes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARJORIE OLSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The director of forensic medicine in Israel said
Thursday that many Palestinian deaths attributed to clashes with
troops in the occupied areas actually resulted from criminal
disputes or other circumstances.
   The comments by Yehuda Hiss, director of the state Abu Kabir
Institute for Forensic Medicine in Tel Aviv, came as an Israeli tax
collector died of injuries from a Palestinian firebomb attack two
weeks ago and a Palestinian, whose family said he was beaten, died
of wounds in the Gaza Strip.
   Tax collector Gideon Zaken's death raised to 39 the number of
Israelis killed in the Palestinian rebellion. At least 554
Palestinians have been killed by soldiers or Jewish settlers during
the 20-month-old revolt, and 100 Palestinians have been killed by
fellow Arabs as suspected collaborators.
   At least 16 Palestinians were shot and wounded in clashes with
troops in the Gaza Strip on Thursday, Arab reports said.
   Hiss told The Associated Press he found 25 percent of deaths
attributed to Israeli troopers during the uprising were not linked
to the army.
   He said 30 percent of the Palestinians killed and said to be
``victims of the intefadeh,'' or uprising, were brought to Abu Kabir
for autopsies.
   In one fourth of the cases, Hiss said he found the Arabs died of
strangulation, stabbing or suffocation and not army force. In two
cases, the victims had been decapitated, he said.
   Hiss attributed the deaths to criminal disputes, family honor
killings and suspicion of collaborating with Israel.
   ``I fear that in a number of years ... the world will blame us
for causing the death of thousands of residents of the territories,
many of whom I am certain did not die from army operations,'' Hiss
said.
   He said the deaths, including some from natural causes, ``are all
put in one basket of victims of the intefadeh.''
   The controversy over cause of death in the occupied West Bank and
Gaza Strip is reflected in differing death tolls offered by rival
sides and by news organizations.
   Official army statistics show 450 Palestinians killed in the West
Bank and Gaza Strip as a result of clashes with troops between
December 1987 and mid-August 1989.
   An unofficial toll for the same period compiled by the AP showed
535 Palestinians killed by troops or settlers.
   Both tolls exclude many deaths which Arab reports said resulted
from tear-gas inhalation or beatings.
   Some Palestinian organizations put the number of Palestinian
deaths at more than 700.
   One Palestinian journalist, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
called the Arab figures exxagerated. He said hospital doctors were
threatened and their cars burned for refusing to falsify death
records.
   Hiss also noted the widespread practice of taking bodies from
hospitals in Arab areas and burying them before an autopsy. He
recommended exhuming the bodies for autopsies.
   Hiss said many claims of torture or killing by troops proved
untrue when autopsy was performed. He cited the death of Amjad
Jibril Tawil, 14, a Palestinian-American boy, near the West Bank
city of Ramallah two weeks ago.
   Palestinian reports said the boy was found dead with broken arms,
teeth knocked out and cigarette burns covering his body, but an
autopsy at Abu Kabir and a subsequent independent autopsy found no
signs of torture.
   Tawil died from a gunshot in the back.
   Hospital spokeswoman Ruth Mekel said Thursday that Zaken died in
Jerusalem's Hadassah hospital after suffering burns on 70 percent of
his body in a firebomb attack.
   In Gaza, 19-year-old Ahmad Abdullah Agha died at Nasser Hospital
in Khan Yunis of head injuries. His family said he was beaten by
soldiers in a clash four days earlier. The army said it was
investigating the reported beating.
   In the West Bank, the body of a 30-year-old Palestinian taxi
driver, Burhan Badawi, was found in a pushcart in Nablus, the army
said. Arab reporters said the reason for his death was unclear.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
