<HEAD>Four Social Workers Indicted in Toddler's Abuse Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BARTOW, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four social workers were indicted on child
abuse charges Thursday in the death of a 2-year-old boy who was
released to his parents despite warnings that he was in danger.
   Bradley McGee died of a brain hemorrhage at his home on July 28
after his mother and stepfather punished him for soiling his diapers
by repeatedly dunking him ``plunger-like'' head-first into a
commode, police said.
   ``I think we are seeing the beginning of accountability,'' said
Pam Kirland of Lakeland, who was Bradley's foster mother before he
was returned to his parents. Bradley died two months later.
   Mrs. Kirkland had warned caseworkers of the state Office of
Health and Rehabilitative Services of the possibility that Bradley
was being abused at his parents' Lakeland home.
   She called the Polk County grand jury action an ``indictment of
the system which failed Bradley and other children like him.''
   Caseworker Margaret Barber was indicted on a third-degree felony
charge of child abuse and a second-degree misdemeanor charge of
failing to report child abuse.
   Judy Ross, Barber's former supervisor, program administrator
Kenneth Houk and former caseworker Shirley Duboise each were
indicted on charges of failing to report child abuse.
   On conviction, each count of child abuse could be punishable by
five years in prison; failure to report child abuse could be
punished by 60 days in jail.
   An earlier HRS investigation led to Barber's suspension for six
weeks on Aug. 15. Ross was demoted from supervisor to caseworker,
Houk was reprimanded and DuBoise resigned rather than face action
from her superiors.
   Regional administrator Thomas McFayden, who was given a
three-week suspension by HRS, wasn't charged in the Thursday
indictment.
   Bradley's parents, Thomas Coe, 22, and Sheryl McGee Coe, 20, have
been indicted on first-degree murder charges. Their trial is
scheduled to start Dec. 11.
   Mrs. Coe abandoned Bradley shortly after his birth, turning him
over to a stranger in a shopping mall.
   He wound up in a foster home, and his foster parents told social
workers there were signs of his being abused on weekly home visits
allowed with the Coes.
   Gov. Bob Martinez on Wednesday extended his call for a special
session of the Florida Legislature Oct. 10 on abortion to include
revision of child protection laws.
</TEXT>
