<FIRST>u i AM-Paraguay-Adoptions     08-31 0499</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Paraguay-Adoptions,0516</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Suspends Adoptions by Foreign Families</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court on Thursday suspended
the adoptions of babies by foreigners after President Andres
Rodriguez complained the system was run more like a business than a
social service.
   Court President Jose Alberto Correa said adoptions in process may
be completed.
   Rodriguez complained publicly on Aug. 17 that ``infants are being
sold for $7,000 and incredibly, judges and lawyers are involved in
this business. ... It is a shame that Paraguayan children are
negotiated over like merchandise.''
   The general ousted the 34-year regime of President Gen. Alfredo
Stroessner in a Feb. 3 coup and was overwhelmingly elected president
on May 1.
   Newspapers printed stories involving poor women who said they
felt pressured to give up their children, and of foreigners, many
from the United States, allegedly paying large sums for healthy
babies with blond hair and blue eyes.
   Judges became reluctant to give the final authorization that
would allow Paraguayan infants to leave the country with adoptive
parents.
   Jay and Susan Steinhof of Berlin, Mass., are among eight U.S.
couples in Asuncion awaiting judicial permission to take home babies
they were given since arriving during the previous two weeks.
   ``Jason has put on 1{ pounds since we got him,'' Jay Steinhof, a
36-year-old computer software salesman, said in a telephone
interview.
   ``They asked us what color we wanted,'' he said, noting that the
baby has ``dark hair, dark eyes and medium to dark skin ... We
didn't care. We were more concerned that it be a boy. We have a
daughter.''
   Until recently, adoptions by foreign families were comparatively
easy and fast. Adoptions by U.S. families went from 37 in 1985 to
322 in 1988.
   ``I called several adoption agencies in Alabama, but when they
found out our ages, they wouldn't accept us,'' said Judy Hooper, 37,
in an interview earlier this year.
   She and her husband, Granville Hooper, 40, of Hanceville, Ala.,
now are the parents of 6-month-old Tyler Dennis, a chubby,
black-haired boy with brown eyes.
   About 220 adoptions are pending, a U.S. Embassy official said in
a telephone interview. The official, who commented on condition of
anonymity, said it was unclear how many would be allowed to go
through.
   Under regulations due to be revised, preference was given to
Paraguayans seeking to adopt and foreign families had to submit
eight reports during the first two years to document their child's
progress.
   The maximum age was 60 instead of 45, as is the limit in many
U.S. states, and there were fewer obstacles to adoptions by single
parents.
   Most U.S. applications included an approval from a stateside
adoption agency or social worker, and a visa from the Immigration
and Naturalization Service that allowed the child to enter the
United States.
   Steinhof said he thought public opposition to the adoptions was
based on misconceptions. ``They seem to think we come on a plane on
Tuesday, pay someone and leave with a kid on Wednesday.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
