<FIRST>r w AM-ContraAid     08-31 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Contra Aid,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressman Says Contras Cannot Be Monitored</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congressman opposed to aid for Nicaragua
Contras contended Thursday the State Department admits it lacks the
intelligence capability to assure that rebel attacks on civilians in
Nicaragua had ceased.
   ``The adminstration admits now that they knew that they couldn't
keep their promise to Congress and the American people,'' Rep. Peter
DeFazio said in a news release that quoted a State Department letter
to him.
   DeFazio was referring to the agreement under which the Contras
could receive non-military aid if they refrained from offensive
actions.
   The State Department, however, said its letter was misinterpreted.
   The letter from Janet Mullins, assistant secretary of state for
legislative affairs, said: ``We do not have a strong intelligence
capability to assess responsibility for the initiation of the
reported clashes which mar the informal truce in effect between the
Nicaraguan Resistance and Sandinista forces.
   ``But given that the Resistance has been cut off from military
aid and is very low on ammunition, we do not believe that they have
the ability to take an offensive mode.''
   Ms. Mullins said the department has asserted to the Contras its
position against military attacks.
   ``In one case, we terminated family support to a commander whose
unit initiated an offensive operation after the bipartisan accord,''
she said.
   She also said ``we may have prevented an offensive operation'' in
another instance, by contacting the Contra command after learning a
unit leader may have been planning an attack.
   The letter was a response to one written by DeFazio and signed by
83 members of Congress asking the administration to investigate
allegations that the Contras were ``engaged in offensive military
actions.''
   DeFazio's letter listed nine alleged Contra attacks between April
13 and June 8, reported by Witness for Peace, a human rights
organization. The congressman said the reports have been
corroborated by U.S. journalists.
   ``The administration is turning a blind eye to a series of
well-documented human rights abuses and military actions by Contra
forces,'' said DeFazio.
   Mullins' response did not speak directly to the Witness for Peace
list, but alluded to another series of alleged Contra attacks
reported by the Nicaraguan government which, she said, were
investigated by an agency. She did not identify the agency but said
that it could verify only a small number as having taken place.
   On the other hand, she said: ``The Department has received an
increasing number of worrisome reports of Sandinista abuses from
Nicaraguan and international human rights organizations.''
   Under the bipartisan agreement that accompanied the $48 million
Contra aid package approved last April, President Bush promised to
cut off funds to all Contra units that persisted in offensive
actions such as killing or kidnaping civilians.
   Under the informal agreement, which has no legal standing, Bush
said he would not continue spending the $48 million on the Contras
after Nov. 30 if congressional leaders found that the Contras were
not acting in good faith toward peace in Nicaragua.
   The money was appropriated for use through Feb. 28, 1990.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
