<HEAD>No Damage, Says Architect; Change Bid Laws, Says Governor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The historic Lower Pontalba Apartments
sustained no structural damage when three stories of scaffolding
collapsed during renovation of the French Quarter landmark, an
architect reported Thursday.
   The scaffolding on the 138-year-old structure, regarded as the
nation's first apartment building, collapsed Aug. 23 into Jackson
Square. There were no injuries reported.
   Architect Ronald W. Thomas said balconies on the second and third
floors were damaged in the collapse, some third-floor timbers also
need to be shored up, and bricks and stone in the attic should be
stored on the ground floor.
   It was the second spectacular Jackson Square accident in 16
months. In May 1988, fire destroyed the top floor of the nearby
Cabildo, where the Louisiana Purchase territories were transferred
from France to the United States.
