<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia-Hunger,0188</SECOND>
<HEAD>Czech Hunger Striker Said Seriously Ill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Czechoslovak worker who was one of about
100 people detained after an anti-government protest is on hunger
strike and seriously ill in a Prague prison hospital, an emigre
source said Thursday.
   The source, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said Vladimir
Veselsky, 24, was the only person not released after being detained
at an Aug. 21 protest in the city of Brno marking the anniversary of
the 1968 Soviet-led invasion that crushed Communist reform in
Czechoslovakia.
   About 370 people, including 50 foreigners, were detained during
an anti-government protest that day in Prague, the Czechoslovak
capital. All have been released.
   The emigre source said Veselsky's defense lawyer discovered his
client was transferred to a hospital at Prague's prison hospital
Aug. 29 after fasting since his arrest. Veselsky is reported to be
seriously ill, the source said.
   Veselsky is charged with failing to obey the orders of a police
officer and refusing to show his documents, the source said. The
maximum penalty for the charge was not immediately known, the source
added.
