<FIRST>u i AM-Honduras-US     08-31 0137</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Honduras-US,0142</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Soldiers Participating In Honduras Maneuvers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An estimated 4,000 U.S. soldiers are
scheduled to participate in joint maneuvers with Honduran forces
Sept. 7-12, the Honduran government said Thursday.
   The armed forces said in a statement that the land, air and naval
maneuvers would take place in Cortes and Santa Barbara provinces,
northwest of the capital.
   The statement said the maneuvers were designed to prepare ``to
repel a hypothetical subversive action.''
   The maneuvers will help commanders evaluate the defensive
capacity of the Honduran military, the statement added.
   It said that medical and dental teams from both countries would
provide health care in conjunction with the maneuvers.
   The United States and Honduras have staged about 80 joint
maneuvers involving more than 100,000 U.S. soldiers since signing a
joint defense treaty in 1954.
