<FIRST>u a AM-RacialAttack 2ndLd-Writethru a0747 08-31 0569</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Racial Attack, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0747,0581</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alleged Gunman Surrenders in Brooklyn Racial Slaying</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: SUBS grafs 8-9, `At least ..., with 3 grafs to UPDATE with
23 police injured, no civilian casualties reported, bridge reopened. ^By
LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The suspected gunman in the slaying of a black
teen-ager by a gang of whites surrendered upstate Thursday after an
eight-day manhunt and returned to Brooklyn, where protesters marched
with coffins and clashed with police.
   ``My name is Joseph Fama. The New York City Police Department is
looking for me for murder,'' the 18-year-old was quoted as telling a
police officer about 2:30 a.m. in Oneonta, 150 miles north of New
York City.
   A crowd estimated by police at 7,500, chanting ``No more!'' and
``Whose street? Our street!,'' marched through downtown Brooklyn
during Thursday evening's rush hour. Organizers said the march was
prompted by the Aug. 23 killing of 16-year-old Yusuf Hawkins, who
was buried Wednesday.
   ``This is for the folks who couldn't take off from work
yesterday,'' said Jitu Weusi of the National Black United Front.
   Marchers carried two coffins, symbolizing those of Hawkins and of
Huey Newton, the former Black Panther leader killed in an apparent
drug dispute in Oakland, Calif.
   The march was peaceful until it reached barricades police set up
to keep the protesters off the Brooklyn Bridge. The marchers ran
through the barricades, shouting ``take the bridge, take the
bridge!''
   A shoving match ensued with police at the bridge entrance. Police
beat several marchers with nightsticks, and protesters threw bottles
at officers. Several thousand of the marchers poured onto the bridge
and blocked traffic.
   At least 23 police officers were injured, one requiring 20
stitches to the head, police said. There was no immediate report of
injuries to civilians.
   Police defused the demonstration at 7:30 p.m. by agreeing to
release one of the protest leaders in exchange for the march
breaking up, said Chief Thomas Gallagher.
   Police closed the bridge to traffic in both directions for about
two hours, reopening it around 8:30 p.m.
   ``This was an absolute success!'' Sonny Carson, a black community
leader, proclaimed. ``This will make the city wake up. This will let
the city know that there are young black people who will not take
this any more.''
   Earlier Thursday, when Fama surrendered, he asked for a lawyer
and refused to answer questions, police Inspector Richard Mayronne
said. Fama was returned to Brooklyn to face a lineup and possible
murder charges, authorities said.
   ``He was running like hell, scared to death, and knew we were
breathing on his heels,'' said Police Commissioner Benjamin Ward.
   Six other suspects have been charged in the attack and are out on
bail.
   Hawkins was shot and killed after being ambushed by a gang of up
to 30 white youths carrying bats and golf clubs. He had arrived in
the mostly white neighborhood with three black friends to answer a
used-car ad.
   Police said the gang mistook the blacks for friends of a white
teen-ager whose friendships with blacks had raised tension in the
neighborhood.
   The slaying has prompted calls for justice from such figures as
the Rev. Jesse Jackson, the Rev. Louis Farrakhan and director Spike
Lee, whose film ``Do the Right Thing'' is about racial violence in
Brooklyn.
   Fama told police he was tired of running after hitchhiking from
the city, said Oneonta Police Chief John Donadio.
</TEXT>
