<FIRST>u i AM-Afghanistan-US     08-31 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan-US,0410</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Envoy Keeps Faith with Afghan Rebel Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A special U.S. envoy to the Afghan
resistance promised Thursday that Washington will keep faith with a
fragile rebel government torn by internal feuding.
   Peter Tomsen told a news conference the fractious guerrilla
``interim government'' remained the strongest symbol of the
11-year-old insurgency movement. He conceded, however, that the
internecine fighting within the guerrilla alliance is
``discouraging.''
   The two most powerful rebel groups _ Jamiat-i-Islami and
Hezb-i-Islami _ are fighting with each other in northern Afghanistan.
   On Wednesday, Hezb-i-Islami's charismatic leader, Gulbaddin
Hekmatyar, suspended his role in the rebel government to protest its
failure to hold elections. He is foreign minister of that government.
   Sibghatullah Mojaddidi, an Islamic scholar and president of the
guerrilla interim government, labeled Hekmatyar a ``killer.'' He
said publicly that the vociferously anti-American Hekmatyar has used
U.S.-supplied weapons to kill other guerrillas and other Afghans, a
charge Hekmatyar denied.
   On July 9, Hekmatyar's group was charged with killing 32
Jamiat-i-Islami rebels.
   Washington backs the anti-communist rebels trying to oust Kabul's
ruling Marxist government led by President Najib.
   Tomsen said Moscow has swamped its Afghan communist allies with
military hardware, including medium-range Scud missiles, since
pulling the Red Army out of the Central Asian nation Feb. 15.
   After nine years of military intervention the Kremlin withdrew
more than 110,000 soldiers from Afghanistan in line with a
U.N.-brokered accord.
   Tomsen said since the Soviet troop withdrawal, more than 2,000
Soviet flights loaded with supplies have landed at Kabul airport. He
said 300 Soviet military advisers remain in the Afghan capital.
   Tomsen said the advisers have orchestrated hundreds of Scud
missile firings and that some missiles hit Pakistan. Scud has a
range of up to 170 miles.
   Soviet personnel are also working in key Afghan government
ministries, said Tomsen.
   He blamed the continued fighting in Afghanistan on the Soviet
Union.
   Washington will support a political settlement that removes Najib
and his Marxist People's Democratic Party of Afghanistan from power.
   Millions of dollars in U.S. military and humanitarian help have
gone to the Afghan guerrillas through Pakistan, which also harbors
more than 3 million war refugees.
   Gradually, however, the guerrilla government has been given
direct U.S. aid until now Tomsen said almost 50 percent of all
humanitarian and military help goes directly to it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
