<DOCNO> AP890831-0193 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-89 2247EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Mexico-Mine     08-31 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Mine,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Head Of Bankrupt Mine Arraigned For Fraud</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former director of Mexico's largest copper
mine was arraigned Thursday on charges of defrauding the bankrupt
state company. Thirty-three company officials have been arrested.
   Attorney General Enrique Alvarez del Castillo said Emilio Ocampo
Arenal's actions did not involve the administrative council of the
Cananea mine and that his office will not investigate the full
council.
   ``All of the illegal actions that were taken were without the
consent and without the knowledge of the administrative council.
They were personal actions of the implicated party, and he confessed
that,'' he told a news conference on Thursday.
   Ocampo is accused of embezzling $3 million. He is the son-in-law
of former President Luis Echeverria, who served from 1970-76.
   The miners' union had demanded an investigation of the
Chilean-born Ocampo and other top management. Opposition political
parties also alleged company mismanagement was involved and asked
for an investigation after soldiers forced the open-pit mine to
close down on Aug. 20.
   Alvarez del Castillo said the bankruptcy was not due solely to
mismanagement. ``The bad administration and conspiracy that occurred
obviously caused damage. That is one of the reasons,'' he said.
   His office said in a statement earlier that Ocampo admitted ``to
illegally authorizing contracts to obtain personal benefit of 5
percent of authorized sales'' from 1983-89.
   Closing of the mine, 25 miles south of the Arizona border, threw
3,200 miners out of work. It came one week before the mineworkers
had scheduled a strike to press for a 330 percent wage-and-benefit
increase.
   The government, which owns 90 percent of the operation, is
seeking a buyer for the insolvent mine.
</TEXT>
