<FIRST>r w AM-US-SovietLawmakers     08-31 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Soviet Lawmakers,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>EDS: Retransmitting a0745 to include AMs cycle designator.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Soviet Legislators Want Electronic Voting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet lawmakers here observing the workings of
U.S. government said Thursday they want the same authority that
Congress has in order to curb the power of executive government
officials in Moscow.
   ``Unfortunately, many good ideas'' for Soviet democracy such as
legislative oversight over the military and the KGB secret police
still lack support to become law, said Konstantin Lubenchenko,
leader of the six-member delegation of the Supreme Soviet.
   Lubenchenko, deputy chairman of the Supreme Soviet's committee on
constitutionality and legislative reform, said many Old Guard
deputies in his country's legislative body refuse to even vote on
such proposals.
   ``When the question of roll call arises, two-thirds of the
deputies oppose letting the voters know how they voted, and until
today the proposal is blocked,'' said another Supreme Soviet member,
Andrei E. Sebentsov.
   The delegation is studying the adoption of time-saving U.S.
electronic voting systems ``that will make it possible for every
voter to know how his deputy voted,'' Sebentsov said. ``This may be
hard for some deputies to get used to, but they're going to have
to.''
   Addressing a news conference here, the Soviet lawmakers said they
are determined to convert their country to a genuine democracy
despite entrenched resistence and potentials for setbacks.
   ``People in all groups of society favor moving toward greater
democracy _ farmers, intellectuals, the working class, young people,
the middle-aged _ and this is a very powerful force,'' Lubenchenko
said.
   `` ... We are building from the ground level, like bricklayers
... without a good blueprint, but with great desire to build a good
house,'' he said. ``To draw the blueprint we have come to study the
U.S. model, and not only the U.S. but also (European) continental
parliaments.''
   The Soviet lawmakers' three-week visit is being sponsored by the
American Committee on U.S.-Soviet Relations, an independent
non-partisan educational group, and the International Foundation, a
philanthropic organization.
   The visitors have met with numerous congressional staff and
support officials and next week will meet legislators and witness
Congress in action.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
