<FIRST>u a AM-TropicalWeather 1stLd-Writethru a0697 08-31 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tropical Weather, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0697,0240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Weak Storms in Far Atlantic</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with Hurricane Gabrielle forming, 10:30
p.m. EDT positions; no pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The fourth hurricane of the season formed Thursday
in the eastern Atlantic with forecasters predicting gradual
strengthening, and a tropical storm also churned across open water
with winds remaining steady.
   Hurricane Gabrielle, which intensified as it pushed away from the
African coast, had maximum sustained winds of about 75 mph with
higher gusts in squalls, said forecasters at the National Hurrican
Center in suburban Coral Gables.
   At 10:30 p.m. EDT, Gabrielle was centered near 11.4 north
latitude and 32.0 west longitude, or about 540 miles southwest of
Sal in the Cape Verdes, moving west at 17 mph.
   Forecasters expected Gabrielle would slow down as it increases in
strength by Friday. There is no danger Gabrielle hitting land for
several days, said forecasters.
   Tropical Storm Felix, meanwhile, maintained winds of 40 mph to
keep it just above official storm status.
   At 10:30 p.m. EDT, Felix was near 30.8 north latitude and 40.8
west longitude, or about 785 miles southwest of the Azores moving to
the west northwest at 17 mph. A turn to the north is expected Friday
or Saturday with little change in strength.
   A tropical storm becomes a hurricane when sustained winds hit 74
mph. The Atlantic hurricane season runs from June 1 to Nov. 30.
</TEXT>
