<FIRST>u i AM-DrugMeeting     08-31 0342</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Meeting,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drug Enforcement Meeting Praises Colombian Battle</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Colombia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TALLI NAUMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nine Latin American countries holding a
drug-enforcement conference on Thursday praised Colombia for its
battle against narcotics traffickers.
   ``The meeting expresses its profound appreciation to the people
and government of Colombia for the resolute and vigorous way in
which they are combating drug trafficking in their country,''
Mexico's Javier Coello Trejo told the closing session.
   He is assistant attorney general and heads Mexico's narcotics
program.
   Colombia imposed curfews in Medellin and eight nearby towns on
Wednesday in its strong crackdown on the narcotics trade. Drug
traffickers have waged a 2-week-old wave of assassinations, arson
and bombings.
   Representatives of the Bahamas, Belize, Costa Rica, the Dominican
Republic, El Salvador, Guatemala, Honduras, Jamaica and Mexico
signed a letter of praise to Colombia at the end of a three-day
meeting.
   They gathered to prepare the agenda for the 8th International
Drug Enforcement Conference, to be held in Mexico in April 1990.
   Mexican Attorney General Enrique Alvarez del Castillo said the
Colombian violence will not be repeated in Mexico.
   He said the United States was more likely to experience drug
violence.
   ``We're strong, and we want to fight (drug trafficking), and we
will,'' he said, adding that ``Mexico has very good prospects'' for
controlling drug trafficking, but the problem must be confronted
with international coordination.
   Delegates agreed on 20 resolutions, among them the ``need to
unite efforts in a common front as an effective instrument in the
fight against drug trafficking.''
   They said drug production, trafficking and addiction are crimes
that affect humanity in general ``and should be deemed an affair of
state and of national security,'' Coello Trejo reported.
   The meeting adopted a resolution recommending that drug laws be
modernized and enforced, with stiffer penalties. It also advocated
raising salaries of personnel in the drug fight.
   The attorney general said ``all of society'' must be involved in
the struggle.
   Delegates agreed to meet again in January in Santo Domingo, the
Dominican Republic.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
