<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-89 0755EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e PM-APArts:EdinburghFestival Adv04   08-31 0717</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP Arts: Edinburgh Festival, Adv 04,0733</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 04</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon PMs, Sept 4 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>American Bombs Light Up the Edinburgh Fringe</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Cristofer is CQ in 3rd graf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT WOLF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDINBURGH, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two plays that flopped in New York are
delighting critics and audiences at the Edinburgh Festival Fringe,
vindicating the faith of a producer with a fondness for ``problem
plays.''
   To be sure, the 422 plays on offer in the 43rd annual Festival
Fringe include the usual number of American classics and Broadway
hits, from ``Long Day's Journey Into Night'' to more recent works
including ``Agnes of God'' and ``Night, Mother.''
   But two plays that were original also-rans are unexpectedly
coming up trumps: Edward Albee's ``The Man Who Had Three Arms'' and
Michael Cristofer's ``The Lady and the Clarinet.''
   Both plays, which were New York flops in the early 1980s, have
won The Scotsman newspaper's coveted Fringe First awards, given
weekly to the best of the Fringe's many openings during the
Festival's three weeks.
   ``Edinburgh is a place where people feel able to see stuff over
again, to make a re-evaluation,'' said Harold Easton, the New
York-based producer of ``Lady and the Clarinet.''
   The play, about the amorous foibles of a woman named Luba,
starred Stockard Channing in its off-Broadway production in 1983.
This time, with British actress Imelda Staunton as Luba, the play is
selling out at the 72-seat Netherbow Center playhouse.
   On Sept. 12, it transfers to London's King's Head Theater for a
month, with a further transfer to the commercial West End likely to
follow.
   ``It's not Shakespeare; it's not great social drama. (But) it is
more than just a funny play,'' said Easton, who believes the play
was undervalued in its New York debut. ``I was surprised it hadn't
fared better there.''
   Easton has been at the Fringe for eight years as executive
producer of the American Festival Theater, a producing organization
devoted to a cross-section of American plays.
   ``I've always liked to take on problem plays _ plays that haven't
had whatever reception you think they should have had,'' he said.
   Critics in London and Edinburgh have reaffirmed his faith in
Cristofer, who is at work on the screenplay of Tom Wolfe's novel
``Bonfire of the Vanities.'' John Peter in The Sunday Times of
London called ``Lady'' a ``spick-and-span little play, brilliantly
acted by everyone.'' Michael Coveney in The Financial Times thought
it ``zippy,'' and said Staunton was ``wonderful.''
   Lynn Morrow, director of the Southside International production
of Edward Albee's ``Man Who Had Three Arms,'' similarly refused to
be swayed by her play's previous fate.
   ``I think this is an exciting, really wonderful play,'' said
Morrow, a professor of English at Albright College in Reading, Pa.
She described her contribution as ``getting the play out of the
drawer,'' following its frosty Broadway reception in 1983.
   Morrow first mounted the three-character play at an Albee
Festival last November and decided then to bring it to Edinburgh.
The author is best known for ``Who's Afraid of Virginia Woolf?'' and
``The Zoo Story,'' plays of the 1960s that are also being revived at
this year's Fringe.
   Critic Colin Affleck, writing in The Scotsman, called ``Man'' a
remarkable play, and the same newspaper quoted Albee in a
long-distance interview as saying he was ecstatic with its local
reception in light of his ``long war with the drama critics of the
United States.''
   Morrow said her staging was probably more ``audience-friendly''
than the strident, haranguing production so coolly received in New
York _ a production she did not see.
   ``The original production was a little more hostile to the
audience, and the critics were lying in wait for him (Albee),'' she
said. The play is structured around a lecture given by a man who
mysteriously grows a third arm one day and then watches it shrink.
   ``What Albee does is make us question our own value system,''
said Morrow. ``I think the play is brilliant.''
   Not every unsung American play has its reputation restored in
Scotland. Beth Henley's ``The Wake of Jamey Foster,'' a short-lived
Broadway entry early this decade, got mixed-to-poor reviews at this
year's Fringe, and David Rabe's ``Hurlyburly,'' a Broadway success,
was denounced in The Scotsman as ``exploitative, bad-mouthed, and
boring.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
