<HEAD>$Adv01-03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Sept. 1-3, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Jackie Mason Tries Sitcom After Stand-Up</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bill Cosby. Roseanne Barr. Now Jackie Mason?
   Marcy Carsey and Tom Werner, the producers who put the Cos and
Roseanne together with successful sitcoms, are trying for another
with Mason, fresh from a hit one-man show on Broadway that restarted
his career.
   Mason plays Jackie Fisher, who has just quit his 20-year job as a
pajama salesman and is sharing his apartment temporarily with his
mother, Bea (Rita Karin). She looks askance on his affair with
Maddie, the Catholic neighbor (Lynn Redgrave), a widow with three
children.
   Bea wants Jackie to settle down with a nice Jewish girl and
doesn't take well to the news that he and Maddie are dating: ``Why
can't you be gay like everyone else?''
   At the beginning and end of the show, Jackie goes up on the roof
to deliver his stand-up routine to the audience. ``I always talk to
myself,'' he explains. ``I like to deal with a better class of
people.''
   With its heavy emphasis on ethnicity, ``Chicken Soup'' won't be
everyone's cup of noodles, but it will probably be a modest hit,
slotted as it is behind ``Roseanne'' on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
