<FIRST>a e BC-FallTV-PeaceableKingdom Adv01-03   08-31 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Fall TV-Peaceable Kingdom, Adv 01-03,0260</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv01-03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Sept. 1-3, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>`Peaceable Kingdom' Should Rest in Peace'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   What you want to see in CBS' zoo drama
``Peaceable Kingdom'' is a lot more of the animals and a lot less of
the people.
   Lindsay Wagner (``Bionic Woman'') plays Rebecca Cafferty, the new
director of a large metropolitan zoo who is struggling to meet the
conflicting demands of research science, animal welfare and city
budgets.
   But Rebecca is resourceful. To extract quick disaster assistance
money from a balking bureaucrat, she whips a tiny monkey out of her
purse at lunch.
   But animal rights activists shouldn't worry. This series would
make anybody like animals more than the people.
   Another veteran of bad network televsion, Tom Wopat (``Dukes of
Hazzard''), plays Rebecca's brother, conveniently the curator of
mammals at the zoo. Wopat, a country-western singer, croons to the
lions. Luckily, they don't attack.
   Rebecca also has three children, 16, 12 and 6, who are variously
delighted and chagrined at living on the zoo grounds. ``Face it,
Mom, it's a zoo around here,'' notes one after a visiting seal
breaks a vase.
   Opening CBS' Wednesday lineup, ``Peaceable Kingdom'' is a
candidate for first show to be canceled. It might have had a better
shot with less Wopat and more wombat.
   As Rebecca says in a moment of profound wisdom: ``The lion is
dead. Don't take it out on the gorillas.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sept. 1-3</NOTE>
