<DOCNO> AP890831-0213 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-89 1414EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-FallTV-Others Adv01-03   08-31 0647</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Fall TV-Others, Adv 01-03,0672</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv01-03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Sept. 1-3, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Shows Not Available for Previewing Might Hold Some Surprises</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Fall TV</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Several new network shows weren't available for
screening in their entirety, pre-season. AP Television Writer
Kathryn Baker looked at the casts, producers and plotlines for clues
to how they might do.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Snoops</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   CBS' ``Snoops'' stars Tim and Daphne Maxwell Reid, late of
``Frank's Place'' as TV husband-and-wife in this hour comedy-drama
set in Washington, D.C. He is a noted professor of criminology at
Georgetown University. She is a protocol officer with the State
Department. Together, they solve matters of international intrigue
and just plain, old crimes. ``Snoops'' goes up against NBC's
bikini-clad ``Baywatch'' on Fridays.
 
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Island Son</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Miniseries regular Richard Chamberlain returns to series
television, once again as a doctor _ he played ``Dr. Kildare'' in
the 1960s _ in CBS' ``Island Son.'' Who wouldn't have been lured
back to the weekly grind with a show set in Hawaii? Chamberlain
plays Daniel Kulani, a doctor at a large Honolulu hospital, who was
adopted at birth by a native Hawaiian couple and has a Hawaiian
businessman brother. Little is known about the show, but one of the
co-executive producers, Nigel McKeand, wrote for ``The Waltons'' and
``Family.'' ``Island Son'' goes up against NBC's ``Midnight Caller''
and ABC's ``thirtysomething'' on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Rescue 911</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   CBS will try to match NBC's success with ``Unsolved Mysteries''
by launching its own ``reality-based'' series, ``Rescue 911,''
featuring graphic re-creations of actual emergency calls. It is too
graphic for its early time period on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Free Spirit</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The most unlikely sitcom of the new season is ABC's ``Free
Spirit,'' starring Corinne Bohrer as Winnie the Witch, housekeeper
to a stern single dad and his three young children. This one will
need a magic wand. One of the co-executive producers' credits
include ``Diff'rent Strokes'' ``Women in Prison'' and ``Facts of
Life.'' ``Free Spirit'' should be a free agent soon. It goes up
against CBS' ``Murder, She Wrote'' and NBC's ``Sister Kate'' on
Sundays.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Living Dolls</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Another ABC sitcom looks a little more promising. ``Living
Dolls,'' about four young models sharing a New York apartment, is
something of a spinoff of ``Who's the Boss?'' Tony Danza and Alyssa
Milano will make occasional guest appearances. Michael Learned
(``The Waltons'') plays a former model who serves as the girls' den
mother. ``Living Dolls'' goes in on Saturday after ``Mr. Belvedere.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>The Young Riders</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Also a possibility is ABC's new Western ``The Young Riders,'' the
story of the young men who rode Pony Express. The cast is a passel
of newcomers, except for Josh Brolin. Creator-supervising producer
Ed Spielman also created the 1970s Eastern Western ``Kung Fu.''
``The Young Riders'' gets the Thursday time period opposite NBC's
comedies, but with its kid-appeal, it might last long enough to see
the sunset.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Mancuso, FBI</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   NBC is rounding out its all-new Friday lineup with two shows
derived from successful TV movies of last season. Robert Loggia
reprises his role as the rough-edged FBI agent Nick Mancuso that he
created in the political thriller ``Favorite Son.'' ``Mancuso, FBI''
looks like a good bet as a politically sophisticated crime drama
that could attract a cult following, a la ``Wiseguy.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Baywatch</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Starting out Friday is ``Baywatch,'' a silly lifeguard drama that
the alarmists among us can take as more evidence that civilization,
as well as the beach, is eroding. Watch. It'll be a hit. The rerun
of last season's movie was in the top 10 in the Nielsens. David
Hasselhoff (``Knight Rider''), Parker Stevenson (``Hardy Boys''),
and former Miss Universe Shawn Weatherly (``OceanQuest'') star as
the scantily clad protagonists. Here's irony for you: This is the
only show on the schedule from ballyhooed GTG Entertainment, the new
production company established by Grant ``Quality Television''
Tinker, former chairman of NBC.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sept. 1-3</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890831-0214 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-89 1411EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s w BC-DrugWar-Survivor'sStory Adv03   08-31 0895</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Drug War-Survivor's Story, Adv 03,0915</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Sept. 3, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Businessman Relates Escape From Drug World After 20 Years of Crime</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX10 of Aug. 31</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAMARA HENRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When James Lee left prison five years ago, no
one believed he was a changed man. After all, Lee began smoking
marijuana at age 13 and graduated to snorting cocaine and heroin at
14, feeding an appetite for drugs that for two decades dictated a
life of crime.
   ``I knew the ins and outs of drugs,'' he says, explaining that as
a youngster he had seen the debilitating effects of illicit drug
use, ``but it was the slick thing to do. I wanted to belong, to do
what everybody else was doing at the time.''
   So at 13, he began an involvement with drugs that would last
almost 20 years.
   Now a successful businessman who spends his free time speaking at
churches and counseling inmates at the Lorton correctional
facilities in suburban Virginia, Lee says he is committed to help
others change the dead-end course of their lives.
   ``My whole life had been filled with drugs'' and hustling, said
the 45-year-old Lee, whose closely cropped hair now has an even mix
of gray.
   Occasional use of marijuana, then cocaine and heroin, became an
obsession by age 15, and ``that's when the crimes increased because
I had to get drugs every day,'' he said.
   At first, money for the drugs came from petty thefts and what he
described as ``yoke robberies'' _ strong-arm robberies or holdups
without weapons.
   Despite all of this, Lee continued to attend school and to
conceal his drug habit and crimes from his mother, a Christian who
demanded church attendance. Most of the expensive clothes and
jewelry he bought with his ill-gotten money were stored at friends'
houses.
   Lee's first car at age 16 _ a 1964 Mustang that then held the
same prestige as today's BMW _ was parked around corners and in
friends' garages and driveways.
   ``Robbery was the thing in the '60s; we went from bank robbery to
robbing private businesses,'' said Lee, whose first adult arrest
came in the summer of 1966 when he joined some friends who hijacked
a truck full of merchandise. The charges were later dropped.
   His profession as a thief ended in April 1968 when Lee was
arrested for felony murder after an accomplice shot a clerk during a
postal robbery. While waiting 18 months in jail to go to trial, he
met two men from New York who convinced him that selling drugs would
reap greater profits faster.
   So when charges again were dropped, Lee headed for New York,
where his friends ``introduced me to a new hustle, selling drugs.''
   ``The money came so fast, there was no comparison'' with money
from the robberies, said Lee. ``That's part of the problem today.
The money is fast. There is no money in the world faster than drug
money.''
   Lee's success was meteoric. ``I was able to acquire a grocery
store, a new home, an apartment building, new cars, fine clothes,
jewelry and traveled around the world. I met people that put me in a
position to get more and better drugs.''
   But as his business skyrocketed, so did his craving for drugs.
``I went from snorting drugs to shooting drugs because I had a raw
habit,'' he said. ``When you become your best customer, you become
unreliable, as far as the supplier is concerned, as far as paying
money back.''
   Lee's drug suppliers entrusted him with smaller and smaller
amounts of drugs, dropping from 10 kilograms down to five kilos and
then three. He also had frequent skirmishes with the law and was
convicted four times on drug charges.
   ``When you know people, getting drugs or going to jail wasn't a
problem to me because my life pattern never had to change,'' said
Lee, explaining that drugs were ``just as plentiful in jail as on
the streets, if not more plentiful.''
   Lee, who married at age 17, said his son brought him drugs in
prison, concealing them in tennis balls or using other ingenious
smuggling techniques.
   ``My last arrest had me facing 60 years in jail,'' Lee said, but
he was sentenced to only 20 months-to-five years at Lorton.
   It was during his last incarceration that Lee met several
Christian inmates who persuaded him to change his life. After his
release, he was still viewed skeptically by his family, especially
his wife who had left him three years into the marriage.
   ``People didn't want to believe it. They've heard before I'd
changed and then I'd come out and do the same thing,'' he said.
``But the longer I stayed out the more they had to re-evaluate
whether or not I was serious.''
   Lee's family began to respect his commitment. Then in April 1988,
his 24-year-old son, a dealer himself, was killed on the street,
shot nine times. Lee said he successfully suppressed his urge to
retaliate against his son's murderers.
   Today, Lee is production manager of a print shop in Reston, Va.,
making $40,000 a year that he can spend ``without worrying about the
police kicking my door in.''
   After a 20-year separation, Lee and his wife reunited last
November and live in suburban Maryland.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Sept. 3</NOTE>
</DOC>
