<DOCNO> AP890831-0215 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-89 1710EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-DrugWar-Fortune Adv03   08-31 0719</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Drug War-Fortune, Adv 03,0737</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Sept. 3, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>The White Powder Road to the High Life</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD POWERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When law officers arrested high school dropout
Thomas ``Tony Montana'' Mickens just a month short of his 25th
birthday, they gawped openly at his $730,000 Long Island home and
fleet of luxury cars.
   This was no Wall Street financier or wunderkind film producer.
Like many young people seeking their share of the American dream,
Mickens amassed his fortune the new-fashioned way _ he sold cocaine.
   His 100-employee, multimillion-dollar operation was based in the
New York City neighborhood of Laurelton, the working-class section
of south Queens where Mickens grew up. His headquarters was the
corner of Merrick Boulevard and 226th Street, but he also sold drugs
in Harlem and Atlantic City.
   The Mickens operation wasn't the largest in drug-infested south
Queens. But authorities said it was one of the most sophisticated.
   ``How many 25-year-olds do you know who can accumulate so much
wealth and know how to launder illegal money?'' one investigator
said after Mickens' arrest last year.
   Two months ago a Brooklyn federal jury convicted him of 16 counts
of drug conspiracy, tax evasion and money laundering. He faces
sentences totaling 220 years of prison time.
   Defense lawyer Robert Simels maintains his client's innocence. He
argues that the fabulous wealth was left by Mickens' late father,
said to be a big-time Queens numbers runner.
   But Andrew J. Maloney, the U.S. attorney for the Eastern District
of New York, said Mickens personally cleared at least $2.5 million
in cocaine profits in the 3{ years before his arrest. Like other
young drug kingpins, Mickens spent it freely and lavishly, Maloney
said.
   In Mickens' circle, incredible sums of money changed hands,
packed in bags and shoeboxes. With sacks of cash and stacks of money
orders, Mickens bought a $100,000 custom Rolls-Royce equipped with a
pair of television sets, VCRs and videogames. He maintained a fleet
of sporty, expensive cars _ BMWs, Porsches, Ferraris and
Mercedes-Benzes _ in which the popular young man took neighborhood
kids for rides.
   ``He was the big talk of Laurelton,'' said a teen-age
neighborhood girl, who declined to give her name. ``They'd talk
about his cars, and how `fly' they were, how nice.''
   Mickens took his moniker from Tony Montana, the violent,
high-living cocaine-addicted gangster portrayed by actor Al Pacino
in ``Scarface,'' prosecutors said. ``He tried to model his existence
after that character,'' said Capt. Charles Mattes of the Queens
narcotics squad.
   His fascination with the movie was complete: he named his
businesses after Tony Montana, and several copies of ``Scarface''
were found in Mickens' home and in his limousine.
   Agents who arrested Mickens at his home in exclusive Dix Hills
were amazed to find a Jacuzzi for 10 and a spiral staircase that
ended at a fully outfitted workout gym.
   He wore fancy clothes and gold jewelry and owned homes in Florida
and California, where he docked his 38-foot-long yacht.
   ``That someone so young could become a multimillionaire by
selling cocaine shows how tempting and lucrative the business is,''
said Assistant U.S. Attorney Patricia A. Pileggi.
   Prosecutors said Mickens showed financial savvy in making his
purchases and hiding his income. Much of his property was registered
under false names or by his girlfriend, Shelby Kearney, who was
convicted of helping him launder money. Major purchases were made in
installments under $10,000 to avoid federal financial reporting
requirements.
   Unlike most drug dealers, Mickens' empire went beyond the cocaine
trade: He owned several stores, the Gold Coast Lounge, Montana Dry
Cleaners, all of which _ along with the houses, boat and cars _ were
seized by the government.
   Montana Sporting Goods, one of those companies, sponsored a team
in a summer basketball league in St. Albans, Queens. Mickens also
coached the team; among the players was Mark Jackson, guard for the
New York Knicks.
   Mickens ``enjoyed a good reputation for truthfulness and
honesty,'' Jackson said in testimony at Mickens' trial.
   Others also defended him. An old friend told New York Newsday
that wealth notwithstanding, Mickens had not changed very much.
   He was still ``one of the guys, not Tommy the drug dealer, just
cool Tommy the guy we grew up with.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Sept. 3</NOTE>
</DOC>
