<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-89 1419EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-FallTV-DoogieHowser Adv01-03 1stLd-Writethru 08-31 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Fall TV-Doogie Howser, Adv 01-03, 1st Ld-Writethru, b0536,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv01-03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Sept. 1-3, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Unusual `Doogie Howser' Casts 16-Year-old As Doctor</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf to add dropped first name of Harris</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No one can accuse Steven Bochco of resorting
to stale, old formulas with ``Doogie Howser, M.D.''
   In the pilot, our hero interrupts his driving test to administer
emergency medical aid at the scene of a traffic accident. So why is
a doctor just now getting his driver's license? He's only 16.
   The half-hour ``dramedy'' is the first show to derive from
Bochco's multimillion-dollar development deal with ABC.
   ``Howser'' is a well-made show but it remains to be seen what
audience will take to an offbeat pairing of adult and teen themes.
In the pilot, Doogie wins his first kiss and loses his first patient.
   The series is slotted in a decidedly adult time period, replacing
Bochco's other dramedy, ``Hooperman,'' on Wednesday.
   Bochco says it is feasible that a child genius, who graduated
from Princeton at 10, could have a medical license at 16. The
premise interested him because his late father was a violin prodigy.
   Neil Patrick Harris is an excellent actor, and taking the same
character in and out of parallel lives is kind of interesting,
dramatically.
   But do we want to watch Doogie make life-and-death decisions at
the hospital, then come home and sulk because his father (James B.
Sikking) won't loan him the car?
   Bochco has tried to do something different here, but it has ended
up just being kind of weird.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sept. 1-3</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890831-0217 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-89 1704EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s w BC-WalterMears Adv03   08-31 0867</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Walter Mears, Adv 03,0888</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sun Sept. 3 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Declaring Drug War is Easy, Fighting One is Not</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WALTER R. MEARS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With no secret weapons available, the strategy
President Bush sets Tuesday night for the war on drugs will foretell
a long struggle in the trenches. That is going to demand patience,
persistence and drudgery, long after the drama of a nationally
televised re-declaration of war has faded.
   The government has declared war on drugs before. Bush has
commanded such an effort before. And the government has reported
some progress, but against a changing and growing target. Now, as
president, Bush is setting a course to redeem a campaign pledge
underscored in his inaugural address:
   ``Take my word for it: this scourge will stop.''
   As Bush outlines his drug-fighting program in an address to the
nation, Americans are said to be ready to make war on drugs whatever
the cost, even if it takes a tax increase. Bush has said it won't,
that the needed funds will be shifted from other programs.
   ``In key ways today, the American people are in a wartime mode
and sense a national emergency in the drug crisis,'' said George
Gallup Jr., reporting on an early summer poll his organization
conducted for the drug-fighting effort.
   That sense of crisis has since been heightened by the Colombian
government crackdown on the drug lords blamed for the murder of a
presidential candidate there, and said to be responsible for about
80 percent of the cocaine flowing into the United States.
   Bush already is sending $65 million worth of arms and equipment
to help the Colombians combat the drug cartels. The broader
administration program will propose up to $260 million in economic
and military drug-fighting aid to Colombia, Bolivia and Peru.
   Bush is presenting a strategy report required by the law that set
up the Office of National Drug Control Policy, the new agency
William Bennett heads. Bush could have left the report to his drug
czar; by delivering it himself, in his first nationally televised
address from the White House, the president puts the drug crisis at
the top of his autumn agenda.
   There's likely to be more drama in the medium than in the
message. Bennett has said again and again that there is no magic
bullet to be fired in the drug battle. His report sets goals far
more cautious than the rhetoric of the Bush campaign or inaugural
address _ a 10 percent reduction in drug use in the next two years;
50 percent in 10 years.
   The tools include increased federal aid to local law enforcement
agencies; more prisons to house drug offenders; tougher and more
certain punishment; more funds for drug education and treatment;
interdiction efforts that will increase the role of the U.S.
military.
   During the 1988 campaign, Bush advocated execution of big-time
drug dealers. ``For those who commit drug-related murders, for the
drug kingpins who are poisoning our kids, the penalty should be
death,'' he said. ``If this is war then let's treat it as such.
Let's get these killers off the streets.''
   That proposal has not been mentioned in advance discussion of the
drug strategy report.
   All told, the administration plan would cost an estimated $8
billion, about $2 billion over the current budget for the programs
involved.
   There will be debate on whether that's enough, how much should be
spent, and how it should be used.
   Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del., chairman of the Judiciary Committee
and a prime sponsor of the bill that created the new drug policy
agency, has complained that the government so far hasn't been
willing to pay what's needed to fight the drug epidemic. ``We have
no war on drugs,'' he told a mid-August conference of corrections
officers. ``We need a D-Day, we don't need another Vietnam.''
   Biden, who is to deliver a Democratic response to Bush after the
president speaks Tuesday night, proposed this week that the United
States set up a system of debt relief for Latin nations that
subsidize shifts away from the coca crops that are the raw material
of cocaine.
   The Gallup survey, conducted in June and July and donated to the
drug agency, reflected a D-Day mood. The poll of 1,005 adults and
500 teen-agers showed that Americans consider drugs to be the most
serious problem facing the nation, with no other single concern even
coming close.
   Gallup said the survey showed a public willingness to sacrifice
as in wartime, with a majority favoring increased spending to combat
drugs and willing to pay higher taxes if necessary.
   By all those measures, the Bush address comes at prime time on
the calendar as well as the clock, to a nation fed up with the drug
crisis and ready for action.
   That bodes well for the send-off. The greater challenge may come
in finding the staying power for a drug war that won't end any time
soon.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Walter R. Mears, vice president and columnist for
The Associated Press, has reported on Washington and national
politics for more than 25 years.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sun AMs Sept. 3</NOTE>
</DOC>
