<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--VirginStand Adv04   08-31 0782</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--Virgin Stand, Adv 04,0802</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv04</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday, Sept. 4, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Spared By Man, Virgin Stand of Spruce Is Battered By Nature</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL MOKRZYCKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURG, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The hulking roots of a toppled tree,
covered by lush moss and surrounded by saplings, symbolize the
extremes of life and death in one of North America's last virgin
stands of spruce and balsam fir.
   The 110-acre stand, on the Connecticut River headwaters six miles
from Canada, has faced threats from nature as well as man in the
past century. What is left, owned by The Nature Conservancy, is in
many places not a pretty sight.
   Saved by man from logging operations but ravaged by the great
hurricane of 1938 and a spruce budworm attack in the early 1970s,
the towering spruce trees, some estimated to be 350 years old, are
few and far between.
   ``It looks sad up there now after the budworm. It was so pretty
up there before,'' said Fred Cowan, a paper company forester
instrumental in saving the stand situated at Norton Pool on East
Inlet Brook.
   The boggy lowlands are not ideal for spruce and fir, and more
impressive specimens can be found elsewhere, said Fred's son, John.
But at Norton Pool, he said, ``the idea is that they haven't been
trashed.
   ``You can see what nature does to itself, too. ... It killed its
own trees, and there's thick regeneration coming up underneath.''
   The stand's inaccessibility _ it's 50 miles north of the state's
last stoplight _ has helped protect it through the ages. It faced
its first threat in recorded times, from lumbering, in the late
1800s.
   The Connecticut Valley Lumber Company bought it as part of
125,000 acres of timberland in 1888, and reached East Inlet 10 years
later. The 10,000-acre East Inlet watershed had never been cut, but
its spruce was in demand.
   The spring of 1898 was extremely dry, however, and the loggers
were unable to float logs down to mills and railroads. After a few
weeks, they gave up.
   There was a budworm onslaught from about 1910 to 1915, though it
wasn't nearly as serious as the infestation in the 1970s. The tiny
worms, which later become moths, eat spruce and fir needles,
sometimes killing the trees.
   Nature again wrought havoc in the hurricane of September 1938.
Fred Cowan estimated that at least 25 percent of the spruce and even
more of the fir were blown down or broken. Cowan observed the
destruction for the first time in 1941 when, at age 23, he was in
the first St. Regis Paper Co. team surveying to mark trees for
cutting. St. Regis had bought Connecticut Valley Lumber in 1926.
   ``Sometimes we seemed to go a quarter of a mile climbing on top
of blown-down trees. ... You'd be perhaps 10, 15, 20 feet in the
air, climbing over that stuff.'' The team recognized that the trees
still standing were special, he said. ``Most of us hadn't been in
large old-growth stands before.''
   St. Regis began cutting in East Inlet in the late 1940s, though
not in the area later protected. By the 1950s, with pressure
increasing to cut the huge trees, Cowan and some colleagues began
plotting actively to spare it.
   ``Some of us kind of decided, `Gee, you know, let's kind of skip
around that. We can always get back get to it. That's what we had to
tell some of the other people in the company who said, `Why did you
bypass that?'''
   The Audubon Society and other conservation groups began
expressing interest in saving the area that also held rare birds and
plants. In the late 1960s, St. Regis agreed to save the stand, but
St. Regis and Champion International Corp., which took it over in
1984, for years declined to give the stand to the groups, saying the
company was taking care of it. Champion eventually deeded the land
to The Nature Conservancy in July 1987.
   By then, nature had wreaked havoc.
   In 1974, masses of budworms swept into the region in a five-year
infestation. ``Lots of places, very close to 100 percent of the fir
got picked off, and a lot of the other growth, the small trees
underneath,'' Cowan said. ``The spruce was a little bit more
resistant to it, but it got hit badly up there. It really spoiled
the looks of it.''
   But Cowan remains philosophical about Norton Pool's future.
   ``In this part of the world, things are both man and nature, and
unless they pave it over, nature recovers,'' he said. ``Another 100
years or so and it'll look good again.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sept. 4</NOTE>
