<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--What'sNew-Grizzlies Adv04   08-31 0394</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--What's New-Grizzlies, Adv 04,0401</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv04</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday, Sept. 4, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Grizzly Removal From Threatened Species List Expected</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grizzly bears in
Yellowstone National Park and nearby forests are bouncing back from
a brush with extinction and should be off the threatened-species
list within a decade.
   But the long-term prognosis is uncertain because bear habitat
continues to be pressured by development interests, either for
resources or recreation, said Chris Servheen of the U.S. Fish and
Wildlife Service. ``All those pressures will continue in grizzly
bear habitat. They'll never go away.''
   In the short term, Servheen said, the number of bears with cubs
during the last four years has been good, bears are more dispersed,
mortality rates are down and, perhaps most important, few bears are
seeking human food sources.
   However, agencies managing bears will need to continue working to
protect the grizzlies and their habitat, he said. ``As soon as we
say they're recovered and we drop our guard, we'll be in a crisis
situation again.''
   Two decades ago, grizzly bears fed largely at dumps in and near
the park. In the early 1970s, the dumps were closed, a controversial
move that forced the bears to go ``cold turkey'' off human food
sources. Many continued to seek food from humans, leading to
encounters the bears rarely won; so many were killed in the 1970s
that there is no accurate count, but some put it at well over 100.
   Wildlife agencies and communities fenced dumps and garbage areas,
campers were required to keep food out of bears' reach, bears _
especially females of reproductive age _ were moved, and public
education campaigns were begun.
   Now, Servheen said, ``The goal is in sight. When we started,
there was so much to do that the didn't know where to start. We've
come a long way.''
   It still could be several years before there is serious
discussion of removing the grizzly from the threatened-species list,
he said.
   Michael Scott of The Wilderness Society said much of the bears'
future depends on the Forest Service. ``Biologists agree that the
limiting factor for grizzlies is security and bears are thriving in
Yellowstone because they are secure. ... The pressures are ever
going to increase around Yellowstone, whether it's a new mine, a new
resort or timber sales.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sept. 4</NOTE>
