<FIRST>r f PM-BuildingContracts     08-31 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Building Contracts,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Construction Contracts Up In July</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rebound in public works projects helped push
the level of new construction contracts nationwide up by 2 percent
during July, a survey found.
   The survey, by the F.W. Dodge Group of McGraw-Hill Information
Services Co., found that overall construction last month rose to an
annual rate of $256.6 billion, a three-month high, Dodge said
Wednesday. That followed a 2 percent drop in June.
   Contracts for public works and utilities construction jumped 5
percent in July to an annual rate of $45.7 billion. July contracts
for new non-residential buildings, mainly commercial, industrial and
institutional structures, rose 2 percent to $91.8 billion.
   But residential home contracts were up a modest 1 percent, with
multifamily houses and hotels declining slightly and single-family
homes advancing 2 percent.
   ``It's still early to be looking for a surge of one family
housing in response to falling mortgage rates, as July's data bear
out,'' said George A. Christie, the Dodge group's vice president and
chief economist.
   ``In another month or two, when inventory of unsold new homes is
worked down and recession fears subside, conditions will be right
for a solid recovery of homebuilding.''
   For the first seven months of this year the unadjusted total of
all newly started construction was $149.8 billion, off 1 percent
from the same period a year ago.
</TEXT>
