<FIRST>r f PM-Ardent-Stellar     08-31 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ardent-Stellar,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ardent, Stellar Announce Merger Agreement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stellar Computer Inc. and Japanese-backed rival
Ardent Computer Corp., money-losing makers of high-powered graphics
computers, announced they have agreed to merge to form a company
named Stardent Inc.
   Japan's Kubota Ltd., which owns 44 percent of Ardent, will own 22
percent of the combined companies and eventually will take over all
manufacturing as well as Far East distribution of the consolidated
product line, the companies said Wednesday.
   The privately owned companies make single-user computers that
sell for close to $100,000 and are used by scientists and engineers
for complex jobs such as modeling the way air flows over turbine
blades in a jet engine.
   Both Newton, Mass.-based Stellar and Sunnyvale, Calif.-based
Ardent were founded in late 1985, started shipping machines about a
year ago and have not yet reached profitability.
   J. William Poduska, Stellar's founder and chairman, predicted the
combined company would attain profitability by the end of 1990 and
reach revenue of at least $100 million, twice what the two companies
will gross this year.
   Poduska will serve as co-chief executive of Stardent with Allen
H. Michels, Ardent's chairman and chief executive. Eventually the
companies plan to select a single chief executive and headquarters.
   The companies will merge their product lines by early 1991.
Poduska said software written for the old machines would run on the
new ones with a minimum of reworking. In addition, he said, the new
company will broaden its product line to range from machines costing
$15,000 or $20,000 to ones costing $200,000.
   The combination is a straight merger, so no money is changing
hands.
   ``We have a marriage of two equals that is really something to
watch out for,'' Poduska said in an interview.
   Word of the planned merger circulated on Tuesday. The deal is
subject to a definitive agreement and requires the approval of
shareholders and the government.
</TEXT>
