<FIRST>r f PM-Israel-ElAl     08-31 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-El Al,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israel to Sell Shares in National Airline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel's government-owned national airline, El
Al, will be sold to local and foreign investors in a three-stage
plan that will take at least a year, the government said.
   The sale is part of a privatization program aimed at raising
needed capital and streamlining the government's bloated bureaucracy.
   The plans to sell stock in El Al were announced Wednesday by
Finance Minister Shimon Peres. The government hopes the move will
help inject new vitality in an economy that faces 10 percent
unemployment, the highest level in 20 years.
   El Al spokesman Nahman Kleiman said the government set up a
steering committee Friday to evaluate the airline's worth. He said
stocks representing 25 percent of the airline's value will be sold
on the Tel Aviv stock exchange and through employee's committees in
a few weeks.
   He said another 25 percent will be sold on foreign stock
exchanges about a year after the first shares are sold in Israel.
   ``Peres has no objections to selling the rest of El Al in the
third stage but we will first see what happens in the first two
stages,'' Kleiman said.
   El Al, which has been in receivership for the last eight years,
had a profit of $18.8 million last year.
   The company has an estimated value of $400 million and $800
million. It has 3,000 employees and flies to 34 destinations
worldwide.
</TEXT>
