<FIRST>r f PM-NymexChanges     08-31 0119</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nymex Changes,0124</SECOND>
<HEAD>New York Mercantile Exchange Tightens Fraud Rules</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The New York Mercantile Exchange, which handles
futures trading in crude oil, petroleum products and precious
metals, says it will raise its maximum fine for members' offenses to
$250,000.
   The current maximum fine for violations is $100,000.
   The exchange also said Wednesday it was making suspension
mandatory for anyone found to have engaged in fraud or deceit in
connection with a customer order.
   The changes will be submitted to the Commodity Futures Trading
Commission for approval.
   The hearing panel that serves as a grand jury on suspected rule
violations will have permanent memberships instead of being formed
on a case-by-case basis, the exchange said.
