<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-89 0237EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Exxon-Environmentalist Bjt   08-31 0639</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Exxon-Environmentalist, Bjt,0666</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exxon Appoints Environmentalist To Board</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA C. MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The scientist appointed to help oversee Exxon
Corp.'s future environmental policies and practices calls the Alaska
oil spill a ``terrible disaster.''
   John H. Steele on Wednesday was named a director of the nation's
largest oil company. The appointment follows Exxon's promise earlier
this year to large shareholders to appoint a director with interest
and expertise in the environment in the wake of the company's Alaska
oil spill.
   Major shareholders and some environmentalists said they approved
of the marine scientist. But other environmental groups were not
pleased by the choice.
   Steele, 62, is president of and a senior scientist at the Woods
Hole Oceanographic Institution in Massachusetts. In addition to his
seat on the board of directors he will serve on the board's newly
formed public issues committee, which monitors the company's
environmental policies.
   ``I'm confident his presence on the board will increase Exxon's
sensitivity to environmental concerns,'' said Gray Davis, controller
of the California Public Employee Retirement System, the largest
individual U.S. public pension fund, which owns Exxon stock.
   ``Protecting the environment is both good public policy and good
business,'' said Davis, who is also co-chairman of the Washington,
D.C.-based Council of Institutional Investors.
   The California pension fund was one of several funds with large
holdings of Exxon stock that publicized its dissatisfaction with
Exxon's handling of the March 24 spill and cleanup.
   The trustee for New York City's employee, firefighter and police
pension funds also praised Steele's appointment.
   ``The election of Dr. John H. Steele ... demonstrates
environmental and social responsibility,'' said city Comptroller
Harrison J. Goldin.
   However, the Environmental Policy Institute, which includes
Friends of the Earth and the Oceanic Society, issued a statement
that criticized Steele's appointment.
   ``The fact that John Steele has been obscure within the American
environmental movement speaks yet another volume as to Exxon's crude
insensitivity toward the environment,'' the statement said.
   Steele's appointment increases the size of Exxon's board to 15
members.
   In a telephone interview from his office at Woods Hole, Mass.,
about 70 miles south of Boston on the southeast end of Cape Cod,
Steele spoke of the spill.
   ``I think it's a terrible tragedy and a major disaster not just
for the animals but for the people in Alaska,'' Steele said.
   He declined to comment on Exxon's handling of the cleanup but
said he would visit Alaska in about two weeks for a separate
scientific meeting on arctic research and would view the remnants of
the spill.
   ``It will give me an opportunity to discuss these research and
scientific questions with colleagues in Alaska,'' he said.
   Steele will serve on the board until Exxon's annual shareholder's
meeting in April, when his name will be submitted for shareholder
approval along with the other directors, said Exxon spokesman Bill
Smith.
   Born in Edinburgh, Scotland, Steele's career includes 26 years at
the Marine Laboratory at Aberdeen, Scotland. He joined Woods Hole
Oceanographic Institution in 1977.
   Steele's principal research subject is the marine environment. He
is the U.S. delegate to the International Council for Exploration of
the Sea.
   Smith said Steele was elected by Exxon's board from among 100
names submitted for review.
   At the company's annual meeting in May, shareholders demanded
changes in what they called Exxon's ``inadequate state of
preparedness'' for dealing with future environmental problems.
   Although the pension funds ultimately voted for management this
year, they warned of a major shareholder revolt next year if the
Exxon appointment was unsatisfactory to dissident shareholders.
   At the May meeting, Exxon management agreed to create the
six-member public issues committee, which includes four non-Exxon
employees. Exxon said the committee would review the corporation's
``policies, programs and practices on public issues of significance
including their effects on the environment and worker safety and
health.''
</TEXT>
