<FIRST>r f PM-DetroitNewspapers     08-31 0181</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Detroit Newspapers,0188</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Sets JOA Arguments Oct. 30</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Supreme Court says it will hear arguments
in two months on whether The Detroit News and Detroit Free Press
should be allowed to merge some operations to cut costs.
   The court said Wednesday it will hear an hour of arguments at 2
p.m. Oct. 30.
   The Free Press, owned by Knight-Ridder Inc., and the News, owned
by Gannett Co. Inc., have sought since May 1986 to merge business
operations such as advertising, production and circulation to cut
costs, while keeping news and editorial operations separate.
   The newspapers said the Free Press will fail if the joint
operating agreement isn't granted under the federal Newspaper
Preservation Act.
   Former U.S. Attorney General Edwin Meese III approved the limited
antitrust exemption Aug. 8, 1988.
   But Michigan Citizens for an Independent Press is challenging
Meese's ruling, contending the newspapers have failed to prove the
Free Press is in danger of failing, and saying a JOA would give the
nation's two largest newspaper chains unfair control of the Detroit
market.
</TEXT>
