<DOCNO> AP890831-0238 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-89 1001EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-DeereLeader     08-31 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Deere Leader,0515</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deere Announces New Chief Executive Officer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOLINE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deere &amp; Co. Chairman Robert A. Hanson has
given up his title as chief executive officer after directing Deere
through its darkest days and into an era of record profits.
   Hanson, 64, relinquished the company's reins Wednesday to Hans W.
Becherer, currently president of Deere, the world leader in tractor
and agricultural-implement manufacturing.
   ``The action ... is reflective of the commitment by Deere &amp; Co.'s
board of directors to an orderly and effective management succession
plan,'' Hanson said in a news release.
   ``This new appointment indicates the board's confidence in his
ability to continue to exercise the kind of effective leadership
that will help ensure Deere &amp; Co.'s progress in the years ahead,''
said Hanson, who retains his title as chairman.
   Deere spokesman Robert Combs said no firm date has been
established for Hanson's retirement, although company policy
mandates he step down in 15 months on his 66th birthday in December
1990.
   ``Mr. Hanson will remain very active in leading the company up
until his retirement,'' Combs said.
   The choice of Becherer as heir-apparent signals the end of a
remarkable near 40-year tenure which saw Hanson take control in 1982
as the company stood on the brink of collapse.
   Deere accumulated $328 million in losses in two years, and its
operating losses totaled $637 million in the six-year period 1982-87.
   Hanson orchestrated a brutal cost-cutting program and laided off
about 12,000 workers as the farm crisis gripped the Midwest and
caused thousands of farm foreclosures nationwide.
   The problems were compounded by a 163-day work stoppage at 13
Deere plants in Illinois, Iowa and four other states that ended Feb.
1, 1987, when workers accepted a wage freeze.
   Since then, Hanson has led the 152-year-old company to its
highest profit levels ever. Aided by a diversification plan that saw
Deere enter insurance, consumer credit, mail-order catalogue and
health maintenance fields, the company has flourished.
   In 1988, Deere earned $315.4 million on sales of $5.3 billion
despite a crippling drought that cut corn and soybean yields in half
in key states like Illinois and Iowa. Profits and sales again are on
a record pace nine months into the 1989 fiscal year.
   Hanson, an East Moline native, was the first person not a member
of the Deere family by blood or marriage to run the company. But
he's the ultimate company man.
   Raised a few miles from the corporate headquarters, Hanson's
father was a middle-level manager at a Deere foundry.
   Hanson joined Deere in 1950 and rose through the ranks until
attaining a seat on the board of directors in 1974. He was named
president in 1978 and achieved the post of chief operating officer
in 1979.
   Becherer, 54, joined Deere in 1962 and followed a course to the
top similar to Hanson's in marketing and extensive overseas work. He
joined the board of directors in 1986 and was elected president and
chief operating officer in 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
