<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-89 1035EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Anti-lockBrakes     08-31 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Anti-lock Brakes,0390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Allstate Insurance Introduces Discount for Anti-lock Brake Systems</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES J. GANS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drivers of cars equipped with anti-lock brakes
could soon be getting a break on their auto insurance rates.
   In a move that could set a precedent for other major insurance
companies, Allstate Insurance Co. announced Wednesday it is offering
a 10 percent discount on three major auto-policy coverages for cars
with anti-lock brakes.
   ``This discount, in effect, is the first of its kind for a major
carrier,'' said Greg Rossiter, a spokesman for the company, based in
the Chicago suburb of Northbrook.
   The only other U.S. insurance company currently offering an
anti-lock brake system discount is USAA, of San Antonio, Texas, a
firm which provides insurance to military personnel and their
dependents, Rossiter said.
   Anti-lock brakes use an on-board computer to control wheel speed
during braking, allowing faster and safer stops without skidding or
loss of steering control.
   ``There's no question that the anti-lock brake system provides a
remarkable amount of braking protection that is not available in
regular brake systems,'' Rossiter said.
   William Geen, senior vice-president of CCC Information Services
Inc., a Chicago-based firm that evaluates car losses for the
insurance industry, said he also has found that anti-lock brakes are
effective.
   ``It's certainly been proven that the anti-lock brake system
works very well and more manufacturers are offering it.''
   Geen said he expected other insurance companies to follow
Allstate's example in offering the anti-lock brake discount.
   Geen said there are few cars on the road with anti-lock brakes,
but they should be available as an optional or standard feature on
more 1990 model cars.
   The anti-lock system was introduced about six years ago, and
until recently has only been available on luxury cars. It is now
being offered as an option on more moderately priced autos, but no
statistics are available as to how many cars now on the road in the
United States have anti-lock brakes, Rossiter said.
   The new discount offered by Allstate, a subsidiary of Sears
Roebuck &amp; Co., covers cars equipped with four-wheel anti-lock brake
systems. It provides for 10 percent off three coverages that are
part of an auto policy _ bodily injury, property damage liability
and collision.
</TEXT>
