<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0332</SECOND>
<HEAD>Most Crop Futures Advance On Frost Fears</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The soybean market led most grain futures prices
higher this morning on the Chicago Board of Trade on fears of an
early frost late next week in the Midwest.
   Concerns about the possibility of an early freeze have been
building as the corn and soybean harvest season approaches. At least
one private weather forecasting firm, Weather Services Corp. of
Bedford, Mass., has rated the chances of an early frost as better
than normal.
   Corn futures prices were up slighty on firm cash markets and
hopes for new export sales.
   ``It feels like there's some business in here, maybe the East
German stuff that was talked about earlier in the week,'' said Dale
Gustafson, a grain market analyst in Chicago with Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc.
   The wheat market was nearly unchanged amid indications that an
expected sale of 400,000 metric tons of U.S. wheat to Egypt has gone
through.
   In early trading, wheat was } cent lower to \ cent higher with
the contract for delivery in September at $3.86 a bushel; corn was \
cent to 1 cent higher with September at $2.32} a bushel; oats were
unchanged to { cent higher with September at $1.33 a bushel;
soybeans were 4 cents to 6\ cents higher with September at $5.85{ a
bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures prices were mixed in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .25 cent lower to .23 cent higher with September
at 72.25 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .40 cent
higher with August at 83.55 cents a pound; hogs were .10 cent to .25
cent higher with October at 40.60 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .20 cent lower to .43 cent higher with February at 43.10 cents
a pound.
   Livestock futures settled lower on Wednesday while pork bellies
were mostly higher.
