<FIRST>u f PM-BenzeneRules 1stLdWritethru   08-31 0808</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Benzene Rules, 1st Ld Writethru,0830</SECOND>
<HEAD>For Release at 1 p.m. EDT _ set by source.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Environmental Protection Agency Clamping Down on Emissions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 8 grafs update with announcement; picks up at pvs 4th graf,
According to</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government clamped tighter controls
today on the industrial handling and use of the cancer-causing
chemical benzene, saying the new requirements will cut releases of
the toxic chemical into the air by 90 percent.
   The regulations, some of which will take effect immediately and
others within six months, would cut benzene emissions into the air
by more than 34,000 tons yearly, according to the Environmental
Protecton Agency.
   ``Today's rules and proposals will lower the industrial
emmissions of benzene by 90 percent,'' F. Henry Habicht, the EPA's
deputy administrator, said in the announcement.
   The EPA estimated the new requirements, some of which will be
phased in over two years, will reduce the risk of the general
population of getting cancer as a result of benzene exposure to less
than one chance in 1 million.
   But the agency acknowledged the risk could be much higher _
perhaps one in 10,000 _ near some industrial plants where large
amounts of benzene are found.
   The new controls come 12 years after the EPA first listed
benzene, a colorless, odorless liquid widely found in the chemical,
steelmaking and petroleum industries, as a hazardous air pollutant.
   The sharpest emission cuts are expected to be seen in the steel
industry where benzene has long been a chief byproduct with few
controls on releases into the air, the EPA said. The new rules cut
those emissions by 97 percent, officials said.
   Sizable emission reductions also are expected in the
transportation of benzene, in the pharmaceutical industry and in the
transportation of gasoline from refineries to local service
stations, the agency said.
   According to one EPA official, as many as 100 million people
across the country are exposed to some level of benzene pollution.
Releases into the air can be found anywhere from steel mills and
refineries to the corner service station.
   In addition to cancer, federal authorities concluded in the 1970s
that chronic exposure to benzene also causes leukemia and birth
defects and damages blood-forming organs.
   Details of the new benzene controls weren't disclosed in advance,
but they are considered by the EPA to be among the most costly
issued so far in curbing toxic emissions.
   Initial capital investment costs are expected to exceed $1
billion over the next two years. There was no immediate estimate on
what additional operational costs companies might face.
   ``We think this is an expensive standard. We think it's worth
it,'' said Gerald Emison, director of the EPA's office of air
quality planning.
   In 1987, industry users reported more than 32 million pounds of
benzene was released into the air, but environmentalists say that
doesn't count additional releases by small companies and other
facilities _ such as gasoline stations _ that were not required to
make emission reports.
   Benzene is only the seventh toxic chemical to be regulated by the
EPA, which has been under criticism from Congress for not moving
more quickly to curb releases of such substances from the nation's
plants and factories.
   There are more than 300 toxic chemicals for which industry must
make annual reports of releases.
   EPA officials have acknowledged that the task of developing
comprehensive emission controls for benzene has taken too long, but
blame much of the delay on the complex legal process they have been
forced to follow.
   As part of its planned tightening of federal air pollution laws,
Congress is considering a revamping of how the EPA deals with toxic
chemicals, so the agency can issue broad regulations based on
installation of technology that would curb emissions of many
chemicals at the same time.
   The agency now must deal with each chemical separately _ as it
has with benzene.
   Although some benzene releases are already controlled by either
federal or state regulations, the vast majority of the releases are
not.
   The EPA, for example, says that the largest single source of
benzene releases into the air stem from the production of coke in
the iron and steel industry. Yet those releases have remained
largely uncontrolled until now, according to the EPA.
   Significant releases also continue to occur in the transportation
of benzene, as well as during the transfer of gasoline from
refineries to retail service stations. Controls on releases in those
areas are largely nonexistent, officials said.
   Federal controls have been in effect curbing benzene emissions
from certain industrial equipment since 1984, but those controls
cover only about 5 percent of all industrial releases of the
chemical.
   The Occupational Safety and Health Administration began
regulating benzene releases in the workplace in 1987, but that
doesn't cover emissions outside the immediate work environment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890831-0248 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-89 1333EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f PM-BusinessMirror Adv01   08-31 0599</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 01,0618</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv01</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Friday, Sept. 1</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Deficit That Would Not Die</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: John Cunniff is on vacation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It may not make your day to hear this, but the
federal budget deficit will soon be back making news.
   Congress returns to session after Labor Day facing a deadline
just a few weeks away to shrink, somehow, the projected gap between
income and outgo for the government fiscal year that begins Oct. 1.
   If it doesn't succeed, then the law known as
Gramm-Rudman-Hollings calls for automatic cuts in spending to bring
the deficit down within specified limits.
   ``The stage is set for intense negotiations over the budget in
the coming weeks,'' says Susan Simon, political analyst for the
investment firm of Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   Unless something is done, President Bush's budget staff says, the
government will stand to run $116 billion, give or take a few
hundred million, in the red for fiscal 1990.
   That's $16 billion more than mandated by Gramm-Rudman-Hollings,
but a conservative estimate by comparison to others, who have
projected deficits as large as $140 billion.
   It seems safe to assume that this will bring a lot of the usual
scenes that have become so familiar in the 1980s _ wrangling between
the administration and the lawmakers, late-night maneuvering and
some sort of last-minute compromise that will keep the government
lurching along.
   Lots of people will pay no attention, and why should they? The
debate over the deficit has been going on since the Nixon
administration at least, and the situation never seems to change
much.
   Besides, whatever is done this fall, the underlying problem won't
go away. ``Any budget pain encountered in getting under the
Gramm-Rudman ceiling for 1990 will be dwarfed by the `agony' coming
down the track for 1991,'' observes the United &amp; Babson Investment
Report, a Boston-based newsletter.
   In that fiscal year, Gramm-Rudman calls for a deficit limit of
$64 billion.
   Some people trace the origins of the much-bewailed ``breakdown of
the budget process'' to the mid-1960s, when the nation was faced
with a choice of how to spend its large, but still finite, resources.
   Should it build up its expensive role in the Vietnam war, or
should it embark on a sweeping campaign to deal with domestic
problems? Guns AND butter, decided President Lyndon Johnson.
   The deficit widened with the recessions and oil crises of the
1970s, and got still worse during the ``Reagan revolution'' of the
'80s.
   Along the way, Americans have taken part in a long experiment
determining what happens to their economy in a period of chronic
deficits.
   It turns out that policy measures taken in response to a deficit
can cause severe economic slumps, runaway booms, or long periods of
mere muddling through. They can foster rising inflation or declining
inflation, higher interest rates or lower interest rates.
   In short, under the deficits of the past two decades, the nation
has witnessed just about every conceivable economic environment _
except for the kind of calamity so many analysts of the problem have
predicted.
   Logic still dictates that the government cannot go on
indefinitely spending more than it takes in. Experience has shown
that it could in fact do just that for longer than many experts
thought possible.
   Blamed for everything from the stock market of crash of 1987 to a
decline in family values, the deficit persists. Having survived this
far, it seems ready to take on the 1990s with plenty of energy left.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Friday Sept. 1</NOTE>
</DOC>
