<DOCNO> AP890831-0250 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-89 1354EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-BAT     08-31 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-BAT,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>BAT Takeover Could Fail, Goldsmith Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sir James Goldsmith, one of the three financiers
leading the hostile takeover bid for BAT Industries PLC, said
Thursday a British regulatory panel must extend its deadline or his
takeover attempt will fail.
   Britain's Panel on Takeovers and Mergers requires that all
conditions of a bid, including U.S. regulatory hurdles, must be
completed within 81 days of the posting of the bidder's formal offer
document.
   ``If there is no extension from the panel it's very hard to see
the offer succeeding,'' Goldsmith said.
   Goldsmith's consortium, Hoylake Investments Ltd., posted its 13.4
billion pound, or $21.4 billion, bid for BAT and its U.S.
subsidiaries on Aug. 8, which leaves the group 58 days to meet U.S.
regulatory requirements.
   London-based BAT, the world's largest tobacco company, has
significant interests in financial services, paper and retailing _
including such U.S. holdings as the Saks Fifth Avenue and Marshall
Field department stores and Farmers Insurance Group.
   Goldsmith on Thursday also launched an attack on regulatory
commissions in several U.S. states ``for obstructing the bid.''
   ``The (state) regulators have got to ask themselves whether they
are going to be a poison pill or are going to allow free trade,'' he
said.
   Goldsmith is joined by British banker Jacob Rothschild and
Australian investor Kerry Packer in leading the BAT takeover bid,
Europe's largest to date.
   The British takeover panel said a decision on the extension
request would be made in the next few weeks.
   BAT shares were down 14 pence, or around 22 cents, at 823 pence,
or $13.10, a share on the London Stock Exchange following
Goldsmith's remarks.
   Hoylake is offering 878 pence, or $14.10, a share for BAT.
</TEXT>
