<HEAD>Dollar Up, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: An AMs version planned by 5:30 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose slightly in directionless
European trading Thursday, while gold prices fell.
   Dealers said they avoided taking large positions on the last day
of the month and before Friday's release of U.S. unemployment data
for July, which could give further clues to U.S. economic growth.
   ``There were no sharp moves today,'' said a dealer at a U.S.
bank. ``We remain stuck in a range ahead of the jobs data.''
   Volume was thin with many corporate traders absent from the
market.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 1.20 yen to a closing 144.28 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted higher at 144.55 yen.
   In London, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost
$1.5735 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.5815 late Wednesday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with Wednesday:
1.9580 West German marks, up from 1.9465; 1.6880 Swiss francs, up
from 1.6770; 2.2090 Dutch guilders, up from 2.183; 6.6035 French
francs, up from 6.5515; 1.1758 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1760; and
1,406.90 Italian lire, up from 1,389.50.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid price of $359.95 a troy ounce,
compared with late Wednesday's $360.75.
   In Zurich, gold was lower, closing at a bid $360.00 an ounce,
compared with $361.80 late Wednesday.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold fell $2.33 to close at a bid $360.04
an ounce.
   Silver prices fell in London to a late bid price of $5.09 a troy
ounce from $5.11 Wednesday.
