<HEAD>London Shares End Higher</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with later activity, closing indices;
No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices ended higher but below the day's peaks
Thursday on the London Stock Exchange as the market drifted in
tentative trading.
   Stocks opened stronger and then rallied on unconfirmed rumors
that a U.S. corporate finance specialist was considering taking a
large stake in the British company United Biscuits PLC.
   However, buying interest wilted at higher levels, encouraging
several players to take profits, analysts said. A lackluster opening
on Wall Street provided little incentive for the London market to
push higher, they said.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index ended up 6.6
points, or 0.2 percent, at 2,387.9, but below the day's high of
2,394.3, up 13 points. At its lowest, the index touched 2,384.6.
   Volume was a healthy 447 million shares at mid-afternoon, up from
414 million traded by the same time on Wednesday.
   Traders believe that in the next few weeks the key 100-share
index will be hard pressed to breach the psychologically important
2,400-point level.
   Dealers said the market is cautious ahead of an upcoming series
of interim company earnings reports, which might confirm fears of a
slowdown in British corporate profitability.
   ``This market's been driven by speculative stories and so no one
wants to be reminded of the fundamentals,'' one dealer said.
   The narrower Financial Times 30-share index ended up 6.7 points
at 1,977.6. The 500-share index was at 1,334.52, up 5.07.
   Around the close of trading in London, the Dow Jones average of
30 industrials was up 0.38 point at 2,728.53.
