<FIRST>u f BC-ZZZZBest     08-31 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-ZZZZ Best,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>ZZZZ Best Insider Must Pay $900,000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former ZZZZ Best Co. official was ordered to
repay $224,861 in illegal profits and interest from the fraudulent
rug-shampooing company and to pay triple damages of $674,582.
   Jack N. Polevoi of Woodland Hills, Calif., a former ZZZZ Best
vice president, is serving an 18-month prison sentence after
pleading guilty in June to four counts of stock and tax fraud and
other violations.
   The order for Polevoi to pay the nearly $900,000 came Wednesday
from U.S. District Judge Robert J. Kelleher. It was based on
findings that in mid-1987 Polevoi and his twin brother Jerry ordered
54,200 shares of ZZZZ Best to be sold short.
   Polevoi knew at the time that ZZZZ Best's founder and chairman,
Barry M. Minkow, was considering resigning from the Reseda,
Calif.-based company, which was crumbling.
   When investors sell stock short, they seek to profit from a
decline in the stock price by selling borrowed shares and buying
them back later. ZZZZ Best shares fell from more than $5 each at the
time the short sales were made to 75 cents when Polevoi completed
the transactions.
   Polevoi and others also laundered $712,000 in ZZZZ Best corporate
funds and bank loans through Las Vegas casinos in the days before
the company collapsed.
   Minkow, who convinced Wall Street and the public that he was a
teen-age business genius, was convicted of 57 counts of fraud,
conspiracy and other violations after investigators discovered that
much of the work supposedly done by ZZZZ Best existed only on paper.
   Minkow is serving a 25-year prison term and has been ordered to
repay $26 million in illegal profits and restitution.
</TEXT>
