<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-89 1530EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Saab     08-31 0540</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Saab,0557</SECOND>
<HEAD>Saab-Scania In Crisis But Refuses Clarify on Ford Bid Rumors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DICK SODERLUND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Swedish automaker Saab-Scania AB, facing
mounting losses and lay-offs, refused Thursday to confirm or deny
news reports that Ford Motor Co. is a leading suitor for its ailing
passenger car division.
   Following a board meeting Thursday, Jan-Erik Larsson, head of
Saab's auto division, declined to clarify a report in the Stockholm
tabloid Expressen that a takeover deal with Ford was imminent.
   It has been rumored for several months that Saab is seeking a
buyer to help salvage its crisis-ridden passenger car division and
to enable it to develop a successor to its stock 900 model by 1992.
   The 900 model, in recent years has run into hard times on the
vital U.S. market. When it was developed, Saab managed to halve the
costs by collaborating with Italian auto giant Fiat-Lancia.
   This time Saab reportedly first turned to Japan'e Mazda, which is
one-fourth-owned by Ford, and then turned to Ford itself.
   According to the Expressen report, top-level negotiations with
Ford are nearing their conclusion. The paper reported that Ford, the
second-largest U.S. automaker after General Motors Co., demanded a
majority share of Saab, but other sources said the Swedish company
is only willing to relinquish 20 percent to 40 percent of its stock.
   Lin Cummins, a Ford spokeswoman in Dearborn, Mich., said, ``We
can neither confirm nor deny the report.''
   Larsson in a television interview Thursday night said Saab-Scania
``will remain a Swedish automaking company,'' indicating a possible
refusal of a full take-over bid.
   SAAB president Georg Karnsund, who refused all comment Thursday,
earlier had said ``we will seek to make it on our own.''
   From Ford's viewpoint a take-over of Saab's profit-making truck
division could be a golden egg. Sweden's top automaker Volvo two
years ago purchased General Motors' heavy truck division. Ford sells
hardly any heavy trucks in Europe, where Saab's Scania truck
division markets 75 percent of its products, which are partly
produced in the Netherlands.
   Saab-Scania AB last year showed a record group profit of 3.2
billion kronor, about $484 million at current exchange rates, up 16
percent despite increasing losses in the passenger car division. In
addition to automotive and engine manufacturing, Saab makes
aircraft, weapons systems and electronic equipment.
   Larsson on Thursday refused to confirm that the passenger car
losses would mount to about one billion kronor for the first six
months of this year and hit two billion kronor for the full year.
However, he said losses would increase during the year from the 450
million kronor suffered in the first four months, which would
virtually halve Saab's profit for fiscal 1989.
   Larsson also said a tough crisis program, including a staff
reduction of about 2,000 employees, will not take effect until 1991
and admitted that the automaker is in for a couple of tough years
before it can hope to break even.
   According to Swedish business sources, the liquidity problem of
the Saab passenger car division, reportedly losing about $2,500 on
each car it produces due to high costs and setbacks on the dollar
market, is so severe it had to borrow from the parent company to
cover this months' wages.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
