<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   08-31 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybean Futures Rise On Freeze Fears</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices jumped about 10 cents a
bushel Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade amid fears that
freezing temperatures could strike maturing crops in the Midwest as
early as next week.
   Corn and oat futures also finished higher while the wheat market
was nearly unchanged.
   Some private meteorologists say the chance of an early freeze is
greater than usual this year, based on weather patterns that caused
Midwestern temperatures to drop to record lows earlier this month.
   Michael Palmerino, a senior agricultural meteorologist with
Weather Services Corp. in Bedford, Mass., said his firm sees a
1-in-3 chance of a significant freeze in the Midwest during
September, compared with the normal odds of 1 in 15.
   But Palmerino said meteorologists predicting a freeze next week
were likely using a forecasting model developed in Europe whereas
his firm uses a U.S. model that suggests rain followed by a warming
trend in the Midwest next week.
   Furthermore, he said, if a freeze were to occur in the Grain Belt
next week, ``it would probably affect only a very small portion of
the area,'' causing only marginal crop damage.
   At the close of trading, wheat was 1{ cents lower to 1{ cents
higher with the contract for delivery in September at $3.86 a
bushel; corn was 2} cents to 4 cents higher with September at $2.34{
a bushel; oats were 2{ cents to 4 cents higher with September at
$1.35 a bushel; soybeans were 3 cents to 10{ cents higher with
September at $5.88 a bushel.
</TEXT>
