<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market moved modestly higher today in
sluggish trading as a cautious mood prevailed ahead of sensitive
economic reports due Friday.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials managed to eke out a gain
after trading near its opening level throughout the day.
   Wall Street analysts say the market went into a holding pattern
before the Labor Department issues the August unemployment figures
which might provide additional evidence that the economy is strong
enough not to need the stimulation of lower interest rates.
   Also scheduled for release Friday are the August survey of
purchasing managers and the Commerce Department's index of leading
economic indicators.
   A report today that orders to U.S. factories sagged 1.7 percent
in July to the lowest level in eight months went largely ignored by
the market and some analysts said business probably perked up since
that month.
   Airline stocks were an exception to the sluggish activity in the
market.
   Several airline stocks plunged in response to a report that the
government may move to curb leveraged buyouts in the industry. The
Wall Street Journal reported that a high-ranking Transportation
Department official said in an interview that aviation regulators
are concerned about the takeover fever in the airline industry.
   One of the biggest losers in the airline sector was AMR, parent
of American Airlines, which tumbled 5 to 88 as more than 3.7 million
shares changed hands, making it the Big Board's most active issue.
The stock recently soared on speculation that it would be a takeover
target.
   Union Carbide, the second most heavily traded NYSE-listed stock,
rose 1] to 31[ on word that a securities analyst had upgraded his
earnings estimate for the company.
