<FIRST>r f AM-DisneyTaxes     08-31 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Disney Taxes,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Increase Sharply On Undeveloped Land</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KISSIMMEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Walt Disney World faces a 254 percent tax
increase on 10,175 undeveloped acres in Florida's Osceola County,
mostly because of a change in tax rules by the county appraiser.
   Osceola County Property Appraiser Bob Day removed a lucrative
agricultural classification on a large portion of Disney's property
that is suitable for development near Interstate 4 and U.S. Highway
192.
   Disney's Osceola tax notice, which arrived by mail this week,
shows taxes would rise from $395,000 in 1988 to more than $1.4
million this year.
   The property, with the exemption, was assessed at $26.9 million
in 1988. The same parcels were assessed at more than $84 million
this year.
   Like many cattle farmers and citrus growers who use the
agricultural exemption until it's time to sell or develop, Disney
had been using exemptions in state laws created by agricultural
interests in the late 1950s to reduce its property tax exposure.
   ``The taxpayers of this county have been subsidizing Disney and a
lot of speculators for too long,'' Day said Wednesday. ``It's only
fair. This land is best used for development, not farming.''
   Disney has until Sept. 18 to file for a hearing seeking to
reinstate the agricultural classification.
   ``We're still studying the situation,'' Disney spokesman Charles
Ridgway said. ``All we can say at this time is that we're looking at
it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
