<FIRST>u f AM-MoneyFunds     08-31 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Money Funds,0390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Money Funds Rose $53.7 Million in Latest Week</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Interest rate figures reported by Donoghue's Money Fund Report
are for week ended Tuesday. All other figures are for the week ended Wednesday.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the nation's 464 money market mutual
funds rose $53.7 million in the latest week to hit a new record of
$343.4 billion, the Investment Company Institute said Thursday.
   The rise in the seven-day period ended Wednesday marked the ninth
straight week for a new all-time high in fund assets and followed a
$2.68 billion increase in the assets the previous week, according to
the Washington-based mutual fund trade group.
   The previous record set the week ended Aug. 23 totaled $343.35
billion, revised slightly from the $343.22 billion originally
reported by the institute.
   The Investment Company Institute said that in the latest week,
assets of 227 general purpose funds rose $124.3 million to $109.91
billion, assets of 95 broker-dealer funds increased $310.3 million
to $148.16 billion, and assets of 142 institutional funds declined
$380.9 million to $85.33 billion.
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds fell in
the week ended Tuesday to 8.29 percent from 8.31 percent the
previous week, according to Donoghue's Money Fund Report, a trade
journal based in Holliston, Mass.
   The 30-day average yield fell to 8.32 percent from 8.38 percent,
Donoghue's said.
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was 38
days, down from 40 days, Donoghue's said.
   Separately, the newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of
100 leading commercial banks, savings and loan associations and
savings banks in the nation's 10 largest markets showed the
effective annual yield available on money market accounts rose to
6.46 percent as of Wednesday from 6.45 percent a week earlier.
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective
annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super NOW
accounts, was 5.11 percent, unchanged from a week earlier.
   Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield was 8.28
percent on six-month certificates of deposit, up from 8.25 percent
the previous week. Yields were 8.30 percent on 1-year CDs, up from
8.26 percent; 8.21 percent on 2{-year CDs, up from 8.19 percent; and
8.20 percent on 5-year CDs, up from 8.18 percent.
</TEXT>
