<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-89 2031EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-DairyDeficit     08-31 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dairy Deficit,0504</SECOND>
<HEAD>Northeast Shortage May Shake Up Milk Prices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Milk supplies are drying up in New
England, which means consumers probably will have to pay up to 20
cents more per gallon by the end of the year, dairy experts said
Thursday.
   ``It's good news for the dairy farmer because that means his
price is going up,'' said Richard Stammer, senior vice president of
economics and communications at Agri-Mark Inc., a cooperative of
about 2,200 dairy farmers in New England and New York.
   ``Milk is really short all the way from Boston out to Minnesota
and Wisconsin and clear down through the south,'' said James N.
Putnam II, director of research at the Farm Credit Banks of
Springfield.
   Agriculture officials said they don't anticipate a shortage of
milk in stores.
   ``There is milk around, but the cost is going to be increased
because they're going to have to go farther and farther west to get
the milk,'' said Charles Costa, assistant commissioner of the
Massachusetts Department of Food and Agriculture.
   Dairy farmer Jim Williams, who runs a herd of about 170 on his
Sunderland farm, said he hopes the shortage will translate into a
better price. ``I'm optimistic,'' he said.
   A few years ago, the nation appeared awash in a milk surplus with
the government installing price supports and giving away cheese in
bulk amounts. However, there was no overflow in Massachusetts, which
produces only about 25 percent of its fluid milk needs.
   Now, the surplus is gone, partly because of a 1986 ``whole herd
buyout,'' in which farmers sold their entire herds to the government
for slaughter and promised to stay out of the dairy business for
five years.
   Massachusetts imports much of its milk from Vermont and New York,
which are in the same situation of low production at a time when
consumption historically is high, Putnam said.
   Meanwhile, the number of dairy farms in Massachusetts has fallen
from about 770 in 1984 to about 450. The buyout program is estimated
to have reduced herds by 20 percent while rising land prices and
competition from large Midwest dairy farms also affected the state
industry, officials said.
   ``The main reason that we're in the current situation is that the
dairy farmers' prices pretty much constantly declined since 1983.
This has driven a lot of farmers out of business,'' Stammer said.
   ``Right now, market prices are bidding up the price,'' said
Clayton Plumb, chief of the order formulation division in the U.S.
Department of Agriculture's dairy division. ``It's something that
hasn't been the case since the late 1970s in terms of dairy prices
being market driven,'' he said.
   The shortage is being felt strongest in southern New England,
Plumb said.
   In Connecticut, Agriculture Commissioner Kenneth B. Andersen has
issued permits to bring 100,000 pounds of milk this week into his
state as schools order milk for returning children.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890831-0268 </DOCNO>
