<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     08-31 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0438</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Gold Down</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Precedes LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose sharply Thursday against all key
currencies, reaching a two-month high against the Japanese yen.
   Gold prices weakened. On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold
bullion for current delivery closed at $359.90 a troy ounce, off
$1.90 from late Wednesday. Republic National Bank of New York quoted
a late bid for gold of $358.60 an ounce, down $1.75.
   The market's general mood toward the dollar remained bullish
following a string of recent economic data pointing toward continued
growth. Dealers said they were awaiting Friday's release of July
unemployment report, and many are predicting the data will show
moderate growth in new jobs.
   Also helping the dollar Thursday were reports that the Pentagon
plans to send 200 American military personnel to Colombia to help
that government fight drug traffickers.
   ``Any time there's a conflict somewhere in the world it usually
benefits the dollar,'' said Gary Lutnick, a dealer at the New York
office of Banco di Sicilia.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 1.20 yen to a closing 144.28 yen. It was quoted in
London at 144.55 yen, and in New York at 145.065 yen, up from 144.25
yen.
   Dealers said the last tim the yen closed above the 145-yen level
was in June.
   The dollar gained against the British pound. It cost $1.5735 to
buy one pound in London, cheaper than $1.5815 late Wednesday.
Sterling fetched $1.5650 in New York, down from $1.57795.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Wednesday, included: 1.9675 West German marks, up from 1.9533;
1.7005 Swiss francs, up from 1.68325; 6.6290 French francs, up from
6.5775; 1.17935 Canadian dollars, up from 1.17695; and 1,411.00
Italian lire, up from 1,400.50.
   Late dollar rates in Europe, compared with Wednesday: 1.9580 West
German marks, up from 1.9465; 1.6880 Swiss francs, up from 1.6770;
2.2090 Dutch guilders, up from 2.183; 6.6035 French francs, up from
6.5515; 1.1758 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1760; and 1,406.90
Italian lire, up from 1,389.50.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid price of $359.95 an ounce from
Wednesday's $360.75. In Zurich, gold closed at $360 an ounce, down
from $361.80.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold fell $2.33 to close at $360.04 an
ounce.
   Silver prices declined. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for
current delivery fell to $5.045 a troy ounce from $5.085. In London
the late bid price was $5.09 an ounce, down from $5.11.
</TEXT>
