index of leading economic indicators.
   News Thursday that orders to U.S. factories sagged 1.7 percent in
July to the lowest level in eight months went largely ignored by
financial markets.
   High-flying airline stocks lost altitude in response to a report
that federal regulators soon may move to curb leveraged buyouts and
foreign investment in the industry.
   A high-ranking Transportation Department official said in an
interview with the Wall Street Journal that aviation regulators are
concerned about the takeover fever gripping the airline industry.
   One of the biggest losers in the airline sector was AMR, parent
of American Airlines, which plunged 5 to 88 as more than 3.7 million
shares changed hands, making it the Big Board's most active issue.
The stock recently soared on speculation that it would be a takeover
target.
   Delta dropped 4[ to 79~, Southwest Airlines slid 1] to 28~, UAL,
owner of United Airlines, fell \ to 279} and Texas Air, which owns
Continental and Eastern, tumbled 1[ to 20| on the American Stock
Exchange.
   Union Carbide, the second most heavily traded NYSE-listed stock,
rose 1] to 31[ on word that an earnings forecast for the company had
been raised.
   Ford rose ~ to 53~. Reports circulated that Ford might be
interested in acquiring the passenger car division of Sweden's
Saab-Scania AB. Jan-Erik Larsson, head of Saab's auto division,
declined to clarify a report in the Stockholm tabloid Expressen that
a takeover deal with Ford was imminent.
   Upjohn pulled back by 2 to 39[ after going up 2} Wednesday amid
speculation that the drug company could be the next takeover
candidate in the sector.
   Among retail issues, Gap gained 1\ to 52\ after reporting strong
August sales.
   Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 172.35 million shares.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market added $7.61 billion, or 0.22
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
0.36 to 195.27.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index went up 0.93 to 402.85, and
S&amp;P's 500-stock composite index closed at 351.45, up 0.80.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market added
1.06, finishing at 469.33. At the American Stock Exchange, the
market value index closed at 382.19, up 0.61.
   The close in the Dow Jones industrial average was second to the
record 2,743.36 level reached Monday.
