<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     08-31 0679</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0702</SECOND>
<HEAD>Copper Futures Up Sharply On Renewed Supply Fears</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Copper futures prices surged in late trading Thursday on New
York's Commodity Exchange on renewed supply jitters prompted by
plans for a strike at a mine in Chile, the world's largest copper
producer.
   On other markets, frost fears sent most grain and soybean futures
higher; pork belly futures rose sharply while livestock futures were
mixed; precious metals retreated; and energy futures advanced.
   Copper settled 2.95 cents to 3.35 cents higher with the contract
for delivery in September at $1.3195 a pound.
   Copper miners at the Chilean Copper Corp.'s El Salvador mine were
scheduled to walk out Friday, which would add a fourth major mine to
those shut down worldwide by strikes, bankruptcy or terrorism.
   Copper futures prices generally have been rising over the past
month in reaction to the industry's problems. The trend appeared to
have changed Tuesday when prices plunged on signs of weakening unity
among striking miners in Peru and some market analysts declared the
bull market all but over.
   Those assumptions may have been premature, despite reports that
leaders of Peru's mining union voted Wednesday to end their
18-day-old strike at midnight Thursday.
   A walkout at the El Salvador mine in Chile would halt a
production stream that produces 120,000 metric tons of refined
copper a year, less than 2 percent of the 7-million-ton global
output.
   The Bougainville mine in Papua New Guinea, a 180,000-ton-a-year
unit, has been closed due to terrorist attacks since late July;
Mexico's Cananea copper mine, with an annual output of 95,000 tons,
remains shut down while the government investigates alleged
improprieties that led to a bankruptcy declaration last week; and a
strike at the Highland Valley Copper Co.'s 170,000-ton-a-year
Highland Valley mine in British Columbia continued for a 57th day
Thursday.
   Talks aimed at ending the Highland Valley strike are scheduled to
resume Tuesday, but hopes for a settlement are fading.
   Soybean futures prices jumped as much as 10\ cents a bushel on
the Chicago Board of Trade amid fears that freezing temperatures
could strike maturing crops in the Midwest as early as next week.
   Michael Palmerino, a senior agricultural meteorologist with
Weather Services Corp. in Bedford, Mass., said his firm sees a
1-in-3 chance of a significant freeze in the Midwest during
September, compared to the normal odds of 1 in 15.
   Soybeans settled 4 cents to 10\ cents higher with September at
$5.88 a bushel; wheat was { cent lower to 1 cent higher with
September at $3.86 a bushel; corn was 2} cents to 4 cents higher
with September at $2.34{ a bushel; oats were 2{ cents to 3{ cents
higher with September at $1.35 a bushel;
   Frozen pork belly futures rose sharply on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange after Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter told reporters
that a possible package of U.S. food aid to Poland, including pork
bellies, was ``on the front burner.''
   Frozen pork belly futures settled .83 cent to 1.25 cents higher
with February at 44 cents a pound; live cattle were .70 cent lower
to .25 cent higher with September at 71.80 cents a pound; feeder
cattle were unchanged to .22 cent higher with August at 83.67 cents
a pound; live hogs were .30 cent lower to .28 cent higher with
October at 40.47 cents a pound.
   Gold and silver futures prices fell on the Commodity Exchange as
the dollar strengthened.
   Gold settled $1.90 to $2.40 lower with September at $359.90 a
troy ounce; silver was 4 cents to 4.5 cents lower with September at
$5.045 a troy ounce.
   Energy futures advanced on the New York Mercantile Exchange,
boosted by a weekly Deparment of Energy report showing substantial
drawdowns in U.S. supplies of gasoline and petroleum distillates.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled unchanged to 19 cents
higher with September at $18.22 a barrel; heating oil was .47 cent
to .71 cent higher with September at 53.82 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .02 cent lower to .44 cent higher with September at
54.98 cents a gallon.
</TEXT>
