<FIRST>u f AM-TupperwareCredits     08-31 0157</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tupperware Credits,0164</SECOND>
<HEAD>Now You Can Use Plastic To Buy Plastic</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KISSIMMEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's now possible to seal a deal with
Tupperware on credit.
   The maker of the famous air-tight food and beverage containers
now allows shoppers at Tupperware parties to make purchases using
Visa or Mastercard, the company announced.
   The decision was made after testing credit card purchases earlier
this year at several home and office ``parties,'' the only way to
buy Tupperware, said company spokeswoman Lawrie Pitcher Platt.
Tupperware has not been available in retail stores since 1951.
   Previously, guests at Tupperware parties could pay either by
check or cash before delivery.
   The Kissimmee-based company also announced Wednesday that it now
has more than 100,000 independent Tupperware dealers in the United
States.
   Platt said the credit card policy is part of recent modifications
in the party system to meet changing lifestyles, including parties
held in offices or in homes after work hours.
</TEXT>
