<DOCNO> AP890831-0275 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-89 1854EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Brazil-Bonds     08-31 0204</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Bonds,0213</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brazil Issues Bonds to Reduce Foreign Debt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government Thursday issued ``exit
bonds'' to reduce interest payments on its massive foreign debt by
$40 million a year.
   Marcelo Ceylao, a director at the Central Bank, Brazil's
equivalent of the U.S. Federal Reserve, said $1.5 billion worth of
the bonds were delivered simultaneously to financial markets in New
York and London for distribution Friday.
   The exit bonds will pay a fixed interest rate of 6 percent
annually over a 25-year period. They substitute credit titles on old
debt that were subject to the 9 percent Libor Rate on the London
interbank market.
   A Central Bank communique released Thursday said it was the first
time Brazil issued new bonds to foreign markets since 1982.
   Ceylao told reporters that despite the Libor rate's higher yield,
investors showed interest in swapping old debt for the certificates
because the bonds are guaranteed.
   The certificates of custody on the bonds can be traded in a
secondary market after 90 days, or converted into risk investments
in Brazil.
   Brazil, tottering under a foreign debt of $110 billion, the Third
World's largest, will pay $14.9 billion in interest payments this
year, the Central Bank estimates.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
