<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-89 2128EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-US-JapanVisit     08-31 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Japan Visit,0402</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Leader in Washington to Meet Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bush administration officials were beginning
trade and political talks Thursday with visiting Japanese Prime
Minister Toshiki Kaifu, who the day before rejected setting limits
on his nation's exports to the United States.
   The trip has been described as a get-acquainted visit for Kaifu,
58, who took office on Aug. 9 after a money-for-sex scandal that
toppled then-Prime Minister Sosuke Uno and contributed to a major
defeat for his Liberal Democratic Party in elections to the upper
house of parliament last month.
   A State Department official said President Bush was interrupting
his vacation in Kennebunkport, Maine, to meet with Kaifu in
Washington to ``stress the importance we attach to these talks and
our desire to move forward,'' especially on trade issues.
   ``This isn't just a handshake and a photo. They have a lot of
things to talk about,'' said the U.S. official, who spoke on
condition he not be further identified. ``They are going to talk
about bilateral trade and security issues, international questions,
what has been going in China, Cambodia and Korea and the Soviet
Union, and international debt.''
   Kaifu began his U.S. trip Wednesday in San Francisco, where he
told an impromptu news conference that controls on U.S.-Japan trade
would ``stifle the dynamism'' of the two nations.
   He said the aim of his visit was ``to make rock-solid the
relationship between Japan and the United States.''
   Asked to comment on Japan's $55 billion annual trade surplus with
the United States, Kaifu said: ``I plan to talk about this with the
president of the United States. We will be continuing the dialogue.''
   A senior Foreign Ministry official who briefed reporters in Tokyo
before the trip said Kaifu carried no major trade or diplomatic
initiatives.
   Kaifu was meeting Thursday with Secretary of State James A. Baker
III, and on Friday with Bush and congressional leaders.
   He planned to travel Saturday to Boston, Monday to Mexico City,
Wednesday to Ottawa and Friday to Vancouver, British Columbia.
   His visit to Washington falls a week before a U.S. delegation,
including Undersecretary of State for Economic and Agricultural
Affairs Richard T. McCormack, was to head to Tokyo for talks
designed in part to remove barriers to U.S. exports to Japan, said
the state department official.
</TEXT>
