<HEAD>Aloha Airlines Buying New Jets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Aloha Airlines is buying four new Boeing 737-300
jets and has options on four other jets to increase its fleet and
replace older aircraft, the company announced Thursday.
   A. Maurice Myers, Aloha president and chief executive officer,
said the $250 million deal confirms the airline's confidence in
sustained tourism growth in the 1990s.
   The first of the jets was expected to arrive in Hawaii in 1992.
   The 737-300 model carries 139 passengers. Aloha currently has two
737-300s in its 13-plane fleet.
   Myers said he expects Aloha's fleet to continue growing at the
rate of about one plane a year. He said the airline's oldest jets
would be retired as necessary when the new planes arrive.
   In April 1988, an aging Aloha 737 blew open at 24,000 feet on a
flight from Hilo to Honolulu. A flight attendant was swept to her
death. The plane landed on Maui Island missing the front third of
its passenger cabin roof.
