<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-89 2205EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-LIN-McCaw     08-31 0728</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-LIN-McCaw,0750</SECOND>
<HEAD>FCC Approves McCaw's Takeover Of Rival Cellular Phone Company</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission on
Thursday approved McCaw Cellular Communications Inc.'s $5.5 billion
hostile takeover of LIN Broadcasting Corp.
   The commission denied assertions by LIN, a New York-based
cellular telephone, broadcasting and publishing concern, that
McCaw's bid for transfer of control of LIN's telephone and
broadcasting licenses was not in the public interest and that McCaw
didn't have the money to make the deal.
   LIN also had argued that a hearing should be held to determine
whether British Telecom PLC held too much control of McCaw, the
world's largest non-wireline cellular telephone company, under laws
limiting foreign investment in U.S. broadcasting companies; that the
merger would be anticompetitive; that McCaw would be too indebted;
and that the merger would violate cable-television cross-ownership
rules.
   In addition, LIN challenged the character of John Malone, a McCaw
director who is president of the nation's largest cable TV operator,
Tele-Communications Inc. of Denver.
   The FCC said it appeared that Malone would not exert direct
control over the new company's television operations, but it
conditioned its approval on McCaw providing an exact description of
Malone's position and duties and assurances he will comply with the
cable-television cross-ownership restrictions.
   Overall, the FCC said ``no good reason has been shown for the
commission significantly to depart from its longstanding policy of
strict neutrality and hence minimal intervention into the
marketplace for corporate control.''
   LIN operates seven network-affiliated television stations and has
interests in cellular systems serving New York, Los Angeles,
Philadelphia, Dallas and Houston. It also owns a specialty
publishing house that produces hard-cover tourist guides for hotel
rooms.
   In May, LIN's board approved in principal spinning off all of the
stock in a new subsidiary that would own its TV stations. It said it
would operate its cellular operations along with the publishing
business as a separate company.
   Kirkland, Wash.-based McCaw made a $110-per-share cash offer for
all shares of LIN's stock in July, after first offering $120 a
share. LIN management is seeking $127.50 a share for its 53.9
million shares, or nearly $6.9 billion. McCaw already owns 5 million
shares of LIN stock.
   McCaw earlier this month extended its offer to Sept. 1.
   About 1.07 million LIN shares have been tendered, McCaw said
earlier this month.
   LIN said on July 31, its own deadline, that its board would
pursue other options.
   McCaw had asked the FCC that, in order to speed the merger, LIN's
licenses be transfered temporarily to a trustee representing its
wholly owned subsidiary, MMM Holdings Inc. But the commission said
Thursday it could rule on the full application for transfer
immediately.
   The commission said it generally does not consider debt or the
level of debt as a relevant consideration in license transfers.
   As for assertions by LIN that McCaw hasn't lined up the financing
necessary, the commission said McCaw had ``well in excess of the
amount needed to acquire LIN, with the balance more than adequate to
operate the (LIN) television stations for three months.''
   The commission said McCaw had $1 billion in cash from the recent
sale of stock to British Telecom, the British phone company; $1.3
billion in revolving credit; $2 billion from a credit line from a
bank syndicate headed by Morgan Guaranty; and up to $2.5 billion
from public or private equity or debt placements to be managed by
Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   The commission said British Telecom's 22 percent holdings in
McCaw were within the 25 percent limits for foreign investors. The
British government has a 48 percent ownership interest in British
Telecom PLC, the parent of British Telecom.
   The FCC also rejected LIN's request to look into possible
anticompetitive rule violations by BellSouth, the regional telephone
company, which would be partnered with McCaw in Los Angeles and
Houston through the merger, while competing with McCaw in other
areas.
   It also said no further action was warranted on LIN's assertions
that Malone was not qualified to hold licenses because of his
possible involvement in a cable franchise renewal proceeding in
Jefferson City, Mo., that resulted in a multimillion-dollar verdict
against TCI for antitrust violations.
   LIN's TV stations are: KXAS, Fort Worth-Dallas; WISH,
Indianapolis; WOTV, Battle Creek, Mich.; WAVY, Hampton Roads, Va.;
KXAN, Austin, Texas; WAND in central Illinois; and WANE, Fort Wayne,
Ind.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
