<DOCNO> AP890831-0279 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-89 2214EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-TimesPublisher     08-31 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Times Publisher,0381</SECOND>
<HEAD>L.A. Times Names David Laventhol Publisher, Chief Executive Officer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Times Mirror Corp. President David Laventhol
has been named publisher and chief executive officer of the Los
Angeles Times, the media company announced Thursday.
   Laventhol will replace W. Thomas Johnson Jr., who has been
publisher of the newspaper for nine years, Times Mirror said in a
statement.
   The announcement was made by Robert F. Erburu, chairman and chief
executive officer of Times Mirror, following Thursday's meeting of
the company's board of directors.
   The statement said that with Laventhol's appointment, Johnson
will ``assume new companywide responsibilities,'' including
chairmanship of the Times Mirror newspaper management committee, a
policymaking group that shapes the company's strategies in newspaper
publishing.
   ``To be publisher of the Los Angeles Times is to be at the center
of the most exciting journalistic enterprise in the country,''
Laventhol said after the announcement.
   ``I am happy to have this opportunity, and I'm grateful to Tom
Johnson for leading the Times through nine years of growth and
editorial excellence,'' he said. ``I look forward to working with
the men and women of the Times to produce an even better newspaper.''
   Laventhol, 55, has been president of Times Mirror since 1987 and
will continue in that position. Laventhol was editor of Newsday from
1970-78 and served as publisher of the daily on New York's Long
Island from 1978-87. Newsday is owned by Times-Mirror.
   Laventhol previously worked at the Washington Post.
   Johnson said he had been asked ``to assume broader
responsibilities beyond those I currently hold, a set of
opportunities to grow and to contribute to Times Mirror in other
important areas. I look forward to this new era of challenge.''
   Johnson, 47, will oversee joint marketing efforts of all Times
Mirror newspapers and the other media operations and will be
involved in acquisition of additional operations, the statement
said. He also will continue to serve as vice chairman of Times
Mirror.
   The Los Angeles Times has a circulation of 1.1 million daily and
1.4 million on Sundays.
   Times Mirror also publishes the Baltimore Sun, the Hartford
Courant, The Morning Call in Allentown, Pa., The Advocate of
Stamford, Conn. and the Greenwich (Ct.) Time.
</TEXT>
