<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0184</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Opens Higher, Stock Prices Also Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar opened higher against the Japanese
yen in early trading Friday, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange also gained.
   The dollar started trading at 144.95 yen, up 0.67 yen from
Thursday's close. It finished at 145.03 in New York overnight, up
0.80 yen from the previous day.
   Osamu Seto, a dealer at Mitsubishi Bank, said trust banks
purchased dollars soon after the market opened following a
dollar-buying trend in New York.
   However, rumors on the market that a major life insurance company
was waiting to sell a large amount of dollars exerted downward
pressure on the dollar, Seto said.
   He said dealers were also waiting the announcement of the U.S.
unemployment rate in August, due for release in Washington later
Friday. But their long-term position adjustments would have more of
an impact on the market than the jobless rate, he added.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Industrial Average rose 40.07 points, or
0.12 percent, to 34,471.27 shortly after the market opened.
