<FIRST>r f BC-GovernmentPhones     08-31 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Government Phones,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>SBA To Buy Data Network From US Sprint</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Small Business Administration has signed a
letter of intent for data network services to be provided through
the government's new FTS2000 long-distance network, US Sprint said
Thursday.
   Sprint said the SBA will be the first customer Sprint will
provide with new integrated voice and data services through FTS2000.
Sprint said the contract could be worth $7 million over 10 years.
   Sprint is providing 40 percent of FTS2000, while a team led by
the American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. will provide the other 60
percent. The General Services Administration says FTS2000 could be
worth as much as $10 billion to the companies that will provide
voice, video and computer data to more than 1,300 far-flung
government agencies.
   The SBA network will handle transactions the agency sends between
its 10 regional centers nationwide and more than 100 field offices,
Sprint said.
   Sprint said the SBA estimated the new system would save taxpayers
at least $300,000 over five years.
   AT&amp;T announced two weeks ago that the Department of Health and
Human Services' Health Care Financing Administration will be the
first agency to use AT&amp;T's portion of the new data network services.
AT&amp;T said the HFCA contract was worth $100 million.
   Existing switched voice communications at some federal agencies
will begin to be changed over to FTS2000 in October.
   AT&amp;T will serve such agencies as HHS, the Pentagon, the
Department of Agriculture and the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration. US Sprint will serve such agencies as the Department
of Veterans Affairs, the GSA and the Justice Department.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
